<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Fed Gives Wall Street Jitters </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- The stock market has been a little off-kilter  
ever since the Federal Reserve first warned it might raise interest 
rates in an effort to cool down the U.S. economy. 
</P>
<P>
	This past week, however, stocks just plunged. The Dow Jones  
industrial average, after gaining 109 points on Monday, lost 418.87 
points over the next four sessions. Broader market indicators also 
fell, although their losses didn't approach those of the blue 
chips. 
</P>
<P>
	The vague nervousness that had been causing market indexes to  
bob in a narrow range since the Fed's May 18 warning was replaced 
by one specific threat to the value of stocks: a 30-year Treasury 
bond yield that pierced 6 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	Stock prices tend to fall when interest rates go up. Higher  
rates mean higher corporate borrowing costs, cutting into profits, 
and they can also prompt consumers to cut back their spending. 
</P>
<P>
	But as rates climb, they might also draw investors away from the  
volatile price swings of stocks and toward the more stable, 
guaranteed returns that come with bonds. The higher their yield, 
the more favorable bonds appear. And analysts say 6 percent is a 
true, albeit largely psychological, benchmark. 
</P>
<P>
	``The penetration of that 6 percent level is sacrosanct to some  
investors,'' said Ned Riley, chief investment officer at 
BankBoston. 
</P>
<P>
	Why 6 percent? Investors love a round number. Just as market  
watchers have eagerly awaited each new 1,000-point milestone of the 
Dow, awarding special significance to 10,000, a bond yield of 6 
percent turns heads. 
</P>
<P>
	Just last October, the 30-year bond yield hit 5 percent as the  
Fed cut interest rates, hoping to save the global economy from a 
widespread currency crisis that decimated Asian markets and 
threatened U.S. financial markets. That, too, was dubbed a 
psychological barrier. 
</P>
<P>
	The current climate could be a boon for bond buyers, said Don  
Hays, chief investment strategist at Wheat First Union. 
</P>
<P>
	``We think that the recent rise in long-bond (30-year) yields is  
giving investors an outstanding opportunity to nail down very 
attractive yields -- with very low risk,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Risk is a crucial factor to investors weighing whether to put  
their money in stocks or bonds. Volatility anywhere in the economy, 
whether measured by political change, shifting economic policy, or 
major corporate news, can sway a stock investor toward more 
conservative investments like bonds. 
</P>
<P>
	``As short-term interest rates rise, you're getting paid a  
little more to be cautious,'' said David Orr, chief economist at 
First Union Capital Markets Group in Charlotte, N.C. 
</P>
<P>
	Orr said higher bond yields can appear especially alluring to  
investors in growth stocks, which include the pricey, often 
volatile technology companies. Those investments become less 
appealing once increased interest rates start chipping away at 
earnings. 
</P>
<P>
	But some analysts say the current investment climate has room  
for both stocks and bonds. 
</P>
<P>
	``I see 6 percent bonds as no impediment to future rising prices  
of stocks,'' said Joseph V. Battipaglia, chief investment 
strategist at Gruntal &AMP; Co. Battipaglia said that if second-quarter 
earnings are as strong as anticipated, the equities market will 
bear up regardless of the Fed's decision on interest rates. 
</P>
<P>
	``You could make a case that stocks will go nowhere,'' agreed  
David M. Jones, chief economist at Aubrey G. Lanston &AMP; Co., a 
government bond dealer. ``Higher and more attractive interest rates 
are holding stocks down, but good profits could pull them right 
back up.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In Friday's trading, the Dow fell 130.76 to close at 10,490.51,  
finishing down 309.33 points for the week. 
</P>
<P>
	The Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 composite fell 9.18 to 1,293.64, and  
finished down 34.11 for the week. The Nasdaq composite declined 
36.74 to 2,447.88 Friday, losing 30.46 for the week. 
</P>
<P>
	The NYSE composite index fell 3.35 to 619.50 Friday, losing  
15.02 for the week. The American Stock Exchange composite index 
fell 2.43 to 765.82 Friday, and was down 15.16 for the week. 
</P>
<P>
	The Russell 2000 index of smaller companies fell 4.26 to 438.01  
Friday, and was down 4.32 for the week. 
</P>
<P>
	The Wilshire Associates Equity Index, which represents the  
combined market value of all NYSE, American and Nasdaq issues, 
ended the week at $11.9 trillion, off $297.076 billion from the 
previous week. A year ago the index was $10.3 trillion. 

  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
