<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Lakers Discuss Opening With Jackson </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LOS ANGELES (AP) -- The Los Angeles Lakers, who haven't won an  
NBA championship since 1988, are speaking with Phil Jackson about 
their vacant coaching job. 
</P>
<P>
	Jackson guided the Chicago Bulls to six NBA titles in his nine  
years as their coach. He left following last season, after the 
Michael Jordan-led Bulls won their sixth and final title, and 
didn't coach this season. 
</P>
<P>
	The Bulls were 545-193 under Jackson.  
</P>
<P>
	``We're not going to deny the fact that we've talked to Phil  
Jackson about coaching the Lakers next season,'' Jerry West, the 
team's executive vice president for basketball operations, said in 
a statement issued Friday. ``With the success he's had in the NBA, 
he's definitely an attractive candidate. 
</P>
<P>
	``However, we're exploring several possibilities with different  
individuals and no decision has been made yet.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Fox Sports News reported late Thursday that the Lakers offered  
Jackson, 53, a four-year deal worth more than $20 million. However, 
while admitting there was interest, West told the Los Angeles Times 
no offer had been made, and ``it would be wrong to presume a deal 
was near.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Speaking after the WNBA's Los Angeles Sparks played their  
season-opener Thursday night at the Forum, Lakers owner Jerry Buss 
said he would neither confirm nor deny the report. 
</P>
<P>
	``I've been out of town,'' Buss said. ``I've got to talk to  
Jerry West. We'll see.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Jackson's Chicago-based agent, Todd Musburger, was reported by  
Fox Sports News to be in ``serious negotiations'' with the Lakers. 
</P>
<P>
	Musburger wouldn't comment when contacted by the Times, and  
didn't immediately return a telephone call Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	The Showtime Lakers of the 1980s won five championships, but  
haven't reached the NBA Finals since 1991, when they lost to 
Jackson and the Bulls in five games, beginning Chicago's run of six 
titles in a span of eight seasons. 
</P>
<P>
	The Shaquille O'Neal-led Lakers reached the Western Conference  
finals last spring before being swept by the Utah Jazz. This year's 
Lakers were swept by Western Conference champion San Antonio in a 
second-round playoff series to complete their chaotic 
lockout-shortened season. 
</P>
<P>
	Many viewed the Lakers as the logical successor to the Bulls  
after Jackson left, Jordan retired and other key players were 
either traded away or signed contracts with other teams. 
</P>
<P>
	However, Del Harris was fired as coach of the Lakers after the  
team lost three road games in as many days in February to fall to 
6-6, and former Bulls rebounding star Dennis Rodman played his 
first game with the team on Feb. 26 -- the same day 41-year-old Kurt 
Rambis was hired to succeed Harris on an interim basis. 
</P>
<P>
	The Lakers won their first nine games with Rambis as coach, but  
Rodman took a leave of absence at that point, and the remainder of 
the season was a jumble of controversy. 
</P>
<P>
	Rodman, who thrived under Jackson in Chicago, was finally waived  
April 16. 
</P>
<P>
	Rambis, under contract as coach through the end of the current  
season, said the day after the Lakers' lost their fourth and final 
game to the Spurs that he expected to be back next year. 
</P>
<P>
	It appeared that would be the likely scenario until the last few  
days. 
</P>
<P>
	West told the Times late Thursday the Lakers had ``talked about  
a lot of different parameters to a couple different people,'' 
adding the team has had similar discussions with Rambis. 
</P>
<P>
	``There's going to be a lot of speculation out there,'' West  
added. 
</P>
<P>
	Jackson was reportedly on vacation in Alaska, and unavailable  
for comment. 
</P>
<P>
	Several other teams, including the New York Knicks and New  
Jersey Nets, also are reportedly interested in hiring Jackson, who 
played for the Knicks from 1967-78, and for the Nets in 1979-80. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
