<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Salt Lake Olympics Gives Raises </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SALT LAKE CITY (AP) -- Struggling to raise money and cutting  
frills, the Salt Lake Organizing Committee nonetheless has money 
for 3 percent pay raises to 237 employees and officers. 
</P>
<P>
	The Olympic scandal has set back fund raising, with  
belt-tightening governing just about everything in SLOC. 
</P>
<P>
	But officials relented on pay raises because to forego them  
``would be so fundamentally horrible,'' said Ed Eynon, senior vice 
president of human resources. 
</P>
<P>
	A hiring freeze has kept SLOC from adding another 77 staffers by  
now, three years before the 2002 Winter Games. 
</P>
<P>
	``You're working your people harder, and they've gone through a  
very tough time,'' Eynon said. ``Obviously, they'd like more (of a 
raise) but they understand.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Last year's raises were 4.5 percent. This year's 3 percent will  
go to regular employees based on merit after job evaluations this 
month. Nine SLOC officers were offered the same raise by SLOC's 
management committee Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	SLOC president Mitt Romney is drawing no salary pending the  
games' completion under budget, and chief operating officer Fraser 
Bullock is turning away the raise. 
</P>
<P>
	Bullock, hired in April as Romney's right-hand man, is paid  
nearly $200,000 a year. 
</P>
<P>
	Romney says he'll retroactively accept predecessor Frank  
Joklik's $280,000 salary if the Games are a financial success. 
</P>
<P>
	Five other senior vice presidents are taking the raise: Eynon;  
Shelley Thomas for public communications; Grant Thomas, venues; 
Bill Wagner, operations, and Kelly Flint, legal and marketing. 
</P>
<P>
	Vice presidents Cindy Gillespie of federal relations and Mark  
Lewis of marketing and licenses also are accepting raises. Two 
other managers getting raises were not identified. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
