<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Stanford Baseball Coach Likes Team </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	OMAHA, Neb. (AP) -- Stanford coach Mark Marquess has led teams to  
two NCAA titles and an Olympic gold medal. And he likes the look of 
his Cardinal entering this year's College World Series. 
</P>
<P>
	``They think they're good, and that's half the battle,''  
Marquess said before sixth-seeded Stanford (48-13) game against No. 
3 Cal State-Fullerton (49-12) Saturday in the CWS opener for both 
teams. 
</P>
<P>
	In the earlier game, second-seeded Florida State (53-12) meets  
No. 7 Texas A&AMP;M (52-16). 
</P>
<P>
	Stanford, which won NCAA championships in 1987 and 1988, is  
making its 11th CWS appearance. It's the 23rd season at Stanford 
for Marquess, who coached the United States to the gold medal at 
the 1988 Olympics. 
</P>
<P>
	The Cardinal have traditionally had strong pitching. For  
example, Jack McDowell (1985-87) and Mike Mussina (1988-90) pitched 
for Marquess, who credited pitching for taking Stanford to Omaha 
again this season. 
</P>
<P>
	The Stanford staff set a single-season school record with 574  
strikeouts, 12 short of the Pac-10 record. Sophomore right-hander 
Jason Young (11-3, 3.14 ERA), who will start against the Titans, 
had a school-record 161 strikeouts. 
</P>
<P>
	Marquess also got strong efforts from sophomore right-hander  
Justin Wayne (9-1, 4.92, 131 Ks) and freshman right-hander Brian 
Sager (6-0, 3.98, 70 Ks). 
</P>
<P>
	``I thought we were at least a year or two away (from Omaha),''  
Marquess said. ``We basically had to pitch our entire season with 
freshmen and sophomores.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Fullerton beat Stanford 8-0 to start the season, then lost the  
next two to the Cardinal and another at Pepperdine. Coach George 
Horton said he wasn't sure what kind of team he had during its 
early-season struggles. 
</P>
<P>
	When Fullerton went unbeaten in 15 games during March, Horton  
knew he had a good team. The Titans really came together last 
weekend, winning at Ohio State to capture the super regional. They 
played without four starters who were suspended for throwing rocks 
during the regional a week earlier at South Bend, Ind. 
</P>
<P>
	Second baseman David Vacani and shortstop Chad Olszanski and  
pitchers Adam Johnson and Marco Hanlon will play at Omaha. Johnson 
(10-3, 3.22) will start against Stanford. 
</P>
<P>
	``They've served their penalty,'' Horton said. ``That's behind  
us and we're glad to have them back.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Florida State is making its 17th trip to the CWS but the  
Seminoles are still searching for their first title. Coach Mike 
Martin has been criticized for over-managing his previous teams. 
This year, he pulled back and let the team play. 
</P>
<P>
	What resulted was a season of highs and lows, from second  
baseman Marshall McDougall's six home runs in a victory last month 
at Maryland to a five-game losing streak at the end of April. 
</P>
<P>
	``Our season has been punctuated by streaks,'' Martin said.  
``The highs are when you play Miami in a packed house and win 8-2. 
The humilities are when you lose the next five. We accomplished 
that with ease.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Then there was the celebration after the Seminoles won their  
super regional to advance to Omaha. Three players were hurt in the 
pileup, including sophomore right-hander Nick Stocks (12-2, 3.09, 
130 Ks), who will start against A&AMP;M. 
</P>
<P>
	The Aggies hit 127 home runs to set a school record. Outfielder  
Daylan Holt led the nation with 34 homers, another school record, 
while hitting .339 with 105 RBIs. That power almost worked against 
A&AMP;M in the NCAA tournament. 
</P>
<P>
	``We proceeded to do it the hard way in the regionals,'' said  
Aggies coach Mark Johnson, whose team came through the loser's 
bracket to win its regional, then lost a game to Clemson in the 
super regional. 
</P>
<P>
	``We center our team around home runs, which no coach likes to  
do. Good pitching has a tendency to beat us, but we've beat some 
good pitchers.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Left-hander Casey Fossum (12-6, 3.35, 158 Ks) will start for the  
Aggies. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
