<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Police Bust Int'l. Call Girl Ring </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LOS ANGELES (AP) -- Police have busted what they say is one of  
the biggest call girl rings since the Heidi Fleiss case, arresting 
an alleged madam whose clients were said to include Hollywood 
figures, Fortune 500 CEOs and at least one pro athlete. 
</P>
<P>
	Jody Diane ``Babydol'' Gibson, 41, was arrested for  
investigation of pandering Wednesday at a Westside hotel, where she 
had gone to meet someone who turned out to be an undercover 
officer. 
</P>
<P>
	The arrest came after a 10-month investigation that began when a  
disgruntled employee told police she hadn't been paid, police said. 
</P>
<P>
	Ms. Gibson was released on $25,000 bail. Additional pandering  
charges are expected. Each carries a mandatory three-year sentence. 
</P>
<P>
	Ms. Gibson and about 30 employees serviced more than 100 men in  
this country and overseas, charging $500 to $3,000, Lt. Mike Felix, 
acting director of the vice unit, said Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	Ms. Gibson kept detailed notes on clients, but police aren't  
releasing any of the names. 
</P>
<P>
	``There are names that people would recognize as possibly being  
some of Heidi's clients,'' Felix said. ``There are people in the 
entertainment industry involved. Actors, a professional athlete, 
CEOs of Fortune 500 companies.'' 
</P>
<P>
	He added: ``Some of these businesses ought to be checking the  
expense reports of their executives.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Ms. Gibson allegedly ran her business from a dilapidated house  
in the tiny town of Palo Verde, near the Arizona state line. 
</P>
<P>
	Most business was conducted through the mail, though she also  
used a Web site called ``caldreamin,'' which advertised itself as a 
modeling agency and featured photos of semi-nude women, police 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	Clients were accepted by referral only, Felix said. After  
selecting a woman from the Internet site, men would be given a 
number to call to make arrangements. 
</P>
<P>
	At Ms. Gibson's house, investigators found lists with the names  
of about 30 female employees and clients, Felix said. 
</P>
<P>
	According to Ms. Gibson's records, Felix said, Fleiss once  
approached the woman for a job but was turned down. 
</P>
<P>
	Police said they did not know if Ms. Gibson had an attorney. Her  
telephone number is not listed. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
