<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-11 14:30:12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Energy Futures Rise; Pork Up Too  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Energy futures rose sharply Friday on the New York Mercantile  
Exchange amid the possibility of an oil workers' strike in 
Venezuela that could hobble the flow of oil to the United States. 
</P>
<P>
	On other markets, orange juice futures tumbled, while pork  
futures advanced. 
</P>
<P>
	Crude jumped as two key unions moved closer to a strike deadline  
in Venezuela, which exports about 60 percent of its oil to the 
United States and competes with Saudi Arabia for sales. 
</P>
<P>
	Oil workers are pressing their demand that the state-owned oil  
company rescind a decision to freeze wages for 33,000 workers 
nationwide and say they will walk off the job Monday unless that 
occurs. 
</P>
<P>
	Crude also found support after the International Energy Agency  
suggested world demand for oil from the Organization of the 
Petroleum Exporting Countries was on the rise after months in which 
economic downturns in Asia, Russia and Latin America dulled demand. 
</P>
<P>
	Crude products gasoline and heating oil also were supported by  
unconfirmed market rumors that BP Amoco had made additional cuts in 
refinery processing at plants in Illinois and Indiana because the 
cost of making those products is not profitable enough, given the 
relatively high cost of purchasing crude. 
</P>
<P>
	Light, sweet crude for July delivery rose 58 cents to $18.43 a  
barrel; July unleaded gasoline rose 1.67 cents to 53.20 cents a 
gallon; July heating oil rose 2.10 cents to 44.84 cents a gallon; 
July natural gas rose 2.3 cents to $2.375 for each 1,000 cubic 
feet. 
</P>
<P>
	Frozen, concentrated orange juice futures tumbled on the Board  
of Trade of the City of the New York after the government's 
production estimate for Florida's orange crop posted a smaller 
decline than expected. 
</P>
<P>
	The U.S. Department of Agriculture lowered its estimate of  
Florida's orange crop by 500,000 boxes from last month to 187.5 
million boxes, each weighing 90 pounds. But investors were 
expecting the agency to lower the estimate by 1 million to 2 
million boxes amid expectations severe weather had damaged more of 
the crop than originally thought. 
</P>
<P>
	July frozen concentrated orange juice fell 2.55 cents to 90.70  
cents a pound. 
</P>
<P>
	Hog futures finished the day mostly higher on the Chicago  
Mercantile Exchange amid news that retailers plan to feature pork 
next week. 
</P>
<P>
	August live cattle rose .62 cent to 65.02 cents a pound; August  
feeder cattle rose .63 cent to 77.95 cents a pound; July lean hogs 
rose .58 cent to 53.95 cents a pound; July pork bellies fell .45 
cent to 47.17 cents a pound. 


  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
