<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Japan Moves To Create 700,000 Jobs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	TOKYO (AP) -- Japan will try to tackle record unemployment,  
foster business growth and beef up its competitiveness by creating 
more than 700,000 jobs, the government announced Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	``We must allay people's worries about job security and put our  
nation's economy on track to self-sustained growth,'' Prime 
Minister Keizo Obuchi said in announcing the program. 
</P>
<P>
	Unemployment is at an all-time high of 4.8 percent -- about 3.4  
million people -- and government officials are worried that it may 
rise even higher. 
</P>
<P>
	Nearly half of the new jobs will be in the government sector,  
including a two-year program to boost hiring of part-time language 
teachers at public schools. The package also promises subsidies to 
companies in growing industries, such as telecommunications, 
ecology and biotechnology, to encourage hiring. 
</P>
<P>
	Obuchi said he hopes to get a supplementary budget passed as  
soon as possible to fund the program. The Japanese media has 
speculated that he will request $4.2 billion, a figure deemed 
likely by Finance Minister Kiichi Miyazawa. 
</P>
<P>
	While business leaders praised the package, analysts expressed  
doubts over how effective the program could be. 
</P>
<P>
	The main problem is that boosting competitiveness and saving  
jobs are contradictory, said Andrew Shipley, an economist with 
Schroders Japan in Tokyo. 
</P>
<P>
	``If you want to protect jobs, you have to sacrifice  
productivity and wage growth. What the Obuchi administration is 
trying to do is have its cake and eat it, too,'' Shipley said. ``He 
is trying to generate the benefits of a restructuring and 
market-oriented policy without enduring any of the pain.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Akitaka Saiki, the prime minister's spokesman, acknowledged that  
social welfare was a major part of the jobs program at a time when 
the old system of lifetime employment -- in which workers could 
expect to be employed at the same company for their entire career -- 
is quickly eroding. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is a painful phenomenon for most workers,'' he said.  
</P>
<P>
	The program offers a way to help adjust, Saiki said, by offering  
job-training for mid-career workers and opening up new job 
opportunities for business executives, such as language 
instruction. 
</P>
<P>
	The package also seeks to make it easier for small and  
medium-sized businesses to reconstruct and declare bankruptcy, and 
is intended to help companies to shift stock holdings and sell off 
parts of their operations. Such measures will require the passage 
of bills in Parliament. 
</P>
<P>
	Hiroshi Okuda, chairman of Toyota Motor Corp. who heads an  
influential business group called Nikkeiren, called it ``timely.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``From now on, we in the private sector must work toward  
increasing our own competitiveness and creating jobs,'' Okuda said. 
</P>
<P>
	News of the plan comes a day after the Obuchi administration  
released figures showing an unexpectedly strong 1.9 percent 
economic growth rate for the first three months of this year -- the 
first sign of growth since the summer of 1997. But that growth 
largely reflects massive public works spending. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
