<HEADLINE> NASCAR's Petty Denies Move to IRL </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BROOKLYN, Mich. (AP) -- Kyle Petty says there's no truth to a  
rumor that he might drive in a future Indy Racing League event. 
</P>
<P>
	The speculation grew when Petty was offered the opportunity to  
drive a few laps in an IRL car Tuesday at Atlanta Motor Speedway. 
</P>
<P>
	``I've never discussed running an Indy race with anybody at  
Atlanta, or any other races this season,'' Petty said Friday. 
``It's not that I don't think it wouldn't be fun. There just isn't 
time for it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Petty said Terry Linger, part owner of Panther Racing, asked him  
if he would like to drive a few laps in the IRL car while the team 
was testing in Atlanta. 
</P>
<P>
	``I was going to do a few laps for fun, see what it was like,  
tell them thanks and head home,'' Petty said. ``It was just a fun 
deal. 
</P>
<P>
	``My racing plans are focused entirely on Petty Enterprises and  
what we're doing there.'' 
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	 *GUNS 'R US:* Remington Arms Co. Inc., has entered a six-year  
sponsorship agreement with Dale Earnhardt Inc. 
</P>
<P>
	The deal includes a personal endorsement contract with Earnhardt  
and an associate sponsorship for Dale Earnhardt Jr. 
</P>
<P>
	``Two of my favorite things are my steering wheel and my  
Remington rifle,'' Earnhardt said. ``So to me, this announcement 
means two of my favorite passions in life are joining together. 
When he was young, I told Dale Jr. that hunting and racing are a 
lot alike. Holding that steering wheel and holding that rifle both 
mean you better be responsible.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The agreement with Earnhardt begins immediately and the  
associate sponsorship starts in 2000 for Earnhardt Jr. 
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	 *MAKING A DIFFERENCE:* Gary Geissman is proving that drivers of  
race-car transporters can make a difference in children's lives. 
</P>
<P>
	Throughout the 1999 NASCAR season, Geissman, driver of the  
transporter for Johnny Benson's car, has been corresponding with a 
third- and fourth-grade resource room class at Milo A. Brown 
Elementary School in nearby Byron Center. Thursday, he drove the 
transporter to the school for a visit. 
</P>
<P>
	Teacher David Dunn contacted Roush Racing in hopes of finding  
someone to help motivate his students to learn and believe in 
themselves. As a result, Geissman now drives the transporter by day 
around the country and at night reads the letters he receives from 
the students. Geissman also takes the time to respond to each 
student individually. 
</P>
<P>
	``I thought it would be special if I sat down and wrote each kid  
a full-page letter,'' Geissman said. ``It is time-consuming, but I 
think it's the better thing to do.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The letters Geissman sends also are used to teach the students  
math and geography. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
