<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> A Kinder, Friendlier Toys R Us </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- When Jenny Wong thinks of the stores she detests  
to shop at the most, Toys R Us comes to mind. 
</P>
<P>
	``I hate shopping at a store where the sales help literally  
barks at you if you have a question or need help finding 
something,'' said the mother of two from New York. 
</P>
<P>
	While shoddy customer service is a problem at many of the  
nation's retailers, Paramus, N.J.-based Toys R Us has been cited as 
one of the worst offenders. 
</P>
<P>
	In an acknowledgment of its troubles, the company plans Sunday  
to launch its biggest customer service overhaul ever. The 
initiative, designed with the help of Walt Disney Co., is intended 
to rally Toys R Us' 52,000 U.S. employees to change how they treat 
customers. 
</P>
<P>
	``You can lose a customer very fast, but you can win them back  
and part of that comes with great service,'' said Toys R Us chief 
executive Robert Nakasone. ``It doesn't cost any more to smile or 
be polite to a customer, and there's a huge payoff if they come 
back to the store again.'' 
</P>
<P>
	It's been a tough few years for Toys R Us, and its problems --  
including sluggish sales and profits -- have been linked in part to 
its service issues. Consumers complain of cramped aisles, confusing 
layouts and apathetic salespeople who seem unable to distinguish 
Barbie dolls from baseball bats. 
</P>
<P>
	``Toys R Us allowed its stores to get tired, it allowed its  
service to get tired and that can't happen in any kind of 
retailing, but especially toy retailing,'' said Leonard L. Barry, a 
professor of retailing at Texas A&AMP;M University and author of 
``Discovering the Soul of Service.'' ``Toy stores are supposed to 
be a happy experience and selling today to the customer should be 
fun.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Toys R Us is anything but fun, said Wendy Liebmann, president of  
the retail consulting firm WSL Strategic Retail. ``I've heard from 
parents and grandparents that they feel the overall experience has 
been miserable.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Stealing customers from Toys R Us are discount chains such as  
Wal-Mart and Target, which are selling toys for cheaper prices and 
doing it with friendlier and more attentive staffs. 
</P>
<P>
	Wal-Mart, which is famous for its ``greeters'' who welcome  
shoppers, dethroned Toys R Us as the nation's biggest toy retailer 
in 1998. 
</P>
<P>
	Now Toys R Us is fighting back.  
</P>
<P>
	In the last year, the company has started a major renovation of  
its 1,500 stores, developing a brighter, easier-to-navigate layout 
with more selling space. 
</P>
<P>
	The company has also added more products that kids today want --  
such as electronics, science and learning toys and beauty 
accessories. It has scaled back on toys that aren't popular anymore 
like board games. 
</P>
<P>
	Toys R Us is also stepping up its presence on the Internet, and  
later this month, is expected to unveil a new toysrus.com Web site 
that has better graphics and is easier to use. 
</P>
<P>
	But many analysts say the most crucial step in winning shoppers  
back is improving customer service. 
</P>
<P>
	Sunday night every Toys R Us employee in the country will  
participate in a three-hour presentation and cheerleading session. 
The program will highlight the importance of taking the initiative 
with customers and being courteous. 
</P>
<P>
	In addition, employees will learn of changes planned in the  
coming year. One example: workers who never before got specialized 
training will be assigned a section of the store and taught about 
the toys there. 
</P>
<P>
	To symbolize the company's fresh start, workers will get new  
uniforms, a light denim shirt, with a new logo. 
</P>
<P>
	The program was designed with the help of the Disney Institute,  
which teaches other corporations how to implement the Magic 
Kingdom's customer service success. 
</P>
<P>
	``We want our employees to stop working off a task list and try  
to do anything possible to satisfy the customer,'' Nakasone said. 
``We'll know if the customer responds well, because it will show up 
in the sales, it will show up in the profits and it will show up in 
the stock price.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Shoppers like Ms. Wong say the new program may entice her to  
give Toys R Us another chance. In the last year, she's been 
shopping at Kmart and smaller specialty toy stores. 
</P>
<P>
	``Let's see what happens next Christmas,'' she said. ``If they  
are nice then, I'll admit the program is working.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
