<DOCNO> APW19990611.0015 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-11 01:00:18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> America's Health Said To Improve </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BOSTON (AP) -- The nation's top doctor says Americans are taking  
better care of themselves, but children are more likely to be obese 
and suffer from asthma. 
</P>
<P>
	``Asthma has sort of caught us all by surprise,'' U.S. Surgeon  
General David Satcher said at Harvard Medical School's commencement 
on Thursday. ``We don't understand it, to tell you the truth.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In 1996, there were 338 asthma hospitalizations for every  
100,000 children under the age of 14, an improvement since 1995, 
but significantly higher than the 284 hospitalizations observed in 
1987. 
</P>
<P>
	Overall, the health of Americans has improved in the decade  
since the government released its Healthy People 2000 goals -- a 
blueprint of more than 300 health objectives, from reducing smoking 
to increasing seat belt use. 
</P>
<P>
	Launched in 1979, the Healthy People initiative has been  
reformulated each decade to provide a yearly review of Americans' 
health progress. Six months shy of the 2000 goal, some target areas 
are on track or already have been reached, according to Satcher. 
</P>
<P>
	But some serious health problems continue to persist, most  
notably obesity, low-birthweight babies and childhood asthma, cases 
of which have almost tripled since 1980. 
</P>
<P>
	And there continue to be serious disparities in the health of  
whites vs. minority groups. Black children, for example, are three 
to four times as likely as whites to suffer complications from 
asthma, Satcher said. 
</P>
<P>
	More than 20 percent of children and more than half of Americans  
are considered overweight. Over 50 percent of Hispanic and black 
women are considered obese, he said. 
</P>
<P>
	``These things going in the current direction means that we  
continue to load the population with people who are at greater 
risk'' of diabetes, heart disease, cancer and stroke, said Dr. 
Robert Fletcher, a professor of ambulatory care and prevention at 
Harvard. 
</P>
<P>
	The incidence of low birthweight babies increased from 6.9  
percent of all births in 1987 to 7.5 percent in 1997. But much of 
that may be due to the larger number of babies being kept alive due 
to improved medical technology, Satcher said. 
</P>
<P>
	Infant mortality has dropped throughout the 1990s, and the death  
rate for children ages 1 to 4 has declined by 26 percent, 
surpassing the government's objective, he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Improving nutrition and physical activity alone -- the surgeon  
general recommends exercising 30 minutes five times a week -- could 
reduce cardiovascular illness and deaths by 50 percent, and 
colorectal cancer rates by at least 40 percent, Satcher said. 
</P>
<P>
	In encouraging news, 15 percent of the Healthy People objectives  
have been reached, including areas of nutrition, maternal and child 
health, heart disease, breast cancer and mental health. 
</P>
<P>
	Another 44 percent of the objectives are heading toward the  
target, including child immunizations, mammography screenings and 
consumption of five fruits and vegetables a day. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990611.0016 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-11 10:10:20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> entertainment </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Rather Book: Columns Between Covers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- If CBS News were a newspaper, Dan Rather's  
byline would be found on just about every page: 
</P>
<P>
	--Rather anchors the ``48 Hours'' newsmagazine.  
</P>
<P>
	--He serves as a correspondent for the new ``60 Minutes II'' and  
as a contributor to its forebear, ``60 Minutes.'' 
</P>
<P>
	--His name nests in the title of ``The CBS Evening News With Dan  
Rather.'' He does a daily radio commentary. And when the big story 
breaks, he's apt to be reporting from the thick of it. 
</P>
<P>
	If all this were a newspaper, it might properly be called The  
Daily Dan. 
</P>
<P>
	But it isn't a newspaper, it's broadcasting, and that suits  
Rather fine. Except for one thing: There's no ink involved. 
</P>
<P>
	Looking to fix that, Rather added ink to his regimen in June  
1997, when he began writing a weekly column. Syndicated by King 
Features, ``Dan Rather Reporting'' appears in newspapers 
nationwide. 
</P>
<P>
	Now Rather has gathered some of those columns, along with other  
writings, into a volume titled ``Deadlines and Datelines: Essays at 
the Turn of the Century,'' published by William Morrow. 
</P>
<P>
	In its pages, Rather speaks of people and things as diverse as  
Saddam Hussein and Debbie Reynolds; poor service from a Manhattan 
photo shop and heroic service in the rattletrap Mir space station. 
The pieces are crisply composed, a bit folksy and unfailingly 
gracious, even in reproach. It's very much Rather's voice, in ink. 
</P>
<P>
	Here we read of Rather looking, through tears, upon the broken  
body of one survivor of the Oklahoma City bombing after Timothy 
McVeigh is found guilty on all counts. The verdict marks ``the end 
of one chapter, but not the end of the whole story. 
</P>
<P>
	``Justice is like that,'' Rather reflects. ``It's meant to bring  
closure, to answer questions, to put limits on our suffering, to 
stop the wrongdoing. The reality is often more complicated than 
that.'' 
</P>
<P>
	We also read of Rather's wife Jean, who, as a girl, met up with  
a certain good-looking kid, a raven-haired truck driver passing 
through town. 
</P>
<P>
	``And ever since that dance, at the VFW post in Winchester,  
Texas, on a warm summer night many, many years ago, Jeannie has 
been an Elvis Presley fan,'' Rather writes. For the boy at the 
dance, who, ``a few months later, gave up truck-driving for a 
career in music,'' was Elvis himself. 
</P>
<P>
	``Wide variety. Easy to read. Mercifully short,'' says Rather in  
his office, jauntily reciting a few of his new book's selling 
points. ``And I'm supposed to tell you that this is the perfect 
Father's Day gift.'' 
</P>
<P>
	But if at that moment he's kidding around, the author of such  
books as ``The Camera Never Blinks Twice'' and ``The Palace Guard'' 
leaves no doubt he is thrilled to be between covers again -- 
especially since ``Deadlines and Datelines'' certifies for the ages 
that Rather, in addition to the CBS gig, took his turn writing a 
column. 
</P>
<P>
	``Seeing something in a newspaper with my byline on it reaches  
way back with me,'' he says. Back to Depression-era Texas when a 
little boy's dream ``was to become a big byline reporter for the 
Houston Chronicle or the Houston Post or the Houston Press. And 
dreams die hard. Sometimes, they never die.'' 
</P>
<P>
	After college and the Marines, Rather headed for the Chronicle.  
</P>
<P>
	``I wasn't particularly good at it,'' he admits. ``For one  
thing, I was an atrocious speller. But somebody had mercy on me, 
and while never saying to me, `Son, I'm not sure you're going to 
make it as a newspaperman,' they pointed me to the newspaper's 
radio station.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The broadcasting thing worked out pretty well for Rather in the  
decades to come. But when he was approached to write a syndicated 
column, he couldn't say no. 
</P>
<P>
	An unrequited urge can be persuasive. But didn't he already have  
enough to do? 
</P>
<P>
	``Well, when you're an anchor for a big television network, a  
lot of life is easy,'' Rather explains. ``Not everything: You're up 
there for everybody to shoot at. But a lot of things are really 
easy. And when you sit down to the blank computer screen, there is 
nothing easy about it. I like that.'' 
</P>
<P>
	On the jacket of his new book, Rather is pictured with his  
``Front Page''-vintage Royal manual typewriter. It resides on his 
office desk, though largely as a monument to past stories it helped 
him channel into print. 
</P>
<P>
	Now, Rather does his writing on a word processor.  
</P>
<P>
	And yet ... he also keeps a portable typewriter at home, he  
confides. There was a time when he would tote it along for writing 
on planes. 
</P>
<P>
	As recently as January.  
</P>
<P>
	``Flying back from Texas, I had an idea for a column and I was  
going to bang it out,'' he says. But he didn't get much work done. 
``One person said, 'It's been a long time since I saw one of 
those!' Another person brought their child over and said, 'This is 
what they had before computers.' And somebody else complained about 
the noise.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Rather got it. ``I have a new portable computer now,'' he says.  
And, like him, it's primed for the next column, for the next book. 
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	Elsewhere in television ...  
</P>
<P>
	`TOM WAITS: STORYTELLERS': Singer-songwriter Tom Waits is the  
focus of VH1's ``Storytellers'' airing Sunday at 10 p.m. EDT. Waits 
performs, and talks about the creation of such songs as ``Downtown 
Train,'' ``Ol' 55,'' ``Jersey Girl'' and ``Strange Weather.'' He 
also tells of the great stage actress Sarah Bernhardt, who, early 
this century at the end of her career, had her leg amputated, 
``which was purchased by Barnum &AMP; Bailey and displayed in a big 
case. At that time her leg was making more money than she was. 
Whenever I get depressed I think about that, and say things are not 
so bad.'' 
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	Frazier Moore can be reached at fmoore ``at'' ap.org  
  	   	
</P>
