<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Iraqi Resistance Members To Be Freed </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LOS ANGELES (AP) -- Five former Iraqi military officers who  
claimed they fought Saddam Hussein and then spent 2 1/2 years in 
custody here fighting deportation are bitter about their treatment, 
but happy to be getting out of jail. 
</P>
<P>
	``The system here is good, but the people who represent (the  
government) have brought shame to this country,'' Mohammed Jwer 
Abboud Al-Ammary, a former military cargo plane pilot, told The 
Associated Press on Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	A judge ruled Friday that the Iraqis may stay in Nebraska until  
a friendly country agrees to accept them, a judge ruled Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	A sixth Iraqi refused the agreement, the end to a saga that  
began in 1996 when the U.S. airlifted 6,500 Iraqis from Turkey 
following a failed coup in Iraq. 
</P>
<P>
	The men's families were granted asylum, but immigration  
authorities sought deportation of the men based on secret evidence 
that alleged they were actually spies for Hussein. 
</P>
<P>
	The men said they were grateful for the efforts to free them,  
especially those of former CIA Director James Woolsey, now a 
private lawyer who helped fight their deportation. But they also 
feel betrayed by the U.S. government, which they claim promised 
asylum. 
</P>
<P>
	Immigration Judge D.D. Sitgraves denied the men asylum in March  
1998 and ordered them deported, saying they could be double agents. 
The men claimed they would be executed if sent home. 
</P>
<P>
	U.S. authorities justified their imprisonment largely on secret  
evidence, a practice in immigration cases that has come under fire 
from federal lawmakers and activists. 
</P>
<P>
	Last year, the INS unsealed some of the evidence, testimony  
about the six Iraqis from FBI agents who discussed hunches, 
distaste for the detainees and their feelings about Arab culture. 
Woolsey, the former CIA director, called the detention ``a stain on 
the honor of the United States.'' 
</P>
<P>
	A sixth Iraqi, Ali Yasim Mohammed Karim, said he will never sign  
the freedom deal. 
</P>
<P>
	Authorities have given him until July 9 to change his mind. He  
could eventually be deported to Iraq. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'd rather die than accept this agreement,'' Karim said.  
</P>
<P>
	The remaining five will be released within two weeks to Lincoln,  
Neb., where their families were resettled. 
</P>
<P>
	Under the deal, the men must abandon any claims for asylum here  
but may remain in Nebraska until they are deported to a friendly 
country. They must report to the INS daily, stay at home at night, 
accept wire taps on their telephones and stay in the county. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990611.0021 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-11 07:20:29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Coaches Like NCAA Bat Restrictions </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	OMAHA, Neb. (AP) -- When Florida State experimented with wooden  
bats early in the season, it didn't seem right to coach Mike 
Martin. 
</P>
<P>
	``It was my first game with wooden bats in 25 years,'' Martin  
said. ``We got a two-run lead in the seventh inning and I knew it 
was over. That's a funny feeling in Dick Howser Stadium.'' 
</P>
<P>
	NCAA-mandated restrictions on aluminum bats were a hit with  
College World Series coaches, but they're not sure about making the 
metal bats perform too much like wood. 
</P>
<P>
	``Chicks dig the long ball,'' Miami coach Jim Morris said  
Thursday. ``We still want home runs, too. We know the fans love 
home runs. 
</P>
<P>
	This season, the NCAA imposed restrictions on the size and  
weight of aluminum bats, hoping to curtail the whopping offensive 
numbers that have characterized college baseball in recent years. 
</P>
<P>
	The standards required that bats not exceed 2 5/8 inches in  
diameter, one-quarter inch less than allowed in 1998. Also, the 
difference between the length of the bat and weight was restricted 
to a ratio designed to make powerful aluminum bats act more like 
wooden bats. 
</P>
<P>
	The change came after last year's College World Series, when  
eight teams combined to hit 62 home runs. That was 14 more than the 
previous record in Omaha. 
</P>
<P>
	It included a national championship baseball game with a  
football score. Southern California beat Arizona State 21-14. 
</P>
<P>
	Another concern was safety. Officials were concerned about the  
speed of the ball coming off the bat. 
</P>
<P>
	It took a while, but eventually the teams adjusted.  
</P>
<P>
	``Early on, we didn't see as many opposite-field home runs,''  
Alabama coach Jim Wells said. ``The managers were hitting them out 
with the old bats. I wasn't happy with the new bats, but as the 
season progressed the power was there.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Most teams were following the power game, nicknamed ``Gorilla  
Ball,'' that was developed by LSU coach Skip Bertman. The Tigers 
came to Omaha seven times in the 1990s and won four championships. 
</P>
<P>
	``Bertman made all of us decide what we should do,'' Cal  
State-Fullerton coach George Horton said. ``You recruit big strong 
guys, sacrifice some defense and try to score more runs than the 
other team.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The new bats didn't stop all the scoring. Nebraska had 50 runs  
in a game this year. Florida State's Marshall McDougall hit six 
home runs in a victory at Maryland last month. And not every team 
saw its home run totals decline. 
</P>
<P>
	Overall, coaches agreed it was the right move.  
</P>
<P>
	``I do worry about losing our run support, and fans like the  
offense,'' Stanford coach Mark Marquess said. ``This made us play 
with more balance.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The bottom line for the CWS coaches was that the game was  
improved without being damaged. 
</P>
<P>
	``We don't want to take the home run away,'' Texas A&AMP;M coach  
Mark Johnson said. ``In reality, the game was not the same 
hit-and-run, move-the-runner-over type of game. One of our 
obligations we have as coaches is to pass along the game we 
inherited.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990611.0022 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-11 23:00:07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Intersex Mice Found at Calif. Refuge </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LOS BANOS, Calif. (AP) -- Something strange is happening to the  
rodents at a Northern California wildlife area where thousands of 
birds were poisoned by toxic runoff from farms in the 1980s. 
</P>
<P>
	Both male and female reproductive organs were found in one-third  
of the 87 field mice, house mice, harvest mice and California voles 
trapped last year on land that once collected toxic runoff at the 
Kesterson National Wildlife Refuge. 
</P>
<P>
	Just 3 percent of rodents trapped there showed such  
characteristics in 1995. 
</P>
<P>
	``The number of intersex mammals was a surprising finding to  
everybody,'' said Michael Delamore, chief of the U.S. Bureau of 
Reclamation's drainage program in Fresno. ``We're not sure what it 
means, because it's new, and the phenomenon hasn't been widely 
reported.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Technically, the rodents seem to be pseudo-hermaphroditic,  
according to biologist Gary Santolo, who led the investigation. 
They appear to be males from the outside, and lack a vagina, but 
have a fully developed set of female organs internally. 
</P>
<P>
	Some scientists say something in the environment is causing the  
outbreak. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's fair to say that if it happened in four species and  
happened suddenly, it's indicative of an environmental cause of 
some sort,'' said Dr. Richard Auchus, an endocrinologist at the 
University of California at San Francisco. 
</P>
<P>
	Animals in the area have been monitored yearly since an  
investigation in 1985 revealed that selenium, a byproduct of 
agricultural runoff, was killing or deforming thousands of birds. 
</P>
<P>
	Massive quantities of selenium, pesticides and other toxic  
chemicals were being deposited in the refuge in ponds that served 
as a sump for farm runoff. The ponds have since been closed and 
filled in at a cost of $50 million. The refuge no longer 
encompasses the ponds. 
</P>
<P>
	Selenium is not believed to be the cause of the hermaphroditic  
rodents. All of them had elevated levels of the element in their 
livers, but studies of selenium's effect on lab mice have not 
induced similar deformities. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990611.0023 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-11 15:00:18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Tyson Gets OK To Train in Arizona </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PHOENIX (AP) -- Mike Tyson will return to Arizona to train for  
his next fight, which may come as early as August. 
</P>
<P>
	The former heavyweight champion, who is on probation until  
February, can come back after 3 1/2 months in a Maryland jail because 
of an agreement reached under an interstate compact, according to 
John MacDonald, spokesman for the Arizona Supreme Court. 
</P>
<P>
	MacDonald said Tyson had to have a legitimate reason to be in  
the state before he could be transferred under the terms of his 
probation stemming from a misdemeanor assault conviction. 
</P>
<P>
	Tyson intends to resume training for a bout, possibly in August  
or September, at Las Vegas' MGM Grand hotel and casino. 
</P>
<P>
	Paul Kemp, Tyson's lawyer, said he wasn't sure when the fighter  
will arrive. But court officials said he must be here by Monday, 
when he is to report to the Maricopa County Adult Probation 
Department. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm sure he's looking forward to getting back into training  
and boxing,'' Kemp said. 
</P>
<P>
	Tyson will find the welcome mat is already out at his old gym.  
</P>
<P>
	``We're already putting up a banner that says `Welcome Back to  
The Community, Mike Tyson,''' Ricky Ricardo, who helps run the gym, 
told The Arizona Republic on Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	Tyson pleaded no contest to misdemeanor assault charges that  
stemmed from a fender bender in Gaithersburg, Md., last August. He 
will continue with anger management counseling, as well as meeting 
his community service requirements, while in Arizona, Maryland 
corrections officials said in a statement. 
</P>
<P>
	The boxer last fought in January and was behind on all three  
cards before he knocked out Francois Botha in the fifth round at 
Las Vegas. 
</P>
<P>
	He later left his equipment in the Phoenix gym before heading  
out to face his sentencing in Maryland. 
</P>
<P>
	Tyson also served a prison sentence in Indiana on a rape  
conviction. He registered in Arizona as a sex offender last fall 
when he decided to make Phoenix his home. He also has a home with 
his wife in Maryland. 
</P>
</TEXT>
