<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-11 00:10:08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Dismore Posts Best Qualifying Lap </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	FORT WORTH, Texas (AP) -- After posting the best qualifying lap  
for Saturday's Longhorn 500 IRL race at Texas Motor Speedway, Mark 
Dismore let out a big whoop. 
</P>
<P>
	``We have lap speed on our dash, but I never looked at it until  
I did my second lap,'' Dismore said. ``I was just focused on 
driving the car. I went down the back straightaway and looked down 
at the dash and saw that lap, and I yelled in my helmet. I was so 
happy. I didn't know if it would stick, but I knew that it was 
going to be good.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Dismore shook off an afternoon crash to come back and cover the  
1.5-mile oval in 24.332 seconds Thursday night, a qualifying speed 
of 215.272 mph, good enough for the pole ahead of teammate Scott 
Sharp. 
</P>
<P>
	Sharp, who also drives for the Kelley Racing team and who paced  
both of Thursday's practice sessions, qualified second at 214.839 
mph. Tyce Carlson was third at 214.417 and Greg Ray fourth at 
213.805. 
</P>
<P>
	The 42-year-old Dismore began racing karts in 1968 and won 40  
grand national kart races through 1989. He made his Indy-car debut 
at Mid-Ohio in 1989, and won the Formula Atlantic Pacific Division 
championship in 1990. 
</P>
<P>
	He came to Indy, but did not qualify in 1992-93. He won the 24  
Hours of Daytona in 1993 and at Nazareth in 1994 in his only 
Formula Atlantic start. His best IRL finish is fifth twice. 
</P>
<P>
	``We should have won three or four races, and we had a big goose  
egg. I hope this is the start of a good cycle that's going to be a 
good cycle instead of the cycle it had been. I haven't been the 
luckiest guy in the world, so maybe the monkey has fallen off my 
back,'' Dismore said. 
</P>
<P>
	In his first afternoon run, Dismore made contact with an outside  
retaining wall exiting turn 4. His car became loose between turns 3 
and 4, and there was light damage to his right front wheel. 
</P>
<P>
	``We had a motor today that watered the back tires, and I put  
the thing in the wall,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Dismore, who broke his neck, both feet, right wrist and right  
knee in a crash during practice for the Indy 500 in 1991, climbed 
out of the car without assistance. After evaluation in the infield 
care center, he was cleared to drive. 
</P>
<P>
	``It has not been an easy day. In fact, it has been a bit of a  
downer, actually, but this sure makes up for it,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Defending champion Billy Boat was 11th of 26 entrants at 211.671  
mph. After a good first practice, he said: ``It was a good run. 
We're going to make a few changes to make it better. It feels great 
going in as defending champion, and the heat is not getting to the 
car.'' 
</P>
<P>
	But the tires of Boat and Jaques Lazier touched exiting the  
fourth turn, with Boat running high and Lazier low. Both cars spun 
through the infield grass. 
</P>
<P>
	The air temperature was 85 degrees and the track temperature 100  
degrees when the qualifying began. Winds began to kick up and skies 
were threatening, but all drivers got in their qualifying runs 
without rain. 
</P>
<P>
	The qualifying times were well off the track one-lap qualifying  
record of 225.979 mph set last September and the one-lap race 
record of 228.012 set by Tony Stewart a year ago. 
</P>
<P>
	It was the Indy Racing League's first competitive event on a  
high-banked oval since the ill-fated VisionAire 500 at Concord, 
N.C., on May 1 in which three spectators were killed by flying 
debris. 
</P>
<P>
	The IRL moved to reduce speeds slightly beginning with the  
Longhorn 500 by lowering maximum RPMs from 10,300 to 10,000. It 
follows a reduction in the RPMs from 10,500 in 1998. 
</P>
<P>
	Saturday's race is the fifth in the IRL's 11-race season.  
</P>
<P>
	Race speeds Saturday are expected to drop more than 3 mph  
because with the reduction in RPMs. In theory, lower speeds make 
the cars more drivable, resulting in fewer crashes. 
</P>
<P>
	TMS is a 1.5-mile quad-oval with 24-degree banked turns, similar  
to Concord and Atlanta Motor Speedway, which was built for heavier 
and slower stock cars. IRL races have been staged at TMS and 
Concord since 1997 and at Atlanta since 1998. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
