<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Notification Forces Teen's Retrial </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	RICHMOND, Va. (AP) -- The Virginia Supreme Court ruled Friday  
that both parents must be notified when a minor is arrested -- a 
decision that may enable thousands of juvenile prisoners to 
challenge their convictions. 
</P>
<P>
	The unanimous ruling affirmed a Virginia Court of Appeals  
decision ordering a new trial for Jeramie Baker, who was convicted 
at 17 of trying to rob a convenience store and stabbing a clerk. 
Only his mother was notified of his arrest, despite a state law 
that says summonses must go ``to the parents'' of the juvenile. 
</P>
<P>
	Before the appeals court ruling, it was common practice for  
Virginia prosecutors to notify only one parent. Baker's lawyer said 
that practice is no longer good enough. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're at a time when people are suggesting we hold parents  
more responsible for their children's behavior,'' lawyer Clifford 
Y. Rose said. ``If you're going to do that, you've got to let them 
know what's going on.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Prosecutors said the ruling means thousands of convictions --  
including those of murderers and other violent offenders -- could be 
open to challenge. 
</P>
<P>
	Alarmed by the potential consequences, the General Assembly last  
winter changed the law to require notification of only one parent. 
However, that law doesn't take effect until July 1 and is not 
retroactive. 
</P>
<P>
	The ruling does not mean juveniles will be automatically  
released. 
</P>
<P>
	``Virginia should not be greatly concerned about a mass exodus  
of juvenile offenders from detention facilities,'' said David 
Botkins, spokesman for Attorney General Mark L. Earley. 
</P>
<P>
	Any jailed youth seeking release based on the ruling would have  
to go back to court, go through another trial and risk getting a 
stiffer sentence when retried, Botkins said. 
</P>
<P>
	Henrico County Commonwealth's Attorney Toby Vick said the ruling  
will probably crowd court dockets with requests to throw out 
convictions. 
</P>
<P>
	``And who knows what ability we would have to reconstruct and  
retry those cases?'' he said. ``In Henrico, we will make an effort 
to retry the serious ones.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The state had argued that the notification requirement in  
Baker's case was met because the law also allows notification of a 
guardian or legal custodian. Baker's mother, the state argued, 
qualified as his guardian. 
</P>
<P>
	But the Supreme Court said the use of the plural ``parents''  
made it clear authorities must at least make an effort to reach 
both mother and father. 
</P>
<P>
	``Here, even though the juvenile's mother received notice, the  
juvenile's biological father was not notified, there was no attempt 
to give him notice, and the circuit court made no certification on 
the record that the identity of the father was not reasonably 
ascertainable,'' the justices wrote. 
</P>
<P>
	Baker's parents split up when he was 4, and his father's address  
was unknown when the teen-ager was charged in 1996. He was 
sentenced to three years and four months in prison. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
