<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Notification Forces Teen's Retrial </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	RICHMOND, Va. (AP) -- The Virginia Supreme Court has ruled that  
authorities must try to notify both parents when a minor is 
arrested, a decision that may enable thousands of prisoners to 
challenge their convictions and win new trials. 
</P>
<P>
	The court's unanimous ruling Friday affirmed a decision ordering  
a new trial for Jeramie Baker, who was convicted at age 17 of 
unlawful wounding and attempted robbery. Only his mother was 
notified of his arrest, despite a state law that says summonses 
must go ``to the parents'' of the juvenile. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're at a time when people are suggesting we hold parents  
more responsible for their children's behavior,'' said Baker's 
attorney, Clifford Rose. ``If you're going to do that, you've got 
to let them know what's going on.'' 
</P>
<P>
	It had been common practice for Virginia prosecutors to notify  
only one parent. Prosecutors say the decision means thousands of 
convictions -- including those of juvenile murderers and other 
violent offenders -- could be open to challenge. 
</P>
<P>
	Alarmed by the potential consequences of the ruling, state  
lawmakers last winter changed the law to require notification of 
only one parent. However, that law doesn't take effect until July 1 
and is not retroactive. 
</P>
<P>
	The ruling does not mean juveniles will be automatically  
released. 
</P>
<P>
	``Virginia should not be greatly concerned about a mass exodus  
of juvenile offenders from detention facilities,'' said David 
Botkins, spokesman for Attorney General Mark Earley. Any jailed 
youth seeking release would have to go back to court, go through 
another trial and risk getting a stiffer sentence when retried, 
Botkins said. 
</P>
<P>
	Kent Willis, executive director of the American Civil Liberties  
Union in Virginia, said the ruling means prosecutors must follow 
the letter of the law. 
</P>
<P>
	``There's always a tendency among prosecutors to take  
shortcuts,'' he said. ``This is an important due process 
decision.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Baker's parents split up when he was 4, and his father's address  
was unknown when the teen-ager was charged in Stafford County in 
1996 with attempting to rob a convenience store and stabbing a 
clerk. He was sentenced to three years and four months in prison. 
</P>
<P>
	``Here, even though the juvenile's mother received notice, the  
juvenile's biological father was not notified, there was no attempt 
to give him notice, and the circuit court made no certification on 
the record that the identity of the father was not reasonably 
ascertainable,'' the justices wrote. 
</P>
<P>
	Rose said he expects the county to retry his client, who was  
convicted as an adult and is still in a state prison. He said he 
did not know when Baker would be released. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
