<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Miami, Rice Says It's All Pitching </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	OMAHA, Neb. (AP) -- To hear Miami coach Jim Morris and Rice coach  
Wayne Graham, college baseball isn't about home runs anymore. Both 
insisted Thursday their matchup to open the College World Series is 
about pitching. 
</P>
<P>
	The top-seeded Hurricanes (46-13) and No. 8 Owls (58-13) play  
Friday night after the College World Series, celebrating its 50th 
year in Omaha, opens with a matinee between No. 4 Oklahoma State 
(46-19) and No. 5 Alabama (51-14). 
</P>
<P>
	Asked Thursday what Rice needs to do to beat Miami, Graham said  
it depends on what the Owls can do against Hurricanes right-hander 
Alex Santos (11-3, 3.10 ERA). 
</P>
<P>
	``My concern is scoring off Santos,'' Graham said. ``He's pretty  
good. We've got to pitch well, play defense well and scratch a few 
runs off Santos.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Morris, seated next to Graham during a news conference for the  
eight CWS coaches, returned the compliment for Rice ace Mario Ramos 
(13-2, 2.42). 
</P>
<P>
	``I could throw in Ramos and duplicate what he just said. Any  
time you're going against a left-hander, you always have to take 
advantage of every scoring opportunity you get,'' Morris said. 
</P>
<P>
	Morris said this isn't the typical Miami collection of sluggers  
with their mighty alumninum bats. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'd say we're a pitching and defense team,'' Morris said.  
``That's kind of amazing to sit up here and say with all the talk 
of alumninum bats. Our guys play hard. They feel someone is going 
to get it done for them.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Morris said that, in any given game, he doesn't know who will  
carry the Hurricanes. One of the leaders is shortstop Bobby Hill 
(.378, 9 HRs, 28 RBIs), who stole 50 bases this season to become 
Miami's career leader with 137. 
</P>
<P>
	Rice has won 31 of its last 36, and the Owls got gritty after  
losing their openers in the regional and super regionals. The top 
hitters are outfielder Will Ford (.403, 11, 70) and shortstop Damon 
Thames (.377, 9, 68). 
</P>
<P>
	According to rankings established by Collegiate Baseball, Miami  
is No. 1 nationally and Rice No. 2. But forget about it. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's a great matchup to start the series,'' Thames said. ``I  
think our biggest challenge is just to forget about the rankings 
and see how it goes.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Alabama enters the College World Series with a 15-game winning  
streak and has won 23 of its last 25. Not bad for a team that 
sometimes has as many as five freshmen in the lineup. 
</P>
<P>
	The Tide will start left-hander Justin Smith (5-4, 5.91), a  
junior from Elk City, Okla., who knows folks back home might be 
cheering for Oklahoma State. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm trying not to think about it too much,'' Smith said. ``If  
I just throw my game, I'll be all right. Coach (Jim) Wells has it 
all mapped out. He calls the pitches and I just throw the ball.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Cowboys send right-hander Thom Dreier (8-5, 3.61) to the  
mound, and he'll be tested against a hard-hiting Alabama lineup. 
</P>
<P>
	Shortstop Andy Phillips (.393, 22, 66) has a school-record  
33-game hitting streak and became the Tide's home run king this 
season. With 61 career home runs, he is tied with former 
Missississipi State standout Will Clark for third on the 
Southeastern Conference list. 
</P>
<P>
	The Cowboys hit 130 home runs this season, fourth-best in school  
history, and outfielder Lamont Matthews (.396, 30, 105) led the 
way. 
</P>
<P>
	``He does excite people when he comes to the plate,'' Oklahoma  
State coach Tom Holliday said. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
