<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Overview of eBay </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Facts about eBay:  
</P>
<P>
	--EBay is the world's largest online auction site, with more than  
2 million items listed at any time. 
</P>
<P>
	--In an average minute on eBay, more than 150 new items are  
listed, 500 bids are placed and seven new people register. 
</P>
<P>
	--EBay's Web site receives more than 600 million hits a month.  
</P>
<P>
	--50 percent of items listed on eBay are sold.  
</P>
<P>
	--Online auctions are expected to sell $3.2 billion worth of  
merchandise by 2002, according to Internet analysts at New 
York-based Jupiter Communications. 
</P>
<P>
	--EBay's annual revenues grew 996 percent from 1996 to 1998,  
making it the fastest growing publicly traded company in the 
Silicon Valley. 
</P>
<P>
	--EBay had more than 3.8 million registered users as of March 31,  
1999. 
</P>
<P>
	--Among the items listed for auction when the site crashed were  
11,377 Barbie dolls and accessories, an autographed black and white 
photo of Mother Theresa, and a Rolex submariner watch that had 
reached $11,000 with 21 bids when trading was halted. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990611.0051 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-11 15:22:22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> With War Over, Complications Begin </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- It sounded simple: Serb troops out of Kosovo,  
NATO peacekeepers in, refugees back to their homes. 
</P>
<P>
	Now that peace is at hand, this formula for success in Kosovo is  
looking more complicated than suggested by the daily recitation in 
allied capitals during 11 weeks of bombing. 
</P>
<P>
	For example, getting the 40,000 Serb army troops, special police  
and paramilitary forces -- along with their hundreds of tanks, 
artillery, air defense weapons and other equipment -- out of the 
province over bomb-damaged roads and bridges will take more than 
the seven days NATO initially had expected. 
</P>
<P>
	``The dangers aren't over. Indeed, in some respects the dangers  
begin,'' British Prime Minister Tony Blair said Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	``We still have to win the peace,'' President Clinton told  
airmen and their families at Whiteman Air Force Base, Mo. 
</P>
<P>
	Even as the peacekeepers, 50,000 strong, prepared Friday to  
start moving into a Kosovo littered with land mines and other 
hazards, complications arose with Russia, which wants to be part of 
the effort but not on NATO's terms. A column of Russian troops 
entered Yugoslavia and headed toward Kosovo, surprising NATO and 
forcing the alliance to hurriedly come up with a plan for 
accommodating the Russians. 
</P>
<P>
	And those are just today's problems. Among the complications  
coming into focus for the weeks ahead: 
</P>
<P>
	-- Getting enough of a start on rebuilding the ruined homes and  
villages in Kosovo to enable the million or more ethnic Albanians 
to come home. The peacekeepers will get this long-term effort 
started, but completing it will be mainly the job of civilian 
organizations, including private relief agencies. 
</P>
<P>
	``At the moment we don't really know the full impact of the  
crisis on the homelands of Kosovars,'' the British minister for the 
armed forces, Doug Henderson, said Friday in London. ``We do know 
that it lies in ruins and we know that it will be no simple matter 
to enable the Kosovars to return home safely.'' 
</P>
<P>
	-- Disbanding the Kosovo Liberation Army, the rebel group whose  
stated aim is independence for Kosovo. NATO says it will expect the 
KLA fighters to give up their heavy weapons but not rifles and 
other light arms. The group will be ``demilitarized,'' not 
disarmed, officials say. Will the rebels go along? 
</P>
<P>
	Pentagon spokesman Kenneth Bacon said the KLA was  
``skirmishing'' with Yugoslav army troops as recently as Thursday, 
although the rebels were showing no sign of blocking Serb troop 
withdrawals Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	-- Legal disputes. Many of the ethnic Albanians who fled Kosovo  
were stripped of their personal papers. How will NATO and the 
United Nations sort out property ownership questions once the 
refugees return? 
</P>
<P>
	The legal complications are ``enough to keep a division of  
Philadelphia lawyers busy for a decade,'' said Harry Summers, a 
retired Army colonel who writes about military affairs. 
</P>
<P>
	-- Restoring the shattered economy. The United Nations World Food  
Program says there was no agricultural harvest in Kosovo this year 
due to the fighting, and displaced Kosovars have been scavenging 
for food for weeks. The Pentagon is considering using Air Force 
C-130 transport planes to drop as many as 84,000 packaged meals a 
day into Kosovo once the NATO-led peacekeepers enter the province. 
</P>
<P>
	``We will basically enter a territory without food,'' Anna Di  
Lellio of the U.N. food agency said recently. 
</P>
<P>
	-- Autonomy for Kosovo. The NATO agreement that Yugoslav  
President Slobodan Milosevic accepted promises ``essential autonomy 
for Kosovo.'' It does not say just what that means, except that it 
should take into consideration the sovereignty and territorial 
integrity of Yugoslavia. Negotiations on this must not delay or 
disrupt establishment of ``democratic self-governing institutions'' 
in Kosovo, the agreement says. The U.N. is to oversee 
administration of Kosovo in the meantime. 
</P>
<P>
	-- War crimes. Milosevic and four top aides were indicted on war  
crime charges May 27 by a U.N. tribunal. Belgrade has dismissed the 
indictments as a ploy orchestrated by NATO. Will public pressure 
grow for NATO to round up these men? In a nationally televised 
address Thursday, Clinton warned Serbs that the United States would 
not help them rebuild from bombing ``as long as your nation is 
ruled by an indicted war criminal.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
