<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> AP Corrects Media Ruling Story </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- In a June 9 story about court action in a case  
involving NBC's ``Dateline'' show, The Associated Press erroneously 
reported that the segment in question was about the Louisiana state 
police. 
</P>
<P>
	The court case centers on whether NBC has to hand over a  
videotape made for a segment that showed a Calcasieu Parish 
sheriff's deputy stopping a car. The network was investigating 
whether law enforcement officials were making decisions based on 
race, nationality or out-of-state plates. 
</P>
<P>
	The 2nd U.S. Court of Appeals had ruled in September that NBC  
had to hand the tape over to lawyers for a Hispanic couple who are 
suing the deputy, alleging civil rights violations. The June 9 
story reported that the court had set aside that ruling, saying it 
may need to rehear that issue. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990611.0053 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-11 18:00:16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Man Opens Fire in Michigan, 3 Dead </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SOUTHFIELD, Mich. (AP) -- A gunman opened fire on his doctor and  
several other people in an office complex Friday, killing two 
people and himself. 
</P>
<P>
	Four other people were wounded. The victims were shot in or near  
the doctor's office, on the 12th floor of a large building in this 
Detroit suburb. 
</P>
<P>
	``It appears we've got a doctor-patient relationship,'' Police  
Chief Joseph Thomas said. ``We are still trying to determine why it 
happened.'' 
</P>
<P>
	He would not say whether the doctor was among the wounded.  
</P>
<P>
	Four victims were taken to a hospital. A man was in serious  
condition with a gunshot wound to the chest, and three other 
victims were being treated for wounds they received after being 
shot at close range, Dr. Peter Goodman said. 
</P>
<P>
	The building -- an office complex with at least two dozen floors  
-- was evacuated of its visitors and workers. 
</P>
<P>
	Kim Spillane, 29, said she was working on the 11th floor and did  
not hear the gunfire but saw the commotion. 
</P>
<P>
	``I just happened to look out and see all the police cars,'' she  
said. ``I ended up closing and locking our suite door,'' which she 
ultimately had barricaded with a bookcase. 
</P>
<P>
	``We were pretty scared because no one was telling us  
anything,'' she said. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990611.0054 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-11 00:50:15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Miss. Gov. Announces Divorce Plans </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	JACKSON, Miss. (AP) -- Another day, another drama at the  
governor's mansion. 
</P>
<P>
	The latest? Gov. Kirk Fordice has ended years of speculation  
over his marriage and announced that he wants a divorce to wed a 
childhood sweetheart. The problem is that the first lady appears to 
be in no rush to end their marriage of nearly 44 years. 
</P>
<P>
	For the second time since taking office in 1991, Fordice has  
gone public with plans to divorce his wife, Pat, saying in a 
statement Thursday he wants to end their marriage ``equitably and 
with dignity.'' He said he plans to marry Ann Creson, a Memphis, 
Tenn., widow and a sweetheart from junior high, as soon as his 
divorce is final. 
</P>
<P>
	Mrs. Fordice declined to join her husband in the announcement.  
</P>
<P>
	``Her present inclination is to not have a divorce take place  
anytime in the near future,'' said her lawyer, L.C. James. ``It is 
not fair for Gov. Fordice to call upon her to calm the storms by 
making or adopting a public announcement which runs contrary to her 
true feelings.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The governor, who earlier this week threatened a reporter who  
broached the issue, seemed irritated when asked Thursday night if 
he might resign, as some critics have suggested. 
</P>
<P>
	``Have you read the statement? Have you read the statement? It's  
self-explanatory,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Fordice, a two-term Republican who is barred by term limits from  
seeking the governorship again, is scheduled to leave office in six 
months. But in a conservative state where no sitting governor has 
divorced, some wonder whether the flap will end any time soon. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's like a soap opera,'' said Frances Fredericks, a  
Democratic state legislator. ``I think he would bring another 
(wife) in, but if justice works the way it should, he won't be able 
to before his six months is up. I hope Mrs. Fordice will do 
whatever she can to delay it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	This isn't the first time the Fordices have engaged in a public  
marital tug of war. The governor first announced the collapse of 
his marriage in 1993, citing ``irreconcilable differences.'' A day 
later, Mrs. Fordice said she would continue serving as first lady 
unless forced out. They reconciled. 
</P>
<P>
	The couple became news again in 1996, when the governor was seen  
near Memphis having lunch and holding hands with a woman while Mrs. 
Fordice was n France (it was never established whether the woman 
was Ms. Creson). His whereabouts became news when Fordice, 65, was 
seriously injured in a car wreck as he headed home. 
</P>
<P>
	The latest announcement came on the heels of a report that  
Fordice vacationed in Europe last week with Ms. Creson while Mrs. 
Fordice remained in Jackson. Last month, it was revealed he bought 
a house in a Jackson suburb without inviting his wife to live 
there. 
</P>
<P>
	Ms. Creson did not return calls to her home on Thursday.  
</P>
<P>
	For now, the Fordices continue to live in the governor's  
mansion, according to Robbie Wilbur, Fordice's press secretary. And 
Fordice, who was a harsh critic of President Clinton's affair with 
Monica Lewinsky, continues to serve as a national co-chairman of 
Dan Quayle's presidential campaign, where family values are a 
central theme. 
</P>
<P>
	Quayle spokesman Jonathan Baron said the former vice president  
is standing behind the governor. 
</P>
<P>
	``We are pleased to have such support,'' he said.  
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
