<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Knicks' Johnson Injures Knee </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- It should have been a joyous victory for the New  
York Knicks, an unlikely, triumphant advance to the NBA Finals. 
</P>
<P>
	Instead, their 90-82 Game 6 victory over the Indiana Pacers  
Friday night was overshadowed by a frightening knee injury suffered 
by Larry Johnson. 
</P>
<P>
	Indiana's Travis Best, returning to action after missing two  
games with a groin injury, rolled into Johnson's right knee halfway 
through the second period. 
</P>
<P>
	Johnson went down in a heap, grabbing his knee and screaming in  
anguish. He was immediately surrounded by teammates. After several 
minutes on the floor, he was helped off by Herb Williams and Chris 
Dudley, led into the locker room by Dr. Norman Scott, the team 
physician. 
</P>
<P>
	X-rays were negative and the preliminary diagnosis was sprained  
ligaments. Johnson was taken to a hospital for a precautionary MRI 
examination. He will be re-evaluated on Saturday. 
</P>
<P>
	The Knicks' front line is already shorthanded after Patrick  
Ewing suffered a partial tear in his left Achilles, ending his 
season after two games of the Eastern Conference finals. Ewing led 
cheers from the bench as his team closed in on the victory. 
</P>
<P>
	Johnson was a vital cog in the Knicks' attack. His four-point  
play -- a 3-point field goal followed by a free throw -- with 5.7 
seconds left provided the deciding points in the Knicks' 92-91 
victory in Game 3. 
</P>
<P>
	In Game 5, Johnson hit consecutive 3-pointers down the stretch  
as New York pulled away for a 101-94 victory that put it in 
position to close out the Pacers at home. 
</P>
<P>
	When he was injured, Johnson had just scored two baskets after  
an 0-for-3 first quarter. He left the game having scored eight 
points in 14 minutes. 
</P>
<P>
	New York led 28-26 when Johnson went down with his injury,  
forcing adjustments on the fly. Allan Houston turned out to be the 
difference, leading all scorers with 32 points and making basket 
after basket down the stretch. 
</P>
<P>
	Without Johnson, coach Jeff Van Gundy gave additional playing  
time to Marcus Camby, who blossomed in the Eastern Conference 
finals against Indiana. Camby scored 15 points, including two key 
foul shots in the final minutes. 
</P>
<P>
	When Chris Childs made a basket in the third quarter, he formed  
an ``L'' with his arms, the way Johnson has done throughout the 
late stages of the season and the playoffs. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
