<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Cathay Flights Still Not Fully Normal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	HONG KONG (AP) -- Despite a new pay deal between Cathay Pacific  
Airways and its pilots, Hong Kong's flagship carrier canceled more 
than half its flights Friday as the airline worked to rebuild 
operations after a two-week sickout. 
</P>
<P>
	Cathay said the number of pilots calling in sick has gone down,  
but the airline had to cancel 69 of its 118 flights Friday. Cathay 
hired other airlines to fly 52 services on a charter basis to help 
keep passengers in the air. 
</P>
<P>
	Cathay spokeswoman Quince Chong said the airline was hoping to  
dispense with the chartered flights by late next week. 
</P>
<P>
	A two-week sickout of pilots claiming they were too stressed to  
fly crippled Asia's third largest airline, grounding hundreds of 
flights and affecting more than 85,000 passengers. 
</P>
<P>
	Late Thursday, Cathay and the cockpit crew reached an agreement  
for highly paid senior pilots to have their salaries cut by an 
average 7 percent, while junior pilots would see raises of up to 5 
percent over the next three years. 
</P>
<P>
	Cathay said it needs pay cuts to return to profitability after  
being hammered by losses last year during Asia's economic crisis. 
The company persuaded flight attendants to agree to concessions 
earlier in the year. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
