<DOCNO> APW19990611.0065 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-11 16:00:14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Orlando's Hardaway Now a Free Agent </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Four-time NBA all-star Penny Hardaway exercised an option to  
void the last three years of his contract with the Orlando Magic 
and will become a free agent on July 1. 
</P>
<P>
	Hardaway, who averaged 15.8 points, 5.7 rebounds and 5.3 assists  
this season, complained after an early playoff exit that he was 
underappreciated and said a change of scenery seemed like a logical 
solution. 
</P>
<P>
	``As expected, Penny has exercised his option,'' general manager  
John Gabriel said Friday. ``We will see what the future holds. We 
would like to re-sign him.'' 
</P>
<P>
	A telephone message left at the office of Carl Posten,  
Hardaway's Houston-based attorney, was not immediately returned. 
</P>
<P>
	Hardaway helped the Magic compile the second-best record in the  
Eastern Conference during the lockout-shortened regular season, 
however he struggled in the playoffs and felt fans and the media 
targeted him as a scapegoat. 
</P>
<P>
	``I never thought it would come down to this in Orlando. I  
wanted to finish my career here, but it seems like it's just too 
rocky right now,'' the sixth-year pro said the day after the Magic 
were eliminated from the playoffs by the Philadelphia 76ers. 
</P>
<P>
	``I like Orlando. I really do. But it has to be mutual,'' he  
said. ``Right now, I feel like I'm in a very tough situation. 
There's a lot of added pressure on me that shouldn't be there.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Hardaway apologized for the comments the following day.  
</P>
<P>
	Drafted as a point guard when Orlando's offense was centered  
around Shaquille O'Neal, the Magic became more dependent on 
Hardaway's scoring after the center left for the Los Angeles Lakers 
in 1996. 
</P>
<P>
	Hardaway appeared in every game after missing most of the past  
two seasons because of injuries. But he complained at times about 
not being able to get enough shots at point guard. 
</P>
<P>
	Hardaway was due $26 million over the last three years of his  
current contract. The most he could earn in a new deal would $85 
million over seven years, although just two teams -- Orlando and 
Chicago, which has lots of room under the salary, -- could offer a 
package in that range. 
</P>
<P>
	One option available to Hardaway if he is determined to not play  
in Orlando again is a sign-and-trade deal, in which he agrees to 
terms with Orlando and is traded to another team. 
</P>
<P>
	Hardaway played a major role in the firing of former coach Brian  
Hill in 1997 and also had his differences with Chuck Daly, who 
retired last month. 
</P>
<P>
	The Magic hired Doc Rivers to succeed Daly last Monday, and the  
new coach said he would welcome Hardaway back next season if that's 
what the star guard wants. 
</P>
<P>
	``I consider Penny a part of this organization. The key for us  
is we want to make sure he wants to be here,'' Rivers said. ``He's 
had his ups and downs. The one thing that no one questions is his 
talent.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
