<DOCNO> APW19990611.0066 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-11 22:40:11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Garden Nightmare Sends Pacers Home </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- The Indiana Pacers' championship mission failed  
again, stalled this time in the face of Spike Lee and the city they 
love to hate. 
</P>
<P>
	They've got to be getting sick of this by now.  
</P>
<P>
	Thought to be the team to beat in this post-Michael Jordan,  
lockout-shortened season, the Pacers were thwarted again Friday 
night with a 90-82 loss to the New York Knicks that might have 
surpassed the crushing devastation that Jordan and the Bulls 
inflicted on them last year. 
</P>
<P>
	Or maybe it was even worse.  
</P>
<P>
	``You can't compare this to losing to Chicago, because they were  
one of the best teams ever,'' Pacers point guard Mark Jackson said. 
``We're going home -- no disrespect to them -- but knowing that we 
feel we're the better team.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In the '90s, the Pacers have all the pride, experience and  
show-stopping qualities needed for thrilling postseason runs. In 
short, they have everything but rings; in fact, not even a trip to 
the NBA Finals. 
</P>
<P>
	Facing elimination at Madison Square Garden, the Pacers were  
whistled into oblivion as Reggie Miller had only eight points to go 
with five fouls. Rik Smits fouled out with 20 points, and Jackson 
committed five personals and scored 14 points. 
</P>
<P>
	Overall, the Pacers were called for 35 fouls, and the Knicks 16.  
New York shot 33 free throws, making 27. The Pacers were 9-for-9. 
</P>
<P>
	``When you have several guys picking up four or five fouls and  
one guy fouling out,'' said Jackson, his voice trailing off. 
``Let's just hope the NBA Finals is a great series. They got what 
they wanted.'' 
</P>
<P>
	During his Hall of Fame playing career with the Boston Celtics,  
Pacers coach Larry Bird was the beneficiary of foul calls. With 
``Larry Legend'' in a suit on the sideline, it was a different 
story. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's a tough deal when you play against New York,'' Bird said.  
``It's New York. You know you're not going to get a lot of calls.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Pacers completed their Garden nightmare with 27 turnovers  
resulting in 26 points by the Knicks. As a result, the Pacers are 
0-4 in the Eastern Conference finals during their impressive but 
still undecorated run of success this decade. 
</P>
<P>
	What happens now? A year older, and with another crushing defeat  
on their collective conscience, do the Pacers stay together and 
make another run? 
</P>
<P>
	``I love this team,'' forward Antonio Davis said. ``I love the  
guys. I think we can get it done.'' 
</P>
<P>
	When they lost to the Bulls in seven games in the conference  
finals last summer, the Pacers vowed to carry Jordan's torch and 
win the first championship after his retirement. They practiced 
together during the lockout, reminded themselves all season that 
nothing less than a championship would do. 
</P>
<P>
	They are right back where they started. This time, it was the  
Knicks showing them the way back to Indiana -- for the third time in 
five playoff series between the rivals. 
</P>
<P>
	``The guys were counting on me to put them on my backs, and I  
didn't do it this time,'' said Miller, whose long face contorted 
into an expression of disbelief when he picked up those two fouls. 
``I have to take responsibility for that.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Pacers' nerves never frayed, their determination didn't  
falter even when Miller picked up his third and fourth fouls in a 
span of 13 seconds with less than five minutes left in the third. 
With Miller on the bench, Jalen Rose took his customary spot in 
Lee's corner of the Garden, the 31st Street and Seventh Avenue 
corner, to hit several clutch shots that kept them in the game. 
</P>
<P>
	Miller picked up those two crucial fouls while trying -- and  
failing -- to guard New York's Allan Houston, who had 32 points. 
Then, when New York took a four-point lead, and then a six-point 
lead down the stretch, Miller missed the kind of backbreaking shots 
he's come to personify in this building. 
</P>
<P>
	Asked to describe his shooting, Miller said simply,  
``Horrendous. Horrendous.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The last miss came with the clock ticking inside 30 seconds.  
</P>
<P>
	Now, start the clock on the Pacers' offseason.  
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
