<DOCNO> APW19990611.0068 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-11 04:10:13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Celtics Dominate Nominees for Hall </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SPRINGFIELD, Mass. (AP) -- The Boston Celtics, the most dominant  
team in NBA history, dominated this year's nominations to the 
Basketball Hall of Fame. 
</P>
<P>
	Six of 13 candidates announced Thursday played for the Celtics:  
Kevin McHale, Dennis Johnson, Jo Jo White, Wayne Embry, Bob McAdoo 
and retired Georgetown coach John Thompson, who was a backup center 
for Bill Russell on the 1965 and 1966 championship teams. 
</P>
<P>
	``They did so much! How could you leave them out?'' said Red  
Auerbach, who coached the Celtics to nine titles from 1957-1966. 
</P>
<P>
	The Celtics have won 16 NBA titles, more than any other team,  
and 25 players, coaches and others connected to the Celtics already 
are in the Hall of Fame. 
</P>
<P>
	McHale and Johnson were teammates on the Larry Bird-led Boston  
teams that won NBA championships in 1984 and 1986. McHale also 
played on the Celtics' championship team in 1981. 
</P>
<P>
	Brought to the Celtics in 1980 with Robert Parish, McHale at  
first was the team's sixth man. The 6-foot-10 forward went on to 
play 12 seasons on a front line with Parish and Bird. 
</P>
<P>
	``He was so good, and he improved his game so much,'' Auerbach  
said. ``Originally, he was just in the pivot and after a while, he 
started to move around and developed a real good outside shot.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In 1985, McHale set a Celtics record by scoring 56 points  
against the Detroit Pistons. Bird broke the record nine days later 
with 60 against the Atlanta Hawks. 
</P>
<P>
	McHale averaged 17.9 points and 7.3 rebounds in his career, and  
was a 55 percent shooter from the field. He made seven All-Star 
teams and was three-time selection to the All-NBA defensive team. 
</P>
<P>
	Bird once said McHale ``never saw a triple-team he didn't  
like.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Thompson coached Georgetown for 27 years before leaving the job  
in January. His teams went 596-239, made the NCAA tournament 14 
straight times, played in three Final Fours and won the national 
championship in 1984. 
</P>
<P>
	White was sweet-shooting guard who won two championships with  
the Celtics and an Olympic gold medal in 1968. Embry played on 
Boston's 1968 title team. 
</P>
<P>
	McAdoo played in only 20 games for the Celtics, in the 1978-79  
season. The three-time league scoring champion played on two 
championship teams with the Los Angeles Lakers. 
</P>
<P>
	The other nominees are:  
</P>
<P>
	-- Maurice Cheeks, a slick guard for the 1983 NBA champion  
Philadelphia 76ers who was the league's career steals leader when 
he retired. 
</P>
<P>
	-- Gus Johnson, a power forward for the Baltimore Bullets who  
died of brain cancer in 1987. 
</P>
<P>
	-- Sidney Moncrief, a two-time NBA defensive player of the year  
for the Milwaukee Bucks in the 1980s. 
</P>
<P>
	-- Chet Walker, a forward on Philadelphia's 1967 championship  
team. 
</P>
<P>
	-- Mount St. Mary's coach Jim Phelan, the winningest active  
college coach. His career record is 800-442. 
</P>
<P>
	-- Tex Winter, an assistant Chicago Bulls coach who has spent 52  
seasons as a college and pro coach. 
</P>
<P>
	-- Morgan Wootten, the coach at DeMatha High School in  
Washington, D.C., whose record of 1,185-178 is the best ever for a 
high school coach. 
</P>
<P>
	This year's Hall of Famers will be announced June 21. For  
enshrinement, a nominee needs 18 of 24 votes from an Honors 
Committee of Hall of Famers, basketball officials, journalists and 
others. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
