<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Iran Spy Suspects Could Face Death </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	DUBAI, United Arab Emirates (AP) -- The head of Iran's judiciary  
said Friday that 13 Iranian Jews held on charges of spying for 
Israel and the United States could face the death penalty, the 
Islamic Republic News Agency reported. 
</P>
<P>
	``The laws (in Iran) have their own prescriptions which at  
certain instances provide for the capital punishment of spies,'' 
IRNA quoted Ayatollah Mohammad Yazdi as telling thousands of 
worshippers attending Friday prayers at Tehran University. 
</P>
<P>
	``Justice would be done on all members of the group, even (if it  
means) they should receive capital punishment,'' Yazdi was quoted 
as saying by the agency, monitored in Dubai. 
</P>
<P>
	U.S. and Israeli officials have called for the immediate release  
of the 13, saying the charges were unfounded. 
</P>
<P>
	Yazdi dismissed the criticism.  
</P>
<P>
	``We interpret your unhappiness with us as proof of our  
intellectual maturity. You will be happy with us once we agree to 
(be) your slaves, but Iran is an independent country and will not 
surrender to you,'' Yazdi added, according to the agency. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
