<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-11 16:30:12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Marlins, Counsell Part Ways </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MIAMI (AP) -- The Florida Marlins parted company Friday with 1997  
World Series hero Craig Counsell, and he was glad to go. 
</P>
<P>
	Counsell complained this week about his shrinking role on the  
team, and the Marlins responded by designating his contract for 
assignment. The move removed Counsell from the roster, and if the 
Marlins are unable to trade him in 10 days, he'll be placed on 
waivers. 
</P>
<P>
	General manager Dave Dombrowski said Counsell's complaints in a  
meeting with manager John Boles prompted the move. 
</P>
<P>
	``His comments to Bolesy sped things up with some of the things  
he said,'' Dombrowski said. ``He's a first-class individual, but 
sometimes even first-class individuals get frustrated.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Counsell, a fan favorite who lost his starting job at second  
base in spring training to Luis Castillo, said leaving the Marlins 
was what he wanted. 
</P>
<P>
	``I need a new start,'' he said. ``I need to go somewhere  
else.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Counsell scored the winning run in the 1997 World Series, but he  
started just 10 games this year and had a .152 average in 66 
at-bats. He took his frustration public and met with Boles after 
being taken out of a game Tuesday in the eighth inning for 
defensive reasons. 
</P>
<P>
	``Maybe some of my emotions boiled over,'' Counsell said. ``I  
regret feeling like maybe I was a jerk in that situation, but at 
the same time, you've got to fight for yourself.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Said Boles: ``I feel very sad about it. He's just a tremendous  
guy -- exactly how you'd like your sons to grow up. You wish him the 
best.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Counsell's departure leaves the Marlins with just three  
holdovers from the 1997 World Series roster -- Livan Hernandez, 
Cliff Floyd and Antonio Alfonseca. Alex Fernandez, who missed the 
series because of an injury, also remains with Florida. 
</P>
<P>
	To fill Counsell's spot on the roster, the Marlins purchased the  
contract of outfielder Danny Bautista from Triple-A Calgary. 
Bautista, 27, is a .232 career hitter in six seasons with Detroit 
and Atlanta. 
</P>
<P>
	Counsell said he's certain he'll wind up with another major  
league team, but the Marlins aren't so sure. Dombrowski has been 
trying to swing a trade ever since Counsell lost his starting job, 
but there's apparently not much demand for a 28-year-old second 
baseman who hit .251 last year and has little power or speed. 
</P>
<P>
	``Sometimes deals aren't just there to be made,'' Dombrowski  
said. 
</P>
<P>
	Dombrowski said the Marlins won't release Counsell. That means  
he could wind up with their Triple-A affiliate in Calgary, or in 
the minor leagues with another organization. 
</P>
<P>
	``I've got to get my career going again,'' Counsell said. ``I  
have no doubt I'll land on my feet and help somebody.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
