<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Missouri Dairy Recalls Cheese </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- A Missouri dairy is recalling 228 pounds of  
mild cheddar cheese that may be contaminated with listeria, a 
potentially life-threatening bacterium. 
</P>
<P>
	Morningland Dairy Farms Inc. of Mountain View, Mo., ceased  
producing and distributing cheese last month after the Food and 
Drug Administration found the bacteria in another type of cheese 
that Morningland already recalled. 
</P>
<P>
	But Friday, the company also recalled Morningland Dairy Mild  
Cheddar Cheese that it had produced before last month's FDA action. 
The cheese is made from unpasteurized milk, and contamination 
showed up in tests by health officials. 
</P>
<P>
	The mild cheddar cheese was sold in plastic bags ranging from  
half a pound to 20 pounds, with the code C179 written in ink on the 
label. 
</P>
<P>
	Listeria can cause serious, potentially fatal, infections in  
young children, the elderly and people with weak immune systems. It 
also can cause miscarriages. Healthy people, however, usually 
suffer short-term symptoms, including diarrhea, nausea, abdominal 
pain and fever. 
</P>
<P>
	No illnesses have been reported.  
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
