<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Fund Investors Needn't Play Fed Game </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Here's a way to stamp yourself as a true  
contrarian in the eyes of your fellow mutual-fund investors: Tell 
them you don't pay very much attention to the Federal Reserve. 
</P>
<P>
	What?!, they will likely reply. Surely you know that the Fed,  
with its decisions to tighten or ease credit conditions, exerts a 
powerful influence on stocks, bonds, the money markets -- just about 
every kind of security a mutual fund can own. 
</P>
<P>
	Wall Street analysts, economists, journalists and politicians  
sift through every statement uttered by Alan Greenspan, the Fed's 
chairman, like starving prospectors panning for gold. 
</P>
<P>
	The policies of Greenspan and his predecessor, Paul Volcker, are  
widely cited as primary reasons why the United States has tamed 
inflation, setting the stage for a generation-long bull market in 
financial assets. 
</P>
<P>
	That's all true, you may reply -- you have no argument with that  
description, point by point. But the way it is all too often played 
in the financial world, Fed-watching is a short-term game with high 
risks and very uncertain rewards. 
</P>
<P>
	Get caught up in the Fed's doings, and you can easily stray from  
your long-term financial plan, forgetting what you meant to 
accomplish in the first place. Like any other attempt to figure out 
the future, trying to outguess the Fed may subject you to paralysis 
by analysis, a dread cause of indecision and procrastination. 
</P>
<P>
	So your effort to become a better fund investor by keeping a  
close eye on the Federal Reserve's credit policy could wind up 
hurting you more than it helps. 
</P>
<P>
	Illustration: Suppose you set out today to put together a  
portfolio of fund investments, keeping ever-present in your mind 
recent hints from the Fed that it might tighten credit sometime 
soon by pushing short-term interest rates higher. 
</P>
<P>
	By long-standing tradition, you know that that isn't good news  
for stocks, because a restrictive policy puts the squeeze on 
economic growth and enhances the relative allure of 
interest-bearing securities that compete with stocks for investors' 
favor. 
</P>
<P>
	Likewise for high-yield bonds, which depend on an expanding  
economy. Ditto for government and other high-quality bonds, whose 
prices must decline when rates rise to keep their yields 
competitive with new bonds coming to market. 
</P>
<P>
	Bad news, also, for foreign stocks and bonds, even though  
central banks in other countries might not make policy moves 
parallel to those of the Fed. 
</P>
<P>
	Consider these current words from Barton Biggs, the widely  
respected global investment strategist at Morgan Stanley Dean 
Witter &AMP; Co.: ``I am reducing my exposure to equities not only in 
the U.S. but also in Europe and the emerging markets, because it is 
unrealistic to think they can buck the tide if the Dow and the S&AMP;P 
(U.S. market indexes) fade.'' 
</P>
<P>
	What's left to invest in? Very little except short-term  
money-market funds, whose yields, now ranging between 4.5 percent 
and 5 percent, stand to rise with a lag as short-term interest 
rates climb. 
</P>
<P>
	Nice, safe choice. Trouble is, money fund yields may not go up  
after all if the Fed decides not to tighten the screws. Even if it 
does nudge rates slightly higher, you still need to remember that 
money fund returns have historically lagged far behind both stocks 
and bonds over the long term. 
</P>
<P>
	And it's the long term you care about, isn't it? Not what the  
Fed might do, or not do, next. Besides, there is a way to hedge 
against near-term monetary and economic uncertainties that doesn't 
require that you try to outsmart the markets. 
</P>
<P>
	If you diversify your assets among stock, bond and money-market  
funds, you can smooth out the short-term bumps caused by 
adjustments in Fed policy. You don't eliminate risk, but you can 
cushion it. 
</P>
<P>
	Once you are set up that way, you may make little or no change  
in your portfolio thereafter even if analysts proclaim a major 
shift in the Fed's policy. The time to lighten up on stocks, or to 
shift some money from bonds to money funds, or to make any other 
strategic move, will come when changes in your own life dictate, 
rather than when some analysts say they think maybe the Fed seems 
to be saying so. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990611.0083 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-11 00:30:15 </DATE_TIME>
