<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-11 06:40:20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> political </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Lamar Alexander Defends Staff Cuts </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SACRAMENTO, Calif. (AP) -- GOP presidential hopeful Lamar  
Alexander says recent layoffs within his campaign were simply 
common sense shifts of resources. 
</P>
<P>
	``If we were a public company, our stock would have gone up,''  
he says. 
</P>
<P>
	In recent days Alexander has laid off his communications  
director, legal counsel and several support staffers. 
</P>
<P>
	``What we did was look down the road and save money so we'll  
have plenty for TV at the beginning of the year,'' he said in a 
telephone interview. ``And we put the money we have in the place 
where it will do the most good, and I think that's just smart.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The former Tennessee governor and U.S. education secretary has  
said he is moving campaign staff and infrastructure to Iowa, site 
of the first presidential caucus in the nation next year and of a 
straw poll this summer. 
</P>
<P>
	Aides said he drew campaign contributions in the ``low six  
figures'' during a brief California visit. 
</P>
<P>
	He lamented the Republican rush to embrace Texas Gov. George W.  
Bush as the presumptive nominee eight months before the Iowa 
caucus. 
</P>
<P>
	``He's got millions of dollars, huge name recognition, so he  
should be expected to win big,'' Alexander said, seeking to raise 
the expectations for the front-runner. ``If he doesn't, it will 
indicate that people have decided that they'd like to have a role 
in choosing the Republican nominee, and they don't want the 
political elite to tell them who to vote for.'' 
</P>
<P>
	California's GOP is considering eliminating its winner-take-all  
presidential primary, and some political observers have said the 
proposed change would help underdog candidates like Alexander. 
</P>
<P>
	Under a proposal to be considered by the party's executive  
committee June 19, the GOP primary would shift to a ``proportional 
system'' in which the delegates would be splintered by 
congressional district. 
</P>
<P>
	Instead of one candidate taking all the delegates, several could  
walk away with a chunk of them. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm generally of the belief there will be one of us coming  
into California with such a head of steam that he or she is likely 
to win the whole thing,'' Alexander said. 
</P>
<P>
	But, he said, ``It may help candidates who have less money,  
because those candidates can concentrate on individual districts.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990611.0085 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-11 14:40:20 </DATE_TIME>
