<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> AP Top News at Midnight EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NATO Forces Enter Kosovo  
</P>
<P>
	PRISTINA, Yugoslavia (AP) -- NATO peacekeepers began moving into  
Kosovo Saturday, just hours after a Russian armored column entered 
the capital in what Moscow officials called a mistake. NATO Chinook 
helicopters carrying British paratroopers flew across the border. 
The helicopters were to land troops on high ground along the 
Kacanik gorge overlooking the main road north to the Kosovo 
capital, Pristina, where Russian troops arrived hours earlier 
unexpectedly. Shortly after the allied helicopters flew into 
Kosovo, NATO vehicles began rolling into the province at Blace, 
Macedonia. 

</P>
<P>
	U.S., Russians Hold Troop Talks  
</P>
<P>
	MOSCOW (AP) -- Negotiators struggled Saturday to hammer out a  
compromise on how Russian troops will work with NATO peacekeepers. 
A column of Russian soldiers entered the province ahead of the 
alliance's forces. Russian Foreign Minister Igor Ivanov and U.S. 
Deputy Secretary of State Strobe Talbott met Friday and went to the 
Defense Ministry for further talks, a diplomat said on condition of 
anonymity. The talks were still under way at dawn Saturday. 

</P>
<P>
	First Lady Boosts Gephardt  
</P>
<P>
	ST. LOUIS (AP) -- Hillary Rodham Clinton spoke Friday night at a  
fund-raiser on behalf of House Minority Leader Dick Gephardt, heir 
to the speaker's chair if Democrats gain six more seats in November 
2000. Mrs. Clinton didn't mention her possible interest in the 
vacant U.S. Senate seat in New York. ``Whatever she does, she will 
make a mark,'' said Gephardt, who is in his 12th congressional term 
representing St. Louis. 

</P>
<P>
	Bush Launches Presidential Bid  
</P>
<P>
	CHICAGO (AP) -- Texas Gov. George W. Bush Friday launched his  
campaign for the Republican presidential nomination with two 
Midwest fund-raisers. ``See you in Iowa,'' he said after a private 
$1,000-a-plate luncheon at a Chicago hotel. Saturday, Bush visits 
Iowa, site of the nation's first caucuses. On Monday, he goes to 
New Hampshire, site of the first primary. 

</P>
<P>
	Man Opens Fire in Michigan, 3 Dead  
</P>
<P>
	SOUTHFIELD, Mich. (AP) -- A gunman opened fire on his former  
psychiatrist Friday, killing the doctor and another person before 
fatally shooting himself, authorities said. Four other people were 
wounded in the shooting at the office of Dr. Reuven Bar-Levav, who 
died on the 12th floor of a building in this Detroit suburb. The 
name of the gunman -- and the third victim slain, a woman from the 
Detroit area -- was being withheld. 

</P>
<P>
	Online Auctioneer eBay Fixes Site  
</P>
<P>
	SAN JOSE, Calif. (AP) -- The online auction house eBay fixed its  
site Friday night after a computer crash forced it to suspend 
bidding, frustrating millions of customers of one of the hottest 
Internet businesses. The halt came after eBay tried to launch a 
revamped version of its Web site. Its computer server went down 
last night and was up again Friday night. The shutdown disrupted 
bidding on millions of items. 

</P>
<P>
	Dow Ends Down 130.76  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Stocks fell sharply Friday after a tame  
inflation report failed to temper worry that the Federal Reserve 
will hike interest rates. The Dow industrials ended down 130.76 at 
10,490.51. On the NYSE, losers led gainers 1,712-1,304. The Nasdaq 
fell 36.74 points to 2,447.88. 

</P>
<P>
	Actor DeForest Kelley Dies at 79  
</P>
<P>
	LOS ANGELES (AP) -- Actor DeForest Kelley, who played crusty Dr.  
Leonard ``Bones'' McCoy on ``Star Trek,'' died Friday. He was 79. 
Kelley died after an extended illness, said the Motion Picture and 
Television Country Home and Hospital. ``DeForest Kelley was a 
Southern gentleman all of his life -- a kind, good, wonderful 
friend,'' said William Shatner, who played the show's lead 
character Capt. James T. Kirk. ``I will miss him.'' 

</P>
<P>
	Knicks Reach NBA Finals  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- The New York Knicks defeated the Indiana Pacers  
90-82 in Game 6 of the NBA Eastern Conference title series. The 
Knicks will face San Antonio in the NBA Finals. For the Knicks, 
Allan Houston had one of the best offensive games of his career, 
Marcus Camby, Latrell Sprewell and Chris Childs made several clutch 
plays. New York's Larry Johnson sprained a knee ligament and had to 
be carried off the court. 

</P>
<P>
	Magic's Hardaway To Be Free Agent  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Four-time NBA all-star Penny Hardaway exercised  
an option to void the last three years of his contract with the 
Orlando Magic and will become a free agent on July 1. Orlando 
general manager John Gabriel said, ``We would like to re-sign 
him.'' Hardaway, who averaged 15.8 points, 5.7 rebounds and 5.3 
assists this season, complained after the team's early playoff exit 
that he was underappreciated. 

</P>
<P>
	AP NewsBrief by HOWARD SINER  
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
