<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Spain's CASA, Germany's DASA Merging </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MADRID, Spain (AP) -- DaimlerChrysler Aerospace AG and Spain's  
state-owned Construcciones Aeronauticas SA have signed an agreement 
of understanding to merge into Europe's first multinational 
aerospace company. 
</P>
<P>
	The new company, expected to be created by midsummer, will have  
annual revenue of more than $11 billion and a work force of 53,000 
people, the two firms said Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	CASA had been courted by a number of European space groups. Just  
this week the newly merged French aerospace and defense group 
Aerospatiale Matra said it was interested in bidding for CASA. 
</P>
<P>
	Pedro Ferreras, president of SEPI, the Spanish state holding  
company that owns CASA, said Friday's agreement ``wasn't made 
against anyone.'' Rather, SEPI studied all the offers and bids and 
chose the most profitable one, he said. 
</P>
<P>
	The merger will be carried out through a stock swap, with DASA  
controlling an 85 percent stake in the new company and CASA 15 
percent. They have yet to decide on a name for it. 
</P>
<P>
	``The aim of the merger is clear,'' Manfred Bischoff, president  
and chief executive officer of DASA, said at a news conference. 
``We will strengthen our competitiveness by combining our 
complementary activities. And together we will continue to 
contribute to the restructuring of our industry in Europe.'' 
</P>
<P>
	A spokesman for British Aerospace, which has long advocated  
consolidation in Europe's aerospace and defense industries and had 
expressed interest in CASA, said: ``I suppose we are disappointed 
in some way.'' 
</P>
<P>
	But he said the merger does not put BAe at a disadvantage. ``We  
view this as another step in the consolidation process.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
