<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-11 18:20:17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Online Auctioneer eBay Fixes Site </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SAN JOSE, Calif. (AP) -- A computer crash forced the online  
auction house eBay to suspend all bidding, frustrating millions of 
customers of one of the hottest businesses on both the Internet and 
Wall Street. 
</P>
<P>
	The halt came after eBay tried to launch a revamped version of  
its Web site. The computer server went down Thursday night and was 
up again Friday night. The shutdown disrupted bidding on millions 
of collectibles and curios. 
</P>
<P>
	``We do realize how frustrating this is and we are doing our  
best to ensure that the system is restored as quickly and 
efficiently as humanly possible,'' eBay spokesman Kevin Pursglove 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	MarGee Charlier of Kewaunee, Wis., who sells 50 to 100 antiques  
each day through eBay, said she knew her business was in trouble 
when she logged in first thing Friday morning and saw that it had 
crashed. 
</P>
<P>
	``Devastation,'' she said.  
</P>
<P>
	EBay is the world's largest online auction site, with more than  
2 million items listed at any time. In an average minute on eBay, 
more than 150 new items are listed, 500 bids are placed and seven 
new people register. Its Web site receives more than 600 million 
hits a month. 
</P>
<P>
	Visitors to the Web site Friday got a continuing stream of  
updates and apologies from management. 
</P>
<P>
	Bidding was stopped Thursday around 11 p.m. EDT. While eBay  
initially said the site would be back up Friday afternoon, it did 
not become operational until about 8:30 p.m. EDT. Pursglove said it 
would take several hours to return to full service. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is frustrating,'' said Sharon Doney in Severn, Md., who  
is trying to raise $250,000 through online auctions of records and 
books to cover medical bills for her failing liver. ``Say you were 
at a real auction and the auctioneer just walked away for a while. 
It just doesn't work.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Doney said that problems on eBay -- short crashes, slowdowns and  
postponed auction endings -- during the past few months have already 
led her to got to other auction sites, including Amazon.com and 
Yahoo! 
</P>
<P>
	One of eBay's worst previous outages, which lasted about six  
hours, prevented the company from holding auctions of just-released 
merchandise tied to the latest ``Star Wars'' movie. 
</P>
<P>
	The latest outage was unrelated to the computer virus that began  
infecting systems across the country this week. 
</P>
<P>
	EBay has struggled to keep up with a huge surge in demand.  
Registered users went from 1.2 million last fall to 3.8 million as 
of March 31. 
</P>
<P>
	Those users bought and sold more than $541 million in  
merchandise through 22.9 million transactions during the first 
quarter of this year. EBay makes its money by taking a percentage 
on each sale. 
</P>
<P>
	For the first quarter of its fiscal year, eBay reported a  
quarterly profit of $5.9 million, making it one of the few 
consistently profitable Internet companies. 
</P>
<P>
	EBay stock has been traded publicly since September. Its stock  
had rocketed from $8.43 3/4 a share to $234 by April, but has since 
fallen by more than 20 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	News of the site outage sent shares tumbling more than 9 percent  
Friday. Ebay closed down $16.81 1/4 at $165.87 1/2 on the Nasdaq Stock 
Market. 
</P>
<P>
	Andrew Bartels, senior research analyst at Cambridge,  
Mass.-based Giga Information Group, said outages should be 
expected. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's actually not that big of a deal,'' he said. ``This is  
still new technology and these high transaction sites will 
periodically go down.'' 



  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
