<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Oil Prices Fall on Weak Demand </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LONDON (AP) -- Weaker global demand for oil offset production  
cuts by oil exporters, causing the price of crude to drop last 
month by more than $2 per barrel, the International Energy Agency 
reported Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	Oil inventories fell more slowly than expected, even though  
compliance with agreed production cuts by oil-producing countries 
improved to 90 percent from April's level of 82 percent, the agency 
said in a report faxed from its Paris headquarters. 
</P>
<P>
	Global crude production fell last month by 400,000 barrels per  
day to a new total of 73 million barrels per day. 
</P>
<P>
	However, a decline in seasonal demand for heating oil and other  
products together with uninterrupted exports from Iraq helped 
depress prices. OPEC's benchmark price for a barrel of crude 
dropped to $12.66 a barrel in May from $15 in April, the IEA said. 
</P>
<P>
	Last month's price decrease followed a $7 per barrel run-up  
during the previous 2 1/2 months. That earlier price jump resulted 
from an agreement by OPEC members and other producers to slash 
production by 2.1 million barrels per day in an effort to boost 
prices. 
</P>
<P>
	The IEA forecast that global demand for oil would rise this year  
to an average of 75 million barrels per day, an increase of 1.4 
percent above 1998. Much of the reason would be continued economic 
recovery in Asia, particularly in Japan and South Korea, it said. 
</P>
<P>
	Among OPEC's 11 members, only Nigeria, Kuwait and Algeria  
increased production in May, the IEA reported. 
</P>
<P>
	The IEA is part of the Organization for Economic Cooperation and  
Development, a group of the world' most developed nations. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
