<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Pentagon OKs Landing Gear Merger </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The military won't buy some sensitive  
equipment from foreign companies, but doesn't mind going overseas 
for aircraft landing gear, a Pentagon official told a Senate panel 
Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	``It was our conclusion that this was not a security problem,''  
Dave Oliver, the Defense Department's principal deputy 
undersecretary for acquisitions and technology, told the Senate 
Judiciary antitrust subcommittee. 
</P>
<P>
	Responding to concerns that the proposed merger of BFGoodrich  
Co. and Coltec Industries would leave just two choices for the 
essential aircraft component, one American and one French, Oliver 
said the consolidation of the U.S. firms would not change the 
market share of Messier-Dowty, the French company. 
</P>
<P>
	``They have 50 percent of the market for military planes and  
they would have 50 percent after this,'' he said, declining to 
answer some of the subcommittee's questions in order to avoid 
saying anything that might influence a court case challenging the 
proposed merger. 
</P>
<P>
	Oliver said the Pentagon would keep an eye on the merged company  
and take steps to combat any anti-competitive practices, but Alan 
Reuther of the United Auto Workers called that too little, too 
late. 
</P>
<P>
	Sen. Mike DeWine, R-Ohio, chairman of the subcommittee, said he  
was frustrated with the answers he got from Oliver and with 
BFGoodrich, which refused to state outright whether it intends to 
shut down its Cleveland landing gear operation. 
</P>
<P>
	BFGoodrich's general counsel, Terrence G. Linnert, said no plan  
for the Cleveland facility could be made until after the company 
sees all available data on Coltec's operations. 
</P>
<P>
	Richfield, Ohio-based BFGoodrich and Charlotte, N.C.-based  
Coltec want to merge their operations and form the world's largest 
manufacturer of aircraft landing gear. 
</P>
<P>
	BFGoodrich makes landing gear in Cleveland and in Tullahoma,  
Tenn. Coltec's Menasco Aerospace arm makes landing gear in Euless, 
Texas; Everett, Wash.; and Oakville, Ontario, Canada. 
</P>
<P>
	The merger has the approval of the Defense Department and the  
Federal Trade Commission but has been on hold because of a court 
order in Indiana, where a federal court is considering complaints 
from a potentially affected company, Allied Signal Aircraft Landing 
Systems. 
</P>
<P>
	BFGoodrich has about 20 percent of the worldwide landing gear  
market, according to the industry reference, Jane's Aircraft 
Component Manufacturers. Coltec's Menasco has about 25 percent. The 
leader, Messier-Dowty of France, has about 35 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	The U.S. military already buys about half of its landing gear  
from Messier-Dowty. 

  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
