<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> NATO Troops Await Kosovo Orders </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BLACE, Macedonia (AP) -- British paratroopers camped along  
Macedonia's border today awaiting orders to enter Kosovo as Serb 
troops continued their pullout. A Russian convoy stationed in 
Bosnia headed toward Kosovo, intensifying the debate about Moscow's 
role in the peacekeeping force. 
</P>
<P>
	Vice President Gore said Russia has given the allies assurances  
that none of its soldiers will enter Kosovo, a day after NATO 
suspended its 78-day Yugoslav air war and readied a 50-000-strong 
international peacekeeping force to take up positions inside the 
southern Serb province. 
</P>
<P>
	Russian peacekeeping forces based in Bosnia since that war ended  
in 1995 were seen headed toward the province. An AP photographer 
saw a convoy in Ruma, a Serbian town about 35 miles west of 
Belgrade, with vehicles flying Russian flags. 
</P>
<P>
	The independent Beta news agency reported that a convoy of  
Russian troops -- up to 1,000 forces -- in armored vehicles and 
trucks crossed over from Bosnia into Serbia. 
</P>
<P>
	The Russian vehicles were seen with what appeared to be hastily  
drawn KFOR markings, the insignia of the Kosovo peacekeeping force 
waiting along Macedonian borders to enter the southern Serb 
province. 
</P>
<P>
	The convoy passed through Belgrade today and was last seen on  
the southbound highway headed toward Nis, near Kosovo's border. 
</P>
<P>
	The convoy, headed by a Yugoslav government car, contained more  
than 50 vehicles flying the Russian colors and displaying KFOR 
markings. 
</P>
<P>
	Secretary of State Madeleine Albright expressed surprise when  
she arrived in Macedonia and heard about the Russian troop 
movement. 
</P>
<P>
	But she received assurances from Russian Foreign Minister Igor  
Ivanov that the troop movement was just a preliminary step and the 
Russians would not deploy into Kosovo until arrangements were 
worked out, her spokesman James P. Rubin said. 
</P>
<P>
	Albright, told of the movement by British Lt. Gen. Michael  
Jackson, commander of NATO troops in Macedonia, ordered Deputy 
Secretary of State Strobe Talbott to return to Moscow immediately. 
</P>
<P>
	Talbott, who had been in Moscow discussing ticklish arrangements  
for the participation of the Russians in the peacekeeping force, 
had been en route to Brussels. 
</P>
<P>
	Hours after the Russians crossed over from Bosnia, NATO  
spokesman Maj. David Scanlon said up to 200 Russian soldiers headed 
toward Kosovo would return to Bosnia after preparing for the 
arrival of a more permanent Russian peacekeeping contingent. 
</P>
<P>
	He said the Russian move ``was not unexpected.''  
</P>
<P>
	``The Russian commander was ordered through his chain of command  
to deploy an advance party ... to prepare for the arrival of the 
Russian contribution to the international peacekeeping force in 
Kosovo,'' he said in Sarajevo. 
</P>
<P>
	Some Western officials suggested the Russians had caught them  
off guard. 
</P>
<P>
	But Gore told Cable News Network: ``We've been given absolute  
assurances they will not move into Kosovo.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The development came amid continuing debate about Russian  
participation in any Kosovo peace force. The Russians -- 
particularly senior officers -- insist they will not put their 
troops under NATO command, something NATO has insisted on. 
</P>
<P>
	Meanwhile, the entry of the first NATO troops into Kosovo from  
neighboring Macedonia, originally expected today, was pushed back, 
possibly as much as 24 hours, NATO sources said. They did not 
specify the cause of the delay. 
</P>
<P>
	British paratroopers, the spearhead of the international force  
that will eventually number 50,000, camped along the border, 
preparing to move into Kosovo, to be followed by French and other 
NATO forces. Up to 7,000 U.S. troops are to take part in the 
peacekeeping force. 
</P>
<P>
	NATO and Yugoslav liaison officers were trying to coordinate  
movements in a complicated plan that calls for peacekeepers to move 
into designated areas as soon as Serb-led forces pull out. 
</P>
<P>
	Yugoslav troops began their pullback from Kosovo on Thursday,  
prompting NATO to suspend its air campaign, which started March 24. 
The U.N. Security Council then authorized a heavily armed security 
force to enter Kosovo to restore peace and begin reconstruction. 
</P>
<P>
	The Yugoslav withdrawal continued today. In Prokuplje, cheering  
residents threw flowers onto several dozen Yugoslav army vehicles 
heading northward. 
</P>
<P>
	In Brussels, NATO said 4,000 Serb military personnel had left  
Kosovo by today. 
</P>
<P>
	Citing unidentified sources, The New York Times reported today  
that U.S. and NATO officials envision Kosovo will become an 
international protectorate and could gain independence after a few 
years. Yugoslavia has deeply opposed both scenarios. 
</P>
<P>
	Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic proclaimed victory  
Thursday, despite the death and destruction wreaked by the air 
campaign and the imminent arrival of a huge foreign force on 
Yugoslav soil. 
</P>
<P>
	In Washington, President Clinton declared victory too and warned  
Milosevic that airstrikes would resume if he reneges on a peace 
deal to allow more than 860,000 ethnic Albanian refugees to return 
to Kosovo. Most fled to Macedonia and Albania. 
</P>
<P>
	Earlier today, Albright met with Lt. Gen. Jackson, commander of  
NATO troops in Macedonia, and was then taken to Camp Able Sentry, a 
base for U.S. troops preparing to go into Kosovo. 
</P>
<P>
	``We will have to do some winterizing of the tents in the  
camps,'' Albright said. ``We can't count on everyone getting back 
before the weather.'' 
</P>
<P>
	At the same time, Albright said, investigators, possibly  
including the FBI, want to get to Kosovo as quickly as possible 
before evidence of atrocities is destroyed. 
</P>
<P>
	Kosovo is in southern Serbia, the dominant republic in  
Yugoslavia. Although Serbs regard it as the heartland of their 
nation, its prewar population of 2.1 million was 90 percent ethnic 
Albanian. 
</P>
<P>
	The crisis began in February 1998 when Milosevic cracked down on  
the rebellious Kosovo Liberation Army. NATO began bombing 
Yugoslavia after Milosevic refused to sign a peace agreement 
crafted in Rambouillet, France. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
