<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Panel OKs Tariff on Japan Steel </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Domestic steel producers are calling a U.S.  
panel's approval of punitive tariffs against low-priced Japanese 
shipments a vindication for their claims of injury. 
</P>
<P>
	The U.S. International Trade Commission approved tariffs ranging  
from 18 percent to 67 percent on Japanese hot-rolled carbon steel, 
the industry's main product. 
</P>
<P>
	Those tariffs, to be imposed within weeks and made retroactive  
to February, will make Japanese steel more expensive to sell in the 
United States. 
</P>
<P>
	Although domestic producers do not consider tariffs to be a  
cure-all, they portrayed the commission's 6-0 vote Friday as a 
recognition of their plight. The U.S. industry blames low-priced 
imports for thousands of layoffs. 
</P>
<P>
	``The ruling should silence our critics who have portrayed the  
domestic steel industry as antiquated, whining protectionists,'' 
said Richard K. Riederer, president and chief executive of Weirton 
Steel Corp. 
</P>
<P>
	The trade commission determined that Japanese pricing practices,  
already deemed illegal by the Commerce Department, have or could 
hurt domestic producers. Tariffs approved Friday are likely to be 
in place for at least five years. 
</P>
<P>
	The U.S. industry will now turn its attention to the Senate,  
which is expected later this month to consider two bills designed 
to help domestic producers. One would create a $1 billion loan 
fund, and the other would impose global steel quotas. 
</P>
<P>
	The House overwhelmingly passed a quota bill in March by a  
289-141 vote, despite the threat of a presidential veto. Unlike 
tariffs, quotas apply to all countries and all products at once. 
</P>
<P>
	``This (tariff) determination is another good step toward ending  
the flood of illegal imports,'' said Rep. Pete Visclosky, D-Ind., 
chief sponsor of the House quota bill. ``However, this 
determination does not go far enough.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Japanese steel producers blamed politics for the ruling.  
</P>
<P>
	``We are disappointed that a majority of the commissioners,  
facing overwhelming political pressure, ignored the facts and 
imposed long-term restrictions on hot-rolled steel imports,'' said 
Hidenori Tazawa, executive vice president for NKK America Inc. 
</P>
<P>
	He said the tariffs ``will raise prices and limit supply  
availability and choice for U.S. steel users.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Another executive, Masaki Sato of Nippon Steel U.S.A. Inc., said  
earlier that his company is likely to appeal to the U.S. Court of 
International Trade in New York. The court handles disputed cases 
from the trade commission, a fact-finding agency independent from 
the administration. 
</P>
<P>
	Hot-rolled steel can be used as is in such applications as  
construction or turned into higher-grade products for appliances or 
automobiles. 
</P>
<P>
	Japanese hot-rolled shipments already have gone down to almost  
insignificant levels, partly because of the threat of tariffs, so 
Friday's vote was mostly about sustaining those reductions. 
</P>
<P>
	Paradoxically, a rejection of tariffs would probably have  
boosted support in the Senate for import quotas. 
</P>
<P>
	``The recognition that existing protectionist mechanisms are  
doing their job may undermine the case for additional 
protections,'' said Brink Lindsey, director of the Center for Trade 
Policy Studies at the Cato Institute. 
</P>
<P>
	Imports surged last year in the wake of the Asian economic  
crisis, which lowered demand for steel abroad and forced foreign 
producers to turn to the healthier U.S. economy. 
</P>
<P>
	The U.S. industry accused Japanese, Russian and Brazilian  
producers of illegally dumping hot-rolled steel in the United 
States at prices below production costs or home-market prices. 
</P>
<P>
	The Clinton administration has tentatively struck deals with  
Russia and Brazil in which those countries could avoid tariffs by 
voluntarily reducing steel shipments. 
</P>
<P>
	The foreign producers argued that the pricing trends result from  
normal market forces. They added that the U.S. industry's claims of 
harm were exaggerated because profitability and production declines 
last year followed one of the industry's best years ever. 

  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
