<DOCNO> APW19990611.0102 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-11 17:30:12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> IRL Ready To Race With New Rules </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	FORT WORTH, Texas (AP) -- Indy Racing League drivers say they  
hope the excitement level remains high for Saturday's Longhorn 500, 
even though speeds will be lower. 
</P>
<P>
	Twenty-six drivers will compete in the third annual race at  
Texas Motor Speedway. 
</P>
<P>
	The IRL has decided to control speeds slightly by lowering  
maximum rpms from 10,300 to 10,000, beginning this weekend. The 
change was made as part of an effort to decrease the likelihood of 
a crash at TMS, which features a high-banked oval track. 
</P>
<P>
	In the last IRL race on a high-banked oval, three spectators  
were killed by flying debris in Concord, N.C., on May 1. 
</P>
<P>
	But even though race officials expect speeds to be at least 3  
mph below normal Saturday, the change hasn't seemed to dilute the 
enthusiasm surrounding the event. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're flying the whole way around, we never let off the gas  
and we can easily be two or three abreast,'' said Scott Sharp, who 
placed second in qualifying Thursday with an average speed of 
214.839 mph. ``So it's one of the most exciting races we 
participate in.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Mark Dismore will hold the pole position Saturday, thanks to his  
qualifying speed of 215.272 mph. Dismore was forced to use a backup 
car to narrowly beat out Sharp, his Kelly Racing teammate, for the 
top spot. 
</P>
<P>
	The rest of the top five positions for Saturday's race are  
filled out by Tyce Carlson, Greg Ray and Eddie Cheever, Jr. 
Defending Longhorn 500 champion Billy Boat will start in the 11th 
spot. 
</P>
<P>
	The 208-lap race is the fifth in the IRL's 11-race season, and  
drivers say they have noticed the league has become more popular. 
</P>
<P>
	``The series is gaining support and it's gaining momentum,''  
Dismore said. ``It's definitely becoming a stand-alone series.'' 
</P>
<P>
	TMS is a 1.5-mile quad-oval with 24-degree banked turn, similar  
to the track at Concord and Atlanta Motor Speedway, which was built 
for heavier and slower stock cars. IRL races have been staged at 
TMS and Concord since 1997 and at Atlanta since 1998. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
