<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Brewers Retire Molitor's No. 4 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MILWAUKEE (AP) -- Paul Molitor, who spent the first 15 years of  
his career with Milwaukee, saw his No. 4 uniform retired by the 
Brewers on Friday night to fans' cheers of ``Paulie, Paulie, 
Paulie.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The only other Brewers to have their jerseys retired are Hank  
Aaron (44), Robin Yount (19) and Rollie Fingers (34). 
</P>
<P>
	Molitor was greeted with a long standing ovation and told the  
crowd that if elected to the Hall of Fame, ``I'll be proud to go in 
as a Brewer.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``I've been embraced by the fans here, and I want to thank you  
from the bottom of my heart for that,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	In his 21-year career, which ended last season, Molitor hit .306  
with 3,319 hits, eighth on the career list. He was a five-time 
All-Star. 
</P>
<P>
	Molitor was with the Brewers from 1978-92. He is now a part-time  
broadcaster for the Minnesota Twins but said he would like to get 
more involved in ``terms of teaching or shaping'' young players for 
a team. 
</P>
<P>
	Although there was some ill feeling when he left the Brewers as  
a free agent in 1993, and again in 1996 when he chose to play for 
the Twins instead of returning to Milwaukee, Molitor said he could 
return to the Brewers one day. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'd be foolish to close the doors on any avenues in this  
game,'' he said. ``I would say the door's open.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Molitor said many of his fondest memories are from his years as  
a Brewer, especially the friendships he made with Yount and Jim 
Gantner, both of whom spoke at the ceremony. 
</P>
<P>
	``When I talk about a specific year, '82 is the one that sticks  
out, believe me,'' he said, referring to the year the Brewers won 
the AL pennant and lost a seven-game World Series to St. Louis. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
