<DOCNO> APW19990611.0110 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-11 00:50:15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> New Air Bags May Fail Crash Test </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- General Motors, Ford Motor and DaimlerChrysler  
say their latest, less forceful air bags -- designed to reduce 
injuries to children and small adults -- won't be able to pass a 
proposed government crash test standard that the automakers believe 
is too tough. 
</P>
<P>
	The National Highway Traffic Safety Administration has proposed  
reinstating a crash test standard that requires an air bag to 
cushion an unbelted dummy when a vehicle is smashed into a wall at 
30 mph. Federal safety officials believe the test will ensure that 
air bags are protecting adults who are not wearing seat belts in 
higher-speed crashes. 
</P>
<P>
	Automakers already must comply with a 30 mph vehicle crash test  
into a wall using dummies wearing seat belts, and they believe that 
test is necessary. 
</P>
<P>
	But Robert Lange, director of engineering safety for General  
Motors Corp., on Thursday called the test for unbelted dummies ``an 
extremely severe test'' that could force automakers into air bag 
designs that are not as safe for smaller passengers. 
</P>
<P>
	In the real world, the test into an unmoving barrier translates  
into the unbelted driver of, for example, a Toyota Camry ramming 
the back of a parked Toyota Camry at 60 mph, or two Camrys hitting 
each other head-on with each car traveling at 30 mph. 
</P>
<P>
	To meet the unbelted test, the automakers argue, they will have  
to make air bags more powerful again and run the risk that children 
and short adults will be injured. Air bags have been blamed for 135 
deaths -- mostly of children and shorter women -- in low-speed 
accidents the victims otherwise should have survived, according to 
government statistics. 
</P>
<P>
	Starting in 1997, the nation's three largest automakers  
installed air bags with 25 percent to 35 percent less force, and 
they believe the less powerful air bags are doing a good job 
protecting adults in severe crashes. 
</P>
<P>
	The agency's proposed 30 mph unbelted test ``would simply take  
us back to where we were before, and we know we don't like that 
outcome,'' Lange said. 
</P>
<P>
	``If we add too much energy (to the air bag), we create the  
potential to severely injure people who would have been essentially 
injury-free,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	GM officials said they ran the 30 mph unbelted test with one of  
their vehicles and the newer, less powerful air bag failed to 
cushion the unbelted crash dummy adequately. A Ford Motor Co. 
official said Ford performed similar tests with the same result. 
DaimlerChrysler has said for months its less-powerful air bags on 
Chrysler and Dodge vehicles could fail the proposed government 
standard. 
</P>
<P>
	The government is not convinced that automakers need to add more  
power to air bags to comply with the 30 mph unbelted test, which 
was a government standard until early 1997. 
</P>
<P>
	The standard was created at a time when belt use was around 15  
percent. Now it is around 70 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	The test ``is necessary to ensure protection for people in the  
real world in the most difficult crashes,'' said NHTSA spokesman 
Rae Tyson. 
</P>
<P>
	NHTSA has tested 12 vehicles with redesigned air bags and found  
that only two of those would not have met the test standard, a 1998 
Dodge Neon and a 1999 Acura RL. The agency also said in a statement 
that the tests showed ``manufacturer redesign of air bags has 
resulted in slightly reduced protection of large adults.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Government data shows less than 1 percent of crashes involve a  
change of speed of 30 mph or greater. 

  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
