<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Steel Cos. Face Last Tariff Hurdle </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- U.S. steel producers struggling from last  
year's surge in low-priced imports are looking beyond a crucial 
International Trade Commission ruling for an end to their plight. 
</P>
<P>
	The ITC was voting today on U.S. tariffs against Japan on  
hot-rolled carbon steel, the industry's leading product. If 
approved, the Clinton administration would order tariffs of as much 
as 67 percent within weeks. 
</P>
<P>
	But hot-rolled shipments from Japan already have declined,  
partly because of the threat of tariffs, which make imports more 
expensive. Today's ruling would not apply to other steel products 
or to other countries. 
</P>
<P>
	``Certainly a ruling (for tariffs) would have a positive impact,  
but the key here is that this situation has not ended,'' said 
William Klinefelter, Washington representative of the United 
Steelworkers of America union. 
</P>
<P>
	The U.S. industry has been pushing for stronger sanctions, such  
as quotas covering all steel products from all countries, to help 
combat imports that it blames for thousands of layoffs and 
bankruptcies at three U.S. companies. 
</P>
<P>
	Supporters are hoping for a Senate vote on quotas later this  
month. The House passed the measure in March by a 289-141 vote, 
despite the threat of a presidential veto. 
</P>
<P>
	The question before the commission was whether domestic industry  
is hurt by Japanese pricing practices already deemed illegal by the 
Commerce Department. Tariffs would be imposed if the commission 
finds actual or threatened injury. 
</P>
<P>
	Rejection of tariffs could prompt imports to rise and could  
encourage more shipments from other countries that had been looking 
for signs of what practices are permissible. A rejection also could 
boost support in Congress for global quotas. 
</P>
<P>
	Masaki Sato, president and chief executive for Nippon Steel  
U.S.A. Inc., said any attempt to restrict imports would be 
``unjustified, ill-conceived and counterproductive'' and would hurt 
U.S. steel consumers as well as Japanese producers. 
</P>
<P>
	The U.S. industry accused Japanese, Russian and Brazilian  
producers of illegally dumping hot-rolled steel in the United 
States at prices below production costs or home-market prices. 
</P>
<P>
	The Clinton administration has tentatively struck deals with  
Russia and Brazil in which those countries could avoid tariffs by 
voluntarily reducing steel shipments. That leaves Japan as the 
remaining target, and the Commerce Department concurred with the 
industry's charges against Japan in April. 
</P>
<P>
	The foreign producers argued that the pricing trends result from  
normal market forces, including a General Motors strike that 
lowered demand for steel in the United States. 
</P>
<P>
	They also said the U.S. industry's claims of harm were  
exaggerated because any decline last year followed one of the 
industry's best years ever. 
</P>
<P>
	The Clinton administration has faced difficult choices about how  
exactly to respond to complaints from U.S. steel companies and 
workers' unions. The administration has preferred to let the trade 
complaints run their course and has been encouraged by signs of 
import reductions since November. 
</P>
<P>
	Hot-rolled shipments from Japan went down 98 percent to 7,428  
metric tons in April, compared with 405,974 in November. Although 
Japan was a leading source of imports before the U.S. industry 
filed trade complaints in September, the country accounted for less 
than 2 percent of all foreign hot-rolled steel in April. 

  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
