<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-11 14:20:19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Georgetown Academic Adviser Quits </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Now that John Thompson has quit as  
Georgetown's basketball coach, Mary Fenlon is leaving, too. 
</P>
<P>
	Fenlon, the team's tough-love academic adviser for 27 years, is  
retiring July 31. The announcement was made earlier this week at a 
university function. 
</P>
<P>
	Fenlon's retirement follows Thompson's sudden decision to resign  
for personal reasons in January. 
</P>
<P>
	Fenlon, a former nun, was the first person Thompson hired when  
he took over the struggling Hoyas program in 1972. She was also the 
person Thompson chose to accompany him when he visited possible 
recruits, and she kept a tight rein on the schedules and academic 
progress of the players. 
</P>
<P>
	Under Fenlon, 97 percent of the players who stayed four years  
received their degrees. 
</P>
<P>
	``She'd curse you out if you messed up,'' New York Knicks center  
and Georgetown alumnus Patrick Ewing once said. ``And if you needed 
a pat on the back, she'd pat you on the back. Mary is just a great 
lady.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Fenlon rarely granted interviews and was protective of the  
players, often making sure reporters did not stray beyond the 
school's strict coverage rules. 
</P>
<P>
	Fenlon sat on or near the bench for Georgetown's games, and she  
and Thompson often traveled together to watch NBA games featuring 
Ewing or other former Georgetown players. Earlier this year, The 
Washington Post revealed that Fenlon and Thompson had become 
business partners in various real estate investments in Las Vegas. 
</P>
<P>
	Thompson and Fenlon often haggled over how players should divide  
their time between schoolwork and practice. More than once, 
Thompson would get upset because Fenlon wouldn't approve a 
suggested practice time because too many of her students -- she did 
not call them ``players'' -- would have to miss class. 
</P>
<P>
	In an interview in 1996, Thompson explained his relationship  
with Fenlon. 
</P>
<P>
	``I made her promise me when I first came here, that I wanted  
these kids to graduate, and that I did not trust my own competitive 
instincts,'' Thompson said. ``My competitive instincts are to win, 
and I told her 'I'm going to be fighting you all the time about 
what I'm asking you to do.''' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990611.0120 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-11 11:20:13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> entertainment </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Lauryn Hill Visits Old High School </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MAPLEWOOD, N.J. (AP) -- When opportunity knocks, answer with open  
arms, hip-hop diva Lauryn Hill told students at her old high 
school. 
</P>
<P>
	``I want you all to know that there are vast opportunities you  
can tap into. You just have to believe in yourself and start to do 
it. Do what you have to, to increase your mind,'' the singer said 
at an unannounced appearance Thursday at Columbia High School to be 
inducted into its hall of fame. 
</P>
<P>
	Hill, who won five Grammys this year, delighted students with  
impromptu a cappella versions of her songs ``Doo Wop (That Thing)'' 
and ``Ex-Factor'' during assembly. 
</P>
<P>
	``She just touched me a lot,'' said teary-eyed Mara Ostfeld, 18.  
``She is just a great role model.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The 24-year-old former singer with the Fugees still lives in  
nearby South Orange with fiance Rohan Marley and her mother. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
