<DOCNO> APW19990611.0121 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-11 10:17:26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Russia Wants Own Kosovo Peace Area </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MOSCOW (AP) -- Russia dispatched a column of troops and armored  
vehicles to Yugoslavia today, and its foreign minister said the 
forces were preparing to enter Kosovo, even though their 
peacekeeping role was still being negotiated. 
</P>
<P>
	Foreign Minister Igor Ivanov did not say when the Russian forces  
might enter Kosovo, but stressed that none had done so yet. He 
described the Russian troop movement as ``preparatory actions'' to 
aid in peacekeeping. 
</P>
<P>
	Russian leaders have provided scant information about the  
movement of their troops, though Russian forces have traveled out 
of Bosnia and through the Yugoslav capital of Belgrade, heading 
south to Kosovo. 
</P>
<P>
	Vice President Gore and Secretary of State Madeleine Albright  
said they had received assurances from Moscow that no Russian 
forces would go into Kosovo until there was agreement on how the 
NATO and Russian forces would cooperate on the international 
peacekeeping force. 
</P>
<P>
	If Russian forces were to enter Kosovo before such an agreement,  
it could complicate efforts to establish the force in a unified 
manner. NATO says it will lead the force and will be present in all 
parts of Kosovo. The alliance is opposed to Moscow's idea of a 
special Russian sector, and does not want Russia unilaterally 
staking out its own territory in Kosovo. 
</P>
<P>
	Also, Russia is an ally of Yugoslavia, and ethnic Albanian  
refugees returning to Kosovo might be reluctant to move into an 
area dominated by Russian troops. 
</P>
<P>
	Russia and the United States held a second day of talks today to  
work out how NATO and Russian troops would work together in the 
50,000-strong peacekeeping force in Kosovo, which was authorized by 
the United Nations on Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	The talks broke up without agreement and Deputy Secretary of  
State Strobe Talbott flew out of Moscow. But when news broke about 
Russian troop movements toward Kosovo, Talbott returned for a new 
round of urgent talks. 
</P>
<P>
	The Interfax news agency, citing unidentified sources, claimed  
about 1,000 Russians would be leaving this afternoon and flying to 
cities in Kosovo, including the capital Pristina. The Russian units 
were already at military airfields and were waiting for orders to 
take off, a source told Interfax. 
</P>
<P>
	Ivanov said no Russia troops were yet in Kosovo. He did say,  
however, that ``active preparatory actions are taking place for the 
deployment of a (Russian) presence in Kosovo.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``Since the deployment of the international peacekeeping force  
in Kosovo may take place within days, a high degree of readiness is 
needed,'' Ivanov added. 
</P>
<P>
	An AP photographer in Yugoslavia saw a Russian convoy west of  
Belgrade. The independent Yugoslav news agency Beta reported that a 
convoy of Russian troops had crossed from Bosnia into Serbia en 
route to Kosovo. 
</P>
<P>
	The Russian vehicles were marked KFOR, the insignia of the  
Kosovo peacekeeping force. 
</P>
<P>
	Gore said he expected the Russians to stop short of Kosovo,  
telling the CNN: ``We've been given absolute assurances they will 
not move into Kosovo.'' 
</P>
<P>
	That suggested the Russians were moving close -- but not into --  
the province in preparation for a later deployment. 
</P>
<P>
	Russian leaders have said they are considering sending a total  
of 2,500 to 10,000 troops to Kosovo -- but they will not be placed 
under NATO command. 
</P>
<P>
	A Russian general said today that Moscow should be given its own  
peacekeeping sector in Kosovo, or else it would bypass NATO and 
work out its own arrangement with Yugoslavia. 
</P>
<P>
	``We don't intend to beg the American side to provide Russia  
with a relevant sector in Kosovo,'' said Russian Gen. Leonid 
Ivashov. If an agreement can't be reached, ``we will declare our 
sector and agree on this question with the Yugoslav side.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Russia was negotiating with the United States in part because  
President Boris Yeltsin suspended relations with NATO after its 
bombing campaign began in March. The Russian leader has endorsed 
the peace plan, but is not ready to restore ties with NATO. 
</P>
<P>
	``Relations between Russia and NATO ... remain frozen,'' Yeltsin  
said. ``We shall see later what happens.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
