<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> National Champs Lead Olympic Trials </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	FEDERAL WAY, Wash (AP) -- Anna Kozlova and Tuesday Middaugh held  
a slim edge over Olympians Heather Pease and Tammy Cleland-McGregor 
after Friday's first round of duet competition in the U.S. 
Synchronized Swimming Olympic Trials. 
</P>
<P>
	Kozlova and Middaugh, who won the national duet title this year,  
scored a 99 out of a possible 100 in the short program that 
accounts for 35 percent of the total duet score. Pease and 
Cleland-McGregor, the only two returnees from the American team 
that won the gold medal in the 1996 Olympics, had 98.733 points. 
The duo finished third in the nationals last month. 
</P>
<P>
	The winner earns the American spot in the 2000 Olympics at  
Sydney, Australia. 
</P>
<P>
	Carrie Barton and Elicia Marshall, who train at Santa Clara,  
were third with 97.467 points. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
