<DOCNO> APW19990611.0126 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-11 12:50:19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> New Twist to Smirnov Vs. Smirnoff </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- The Russian distillers of Smirnov vodka have  
appealed a federal court's dismissal of their $1 billion 
trademark-infringement lawsuit against the business that sells 
Smirnoff vodka in the United States. 
</P>
<P>
	A U.S. District Court judge in Wilmington, Del., had dismissed  
the lawsuit last month, saying the Russians had waited too long to 
make the claim and were not selling their vodka in the United 
States anyway. 
</P>
<P>
	An appeal was filed Thursday in the 3rd U.S. Circuit Court of  
Appeals in Philadelphia. 
</P>
<P>
	The appeal was filed on behalf of the Joint Stock Society, whose  
principal owners claim to be descendants of Piotr Smirnov, and its 
distributor, the Russian American Spirits Co. 
</P>
<P>
	Smirnov was the Russian distiller who first produced Smirnov  
vodka nearly 140 years ago. 
</P>
<P>
	The lawsuit is against UDV North America, the successor to  
Heublein Inc. and a part of the British beverage company Diageo 
PLC. UDV markets Smirnoff vodka -- Heublein adopted the French 
spelling of Smirnov -- in the U.S. and elsewhere. 
</P>
<P>
	Piotr Smirnov opened his vodka distillery in 1860 and passed it  
on to his five sons. His son Piotr eventually bought out his 
brothers' stakes. 
</P>
<P>
	But the company was nationalized after the 1917 Bolshevik  
revolution and the new government quit using the Smirnov name. 
</P>
<P>
	Another son, Vladimir, began making vodka under the family name  
in 1923, court documents said, but other members of the family 
never formally objected. 
</P>
<P>
	That business was eventually sold to Heublein in 1939.  
</P>
<P>
	Currently, Smirnoff vodka is the most popular brand of vodka in  
the United States, where about 6 million cases are sold each year. 
</P>
<P>
	The Joint Stock Society began contracting with Russian vodka  
makers five years ago to produce and sell vodka under the Smirnov 
name and filed the suit in 1995 for damages. 
</P>
<P>
	But Judge Gregory Sleet in Wilmington dismissed the suit on May  
13, citing the ``years of inaction'' by the Russians. He also said 
the Russians had not tried to sell their vodka in the United States 
and would not have a claim to financial damages until they did so. 
</P>
<P>
	Jack Shea, a spokesman for UDV North America, said the company  
is confident the court's decision will be upheld. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990611.0127 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-11 06:40:19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Dow Gains 15; Nasdaq Is Up 11 / Wall Street Report  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Stock prices have opened slightly higher. The  
Dow Jones industrial average is up 15 points in today's early 
going. Advancers on the New York Stock Exchange hold a 7-5 lead 
over decliners. 
</P>
<P>
	The Nasdaq Composite Index is up eleven points and the S&AMP;P 500  
Index is up two points. 
</P>
<P>
	Wall Street is taking the time to sort through a pair of  
economic reports released this morning. 
</P>
<P>
	The Commerce Department said retail sales jumped a surprisingly  
strong one percent in May. 
</P>
<P>
	And the Labor Department said producer prices edged up just 0.2  
percent last month. 
</P>
<P>
	A strong rise in inflation in April had put financial markets on  
notice for a possible interest rate rise by the Federal Reserve. 
</P>
<P>
	The Fed holds its next policy meeting later this month.  
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
