<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990611.0128 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-11 00:10:08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Labonte Likes Chances in Mich. Race </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BROOKLYN, Mich. (AP) -- Last week, Bobby Labonte won a pole with  
a borrowed set of shocks, and it led to his first Winston Cup 
victory of the season. 
</P>
<P>
	Now it's a new week, a new track and a different sort of  
challenge for Labonte and the Pontiac he drives for the Joe Gibbs 
team. Still, he was certain the car's setup would be the key in 
today's qualifying for Sunday's running of the NASCAR Kmart 400 at 
Michigan Speedway. 
</P>
<P>
	``You've got to get your car set up right here,'' Labonte said  
Thursday. ``That's the big thing, to get good power and a good 
setup. I'll tell you, we've been pretty fortunate, we've run pretty 
well every time we've been here.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Labonte, who won twice at this 2-mile banked oval in 1995, had  
been running fairly well all season for the Gibbs team. But he 
hadn't been winning. 
</P>
<P>
	Then it all came together last week when he drove the Pontiac to  
a victory at Dover, Del. 
</P>
<P>
	Now, he'd like to win at Michigan again.  
</P>
<P>
	``Well, confidence means a lot in racing, just like it does in  
other sports,'' Labonte said. ``We were able to build off past 
weeks to get to last week. 
</P>
<P>
	``There's nothing wrong with coming in to Michigan with a win  
last weekend, no matter where it was at.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The difference at Dover was a set of shocks Labonte borrowed  
from teammate Tony Stewart's car. 
</P>
<P>
	They worked so well that Labonte set a track record at Dover  
Downs International Speedway while earning the pole for the MBNA 
Platinum 400. 
</P>
<P>
	Like most smart NASCAR drivers, Labonte gives much of the credit  
to Jimmy Makar, his crew chief since 1995 when he joined the Gibbs 
team. 
</P>
<P>
	Besides setting the car up right, Makar also made a key call  
during the race that ultimately sealed the triumph. Makar brought 
in Labonte to top off his fuel tank just before the end of the 
final caution period on lap 293. 
</P>
<P>
	It was just enough to get him to the end.  
</P>
<P>
	``I don't like gas-mileage racing because you want to have the  
fastest car and run away,'' Labonte said. ``But it was a great call 
by Jimmy.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The decision cost Jeff Gordon the Dover race for the second  
straight year. He was forced to stop for a splash of gas with five 
laps remaining. 
</P>
<P>
	Labonte is hoping to win on pure power at the bigger, faster  
track in Michigan. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's one of those deals where we like coming to this track,''  
Labonte said. ``It seems like we've got a good setup for it and 
good combination for it between Jimmy Makar and myself.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Labonte heads into this weekend third in the Winston Cup point  
standings with 1,915. Dale Jarrett is first with 1,984 points and 
Jeff Burton, a three-time winner, has 1,933 points. 
</P>
<P>
	``We've been competitive week in and week out,'' Labonte said.  
``We've had some pretty decent finishes, and we haven't had too 
much bad luck. We hope we can keep it going.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Mark Martin, the defending champion in this race -- the 14th of  
34 this season -- is fourth in the standings with 1,854 points. 
Martin, after a career-best seven victories last year, has won just 
once this season. 
</P>
<P>
	Like Gordon, he could be in the right place to start making  
things happen. Martin, second to Gordon last season, has won four 
times at Michigan. 
</P>
<P>
	Labonte's teammate, Stewart, is fifth with 1,700 points. Last  
year's Winston Cup points champion, Jeff Gordon, is a distant sixth 
with 1,645 points. 
</P>
<P>
	Gordon, who has had a run of bad luck lately, won at Michigan  
last August. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990611.0129 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-11 09:10:26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Judge Considers Damages in SI Case </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NASHVILLE, Tenn. (AP) -- A federal judge is deciding whether  
Sports Illustrated alone is responsible for paying punitive damages 
for former boxer Randall ``Tex'' Cobb. 
</P>
<P>
	The issue is whether the magazine's parent, Time Inc., also can  
be held liable for the damages. 
</P>
<P>
	A jury has already awarded Cobb $8.5 million in compensatory  
damages as a result of his libel suit against the magazine. The 
jury was to begin determining punitive damages today. 
</P>
<P>
	U.S. District Judge Robert Echols heard arguments today over  
whether the damages should come from just Sports Illustrated or 
from its parent. 
</P>
<P>
	Sports Illustrated's attorneys told the judge the lawsuit was  
solely against Sports Illustrated, which has its own accounting 
division. 
</P>
<P>
	But Cobb's attorney said the magazine can not be separated from  
Time Inc. and that several of the parent company's resources were 
used in researching the story. 
</P>
<P>
	The jury must decide how much more the magazine should pay Cobb  
as punishment for a 1993 article that said the boxer fixed a fight 
and shared cocaine with the loser. 
</P>
<P>
	The jury awarded the compensatory damages Wednesday.  
</P>
<P>
	Cobb, 46, had asked for $50 million in compensatory damages and  
$100 million in punitive damages. Cobb, who declined to comment 
Thursday, has said the article ended his boxing career and nearly 
ended his acting career. 
</P>
<P>
	``Tex has been a prisoner of this article for six years and  
there's no better feeling in the world than to have a jury come in 
and set the record straight,'' Cobb's attorney, George Bochetto, 
said Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	An attorney for the magazine, Eddie Wayland, had no comment  
Thursday about the award. 
</P>
<P>
	Cobb sued in 1994 over an article headlined ``The Fix Was In.''  
The story began with an anecdote about the 1992 bout between Cobb 
and Sonny Barch, a journeyman fighter and former Memphis State 
football player. 
</P>
<P>
	The magazine reported that Cobb and Barch discussed how to throw  
the fight. The story said Cobb had an injured shoulder and wanted 
it to end as quickly as possible. 
</P>
<P>
	In the article, Barch said he told Cobb: ``I'm going to have to  
hit you to make it look good. But I won't hit your shoulder.'' 
Barch told Sports Illustrated that Cobb responded: ``Bubba, I 
appreciate it. I'll make it up to you.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Barch allowed Cobb to hit him three times, dropping to a knee  
each time and triggering the three-knockdown rule, Sports 
Illustrated reported. Cobb was declared the winner by technical 
knockout. 
</P>
<P>
	The magazine also reported that Barch said he, Cobb and a fight  
promoter shared cocaine after the bout. Sports Illustrated said 
Cobb had tested positive for cocaine use, but said in a follow-up 
item that it was marijuana. 
</P>
<P>
	Wayland told the jury that the article by writers William Nack  
and Sonja Steptoe was accurate and that any damage done to Cobb's 
reputation was the result of his own actions. 
</P>
<P>
	``They believed the story was true. They believed it then and  
they believe it now,'' Wayland said. 
</P>
<P>
	However, Ms. Steptoe testified last month she had little  
evidence that Cobb was a willing participant in a fixed fight with 
Barch. 
</P>
<P>
	Since he quit fighting, Cobb has had roles in several movies,  
including ``Liar, Liar, ``Raising Arizona,'' ``Uncommon Valor'' and 
``The Golden Child.'' He has also been in the TV shows 
``Moonlighting'' and ``MacGyver.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
