<DOCNO> APW19990611.0130 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-11 19:40:14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Villanova Gets Kentucky Transfer </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	VILLANOVA, Pa. (AP) -- Center Michael Bradley, who set a school  
record for field goal percentage at Kentucky last season, has 
transferred to Villanova, the school announced Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	The 6-foot-10 Bradley, a native of Worcester, Mass., started all  
37 games at Kentucky as a sophomore last season, averaging 9.8 
points and 4.9 rebounds in 21.9 minutes. He shot 65.7 percent from 
the field as the Wildcats finished 28-9, falling one game short of 
a fourth straight Final Four appearance. 
</P>
<P>
	He announced his decision to transfer on April 29, and on Friday  
made it official that he will play for Villanova. He will sit out 
the 1999-2000 season, then have two years' eligibility remaining. 
</P>
<P>
	Bradley had originally decided to attend Boston College, like  
Villanova a member of the Big East, out of high school. He signed 
with Kentucky, a member of the Southeastern Conference, after 
then-Boston College coach Jim O'Brien resigned over a flap with the 
school's administration concerning admissions. 
</P>
<P>
	Villanova finished 21-11 last season, losing to Mississippi in  
the opening round of the NCAA tournament. 
</P>
<P>
	``We feel Michael's skills fit in perfectly with our style of  
basketball,'' Villanova coach Steve Lappas said Friday night. 
``There is no doubt we are looking forward to the time when Michael 
becomes eligible to play for us.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
