<DOCNO> APW19990611.0132 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-11 11:20:13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton Won't Get Honorary Degree </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CHICAGO (AP) -- No offense, University of Chicago officials say,  
but President Clinton won't get an honorary degree for speaking to 
graduates Saturday. 
</P>
<P>
	He doesn't even qualify to give the commencement address.  
Instead, he will be the ``distinguished guest speaker.'' 
</P>
<P>
	University officials said it has nothing to do with the  
president and everything to do with strict tradition at this very 
serious institution, where more Nobel laureates -- 70 in all -- have 
taught, researched or studied than anywhere else in the world. 
</P>
<P>
	Rules at the 108-year-old school allow only faculty members to  
give the commencement address and only leading academic scholars 
get honorary degrees. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is not a snub to either the office of the president or  
President Clinton,'' university spokesman Larry Arbeiter said. 
``Other elite universities will give honorary degrees to 
entertainers or sports figures, but we don't do it. We are a bit 
more restrictive.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The university also rejected a proposal to give Queen Elizabeth  
II an honorary law degree when she visited in 1959. 
</P>
<P>
	``Their response was, `Of course we would be happy to consider  
the Queen of England. Please submit to us a list of her scholarly 
publications,''' Arbeiter said. 
</P>
<P>
	A White House spokeswoman called Clinton's billing ``a question  
of semantics.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990611.0133 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-11 15:06:34 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Irvine Leads Formula One Practice </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MONTREAL (AP) -- Even with a final lap miscue, Eddie Irvine still  
beat out Ferrari teammate Michael Schumacher on Friday and led both 
practice sessions for the Canadian Grand Prix. 
</P>
<P>
	``I only made one mistake and I was pleased with myself until  
then,'' Irvine said, referring to a harmless spin in the afternoon 
session. ``My last lap should have been my best, but I used too 
much of the curb at one point.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Irishman got around the 2.747-mile, 13-turn Circuit Gilles  
Villeneuve in 1 minute, 20.576 seconds. That was .700-second 
quicker than the 1:20.664 by McLaren-Mercedes driver David 
Coulthard of Scotland -- last year's Canadian pole-winner -- and 
.934-second faster than Schumacher's 1:21.276. 
</P>
<P>
	Schumacher, the defending race winner, was very confident after  
Friday's action. 
</P>
<P>
	``Tomorrow we will use our new engine for the first time in  
qualifying,'' the German said. ``I expect we will be very 
competitive in qualifying and in the race, as this circuit suits 
our car.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Jean Alesi, the 1995 Canada winner, was fourth overall at  
1:21.510 in a Sauber-Petronas, followed by Giancarlo Fisichella's 
Benetton-Playlife at 1:21.724. 
</P>
<P>
	Riccardo Zonta, a 23-year-old Brazilian, made an impressive  
return to action following a three-race layoff while recuperating 
from a broken foot. The youngster put his British American Racing 
entry sixth at 1:21.810, beating out defending Formula One champion 
Mika Hakkinen, who struggled to a 1:21.950 in the other Team 
McLaren entry. 
</P>
<P>
	Hakkinen, who trails Schumacher by six points in the battle for  
the 1999 series title, does not enjoy racing on the Canadian 
circuit. 
</P>
<P>
	``This track is just weird,'' the Finnish driver said. ``I've  
never got it right, to be honest. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is a challenge. If I get it right, I'll be very  
pleased.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Even further off pace than Hakkinen was Team Williams driver  
Alex Zanardi, the CART champion each of the past two years. 
</P>
<P>
	Zanardi, who was an immediate starter when he joined the  
American-based series in 1996, has struggled badly so far in his 
less-than-triumphant return to Formula One. 
</P>
<P>
	In Friday's practice, Zanardi was 18th at 1:23.824.  
</P>
<P>
	``I certainly miss the competitiveness of the car I had  
underneath me last year (in CART),'' the Italian driver said. 
``But, having said that, the Winfield-Williams team is a great 
organization and nobody on the team is happy with the performance 
of the car right now. 
</P>
<P>
	``I still have something to learn about driving the car on these  
grooved tires, which is the feature that has changed the handling 
of the cars most dramatically since I was last in F1 (in 1994).'' 
</P>
<P>
	Jacques Villeneuve, another former CART champion and Zonta's BAR  
teammate, was ninth at 1:22.021 -- a performance the Canadian-born 
local favorite considered mediocre. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're finding some things out to make the car better, but it's  
very difficult,'' Villeneuve said. '' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990611.0134 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-11 07:30:47 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Asian Stock Markets Close Mixed </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	HONG KONG (AP) -- Asian stock markets ended the week generally  
mixed Friday, with prices rising both in Tokyo and Hong Kong. 
</P>
<P>
	Japanese stocks rose after the Economic Planning Agency's  
announcement Thursday that Japan's economy grew 1.9 percent, or 7.9 
percent on an annualized basis, in the first quarter of the year. 
</P>
<P>
	The numbers marked Japan's first expansion after five quarters  
of contraction. The country is struggling with its deepest 
recession since the end of World War II. 
</P>
<P>
	The benchmark 225-issue Nikkei Stock Average gained 95.93  
points, or 0.56 percent, to close at 17,198.55. On Thursday, the 
average finished up 480.12 points, or 2.89 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	In the morning, the Nikkei rose as high at 17483.38, its highest  
intraday level since October 1997, before slipping back down. 
</P>
<P>
	Meanwhile, the U.S. dollar was quoted at 118.66 yen, down 0.46  
yen from late Thursday in Tokyo and below its late New York level 
of 118.84 yen overnight. 
</P>
<P>
	In Hong Kong, the blue-chip Hang Seng Index rose 153.55 points,  
or 1.2 percent, closing at 12,992.76. On Friday, the index lost 
35.21 points, or 0.3 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	Brokers attributed the rise to Wednesday's cut in interest rates  
by China, which boosted the shares of companies in Hong Kong with 
business ties on the Chinese mainland. 
</P>
<P>
	Shares of Cathay Pacific Airways rose sharply after the airline  
reached an agreement with its pilots over a pay dispute that caused 
the cancellation of a large number of flights. Cathay shares rose 
6.7 percent to close at 12.75 Hong Kong dollars (U.S. $1.63). 
</P>
<P>
	Fears of a rise in U.S. interest rates were discounted by the  
market, brokers said. The United States was to release its producer 
price index later Friday, which will provide clues about whether 
there will be a rise in rates. 
</P>
<P>
	Elsewhere:  
</P>
<P>
	SINGAPORE: Share prices closed higher on the back of heavy  
institutional buying, dealers said. The benchmark Straits Times 
Index rose 37.17 points, or 1.8 percent, to 2,067.17. 
</P>
<P>
	TAIPEI: Share prices closed lower for the first time this month  
on concerns that the U.S. stock market's strength could be waning. 
The market's key Weighted Stock Price Index fell 17.36 points, or 
0.21 percent, to 7,979.40. 
</P>
<P>
	WELLINGTON: New Zealand share prices closed slightly lower. The  
benchmark NZSE-40 Capital Index fell 8.34 points, or 0.3 percent, 
to 2,120.11. 
</P>
<P>
	MANILA: Philippine shares closed mixed as investors awaited key  
U.S. economic data due for release later in the day. The Philippine 
Stock Exchange index of 30 selected companies fell 5.11 points, or 
0.2 percent, to 2,367.79. 
</P>
<P>
	SYDNEY: The Australian share market closed lower amid fears of  
higher inflation and an interest rate hike in the United States. 
The All Ordinaries Index fell 28.4 points, or 0.95 percent, to 
2,950.2. 
</P>
<P>
	SEOUL: Share prices closed mixed. The Korea Composite Stock  
Price Index fell 7.45 points, or 0.8 percent, to 848.61. 
</P>
<P>
	KUALA LUMPUR: Malaysian share prices closed mostly higher as  
investors bought on speculation about a snap general election. The 
Composite Index, which tracks 100 key stocks, rose 5.07 points, or 
0.6 percent, to 772.76. 
</P>
<P>
	JAKARTA: Indonesian share prices closed higher on cautious  
optimism that the vote count in the country's election, although 
slow, will be smooth. The Composite Index rose 3.712 points, or 0.5 
percent, to 668.281. 
</P>
<P>
	BANGKOK: Thailand's benchmark index closed lower due to profit  
taking. The Stock Exchange of Thailand index fell 4.38 points, or 
0.8 percent, to 507.06. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990611.0135 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-11 15:06:34 </DATE_TIME>
