<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Ticketmaster To Buy One &AMP; Only </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PASADENA, Calif. (AP) -- Ticketmaster Online-CitySearch Inc.  
announced an agreement to acquire One &AMP; Only Network, a 
subscription-based provider of online personal ads and auctions. 
</P>
<P>
	One &AMP; Only's affiliate program encompasses more than 110,000 Web  
sites that direct consumers to its matchmaking personals on 
oneandonly.com and its person-to-person auctions on uTrade.com, 
according to a statement released Thursday by Ticketmaster 
Online-CitySearch. 
</P>
<P>
	Ticketmaster Online-CitySearch said it is expanding its network  
of original local information and transaction services. The 
Pasadena-based company also recently announced plans to acquire 
Match.com, an online dating service. 
</P>
<P>
	Match.com and One &AMP; Only together have registered more than  
three million users, Ticketmaster Online-CitySearch said. 


  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990611.0137 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-11 13:40:18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> If Knicks Win, Coach Reaps Millions </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Jeff Van Gundy stands to make millions if the  
Knicks make it to the NBA Finals. 
</P>
<P>
	An option year in Van Gundy's contract worth $3.5 million  
becomes guaranteed if he leads his team out of the Eastern 
Conference finals, and he also would reportedly receive a $500,000 
bonus. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't really care what's in there, I just want to win,'' Van  
Gundy said Friday after the Knicks held their shootaround in 
preparation for Game 6 against the Indiana Pacers. 
</P>
<P>
	New York led 3-2 in the best-of-7 series entering Friday night's  
game. 
</P>
<P>
	Van Gundy's potential windfall headlined the front page of one  
of the city's tabloids Friday along with a rare photo of Van Gundy 
smiling. 
</P>
<P>
	The dour-faced coach, in his fourth season running the team, is  
currently making $2 million per season -- the same amount Doc Rivers 
will be getting from Orlando next season despite never having 
coached at any level. 
</P>
<P>
	Van Gundy said he wasn't exactly sure what's in his contract  
because he keeps it in a safety deposit box. 
</P>
<P>
	``The one thing about this job is, I'm fine (financially).  
Wanting to win has zero to do with money,'' Van Gundy said. ``You 
can't buy your way into something that's worthwhile, and the only 
thing worthwhile out of here is trying to be the best team for one 
year.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Despite his team's postseason success, Van Gundy has not  
received a vote of confidence from Madison Square Garden 
management. 
</P>
<P>
	Garden president Dave Checketts, who demoted general manager  
Ernie Grunfeld in April because of a rift between the GM and coach, 
has steadfastly insisted that all team personnel, including the 
coach, will have their performances reviewed at the end of the 
season. 
</P>
<P>
	Checketts met with former Chicago Bulls coach Phil Jackson in  
April when the Knicks were 21-21 and in jeopardy of missing the 
playoffs. 
</P>
<P>
	Checketts subsequently lied to Van Gundy by denying such a  
meeting ever took place, then met with the coach during the 
second-round series against Atlanta and apologized. 
</P>
<P>
	Speculation about whether Van Gundy would even want to return to  
the Knicks has been rampant ever since. For the past two weeks, Van 
Gundy has brushed aside all queries about his job status. 
</P>
<P>
	Van Gundy has become a risk-taker in the Eastern Conference  
finals. He tinkered with his starting lineup before Game 4 by 
inserting Latrell Sprewell and removing Kurt Thomas. And in Game 5, 
he curiously kept Marcus Camby on the bench for the first 10 
minutes of the third quarter. 
</P>
<P>
	``By starting Latrell, it was neither genius ... nor stupidity  
in Game 4,'' Van Gundy said. ``It was what I felt was in the best 
interest of the team. That's how I make every decision.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Van Gundy took a lot of criticism when the Sprewell move seemed  
to backfire in Game 4. But those same critics were lauding the move 
after Game 5 when Sprewell unleashed an array of offensive moves 
and had his best game of the series with 29 points. 
</P>
<P>
	With Camby, the coach decided to keep him out for the bulk of  
the third quarter because he had three fouls. He wanted Camby 
available for the entire fourth quarter, and he didn't want him 
playing tentatively because of foul trouble. 
</P>
<P>
	The move paid off.  
</P>
<P>
	``I'm just really thankful that I'm a part of a team that's  
still playing,'' Van Gundy said. ``And what small part I play in 
it, I take very seriously. I do the job the best I can. '' 
</P>
<P>
	In this case, it means departing from what got the Knicks here  
and taking a gamble or two to try to help offset the loss of 
Patrick Ewing. 
</P>
<P>
	``If you become paralyzed by the thought that you may be  
criticized for doing something, you're never going to be the risk 
taker you need to be as a good coach. Risk taking is part of it. If 
it doesn't work out, you've got to accept the responsibility for it 
not working out,'' Van Gundy said. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990611.0138 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-11 06:20:24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> L.A. Cops Raid Call Girl Ring </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LOS ANGELES (AP) -- Police say they have busted one of the most  
elaborate call girl rings since they cracked the case of the 
``Hollywood Madam,'' Heidi Fleiss, six years ago. 
</P>
<P>
	Jody Diane ``Babydol'' Gibson, allegedly a former competitor of  
Fleiss, was arrested Tuesday after a 10-month investigation. 
</P>
<P>
	``Actors, producers, Fortune 500 CEOs and at least one  
professional athlete'' used Gibson's service, police Lt. Mike Felix 
said. However, police declined to identify the clients. 
</P>
<P>
	Gibson, 41, kept detailed notes on her customers and marketed  
her business on the World Wide Web as ``California Dreamin','' 
police said. Clients would pay between $500 to $3,000 for the 
services. 
</P>
<P>
	``She ran one of the largest operations since Heidi Fleiss,''  
said Detective Steve Park. ``She was very sophisticated and 
well-known throughout the U.S. and Europe.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Police arrested Gibson on Tuesday during a sting at a West Los  
Angeles hotel. Detectives served search warrants at several 
locations, including one at her Palo Verde home. 
</P>
<P>
	Gibson was booked on one count of pimping, but faces up to nine  
felony counts of pimping and pandering. Each count carries a 
sentence of up to three years. Gibson was released after posting 
$25,000 bail, police said. 
</P>
<P>
	Fleiss was arrested in 1993 and spent 20 months at a federal  
prison for conspiracy, tax evasion and laundering call-girl 
profits. Fleiss' operation also catered to a high-class clientele 
and stars, including actor Charlie Sheen, who spent $53,000 on 
Fleiss' call girls in 1992. 
</P>
<P>
	Police described Gibson as a rival of Fleiss who moved to fill  
the void when Fleiss' operation closed down. Evidence indicates 
that some of Fleiss' prostitutes and clients switched to Gibson's 
business, police said. 
</P>
<P>
	Authorities found a manuscript in which Gibson detailed her life  
as a madam, Felix said. It alleged that Fleiss once asked Gibson 
for a job as an escort, police said. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
