<DOCNO> APW19990611.0139 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-11 07:29:30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Indonesia Leader Concedes Defeat </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	JAKARTA, Indonesia (AP) -- A prominent opposition leader whose  
party was behind in partial election returns conceded defeat today, 
boosting the legitimacy of a key step in Indonesia's democratic 
transition. 
</P>
<P>
	Amien Rais, a vocal critic of former authoritarian President  
Suharto, acknowledged his loss in the parliamentary election even 
though only 20 percent of the votes had been counted. 
</P>
<P>
	International election observers said Monday's poll was fair  
despite scattered irregularities, but worries have mounted that the 
delay in counting votes might rattle confidence in the process. 
</P>
<P>
	Even Rais had earlier speculated that an attempt to rig the vote  
was under way. By the end of the week, however, he was resigned to 
fifth place with 8 percent for his National Mandate Party. 
</P>
<P>
	``I accept the result wholeheartedly,'' Rais told Associated  
Press Television News. ``I don't want to make any protest because, 
as far as I know, the election was fair and free.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Early returns showed opposition leader Megawati Sukarnoputri  
with 35 percent and the ruling Golkar party with 20 percent, 
despite expectations that it would do poorly. 3/8 
</P>
<P>
	Megawati, a former legislator, is the daughter of founding  
President Sukarno. Rais, former head of Indonesia's second-largest 
Muslim group, founded his party last year. 
</P>
<P>
	Rais could still be a pivotal player if, as expected, no party  
wins a majority and negotiations on a coalition government begin. 
</P>
<P>
	He had agreed to join forces with Megawati to thwart Golkar, but  
today he left open the possibility of reluctantly making a deal 
with the ruling party. 
</P>
<P>
	``To make a coalition with Golkar is the last choice I make in  
this world,'' Rais said. 
</P>
<P>
	Golkar was an obedient political instrument during the  
three-decade rule of Suharto, who resigned a year ago amid 
pro-democracy protests and deadly riots in Jakarta and other major 
cities. Like many Indonesians, Suharto has only one name. 
</P>
<P>
	Megawati's Indonesian Democratic Party for Struggle has agreed  
to form a coalition with other opposition parties if necessary. 
</P>
<P>
	They include Rais' party and the National Awakening Party headed  
by Muslim leader Abdurrahman Wahid. It has 13 percent of the 
counted votes. 
</P>
<P>
	The official tally will be announced June 21. Overall, 48  
parties fielded candidates. 
</P>
<P>
	It was not immediately clear how many seats the vote tallies  
would translate to in Indonesia's complex system of proportional 
representation. But the top vote-getter is not necessarily 
guaranteed the most seats in Parliament. 
</P>
<P>
	The election for 462 seats in Parliament was the first step  
toward selecting a president. The new legislators and the military 
representatives, as well as 200 government appointees, will choose 
a president later this year. 
</P>
<P>
	Dozens of students protested today against the slow vote count,  
gathering outside a Jakarta hotel where results were being 
collected. They warned that Golkar might triumph again if reform 
forces splintered. 
</P>
<P>
	They also demanded a trial of Suharto, who faces a corruption  
investigation, and said the military should get out of politics. 
</P>
<P>
	The military, which says it is neutral, is guaranteed 38  
appointed seats in the new 500-member Parliament, down from 75 in 
the current legislature. Several senior Cabinet ministers are 
generals or retired generals, including military commander Gen. 
Wiranto, touted as a possible presidential candidate. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990611.0140 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-11 07:29:30 </DATE_TIME>
