<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Economy Not Helping Smaller Cities </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW ORLEANS (AP) -- The federal government's third annual ``State  
of Cities'' report says smaller American communities are not 
sharing in the economic boom enjoyed by mega-cities like New York 
and Los Angeles. 
</P>
<P>
	Smaller and medium-sized cities are experiencing slower  
population growth, higher unemployment and growing poverty compared 
to larger communities, said Andrew Cuomo, secretary of the 
Department of Housing and Urban Development. 
</P>
<P>
	``A prosperity gap still divides the majority of communities  
that are doing well from the minority that are struggling,'' Cuomo 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	The report was issued here in advance of the 67th annual  
Conference of Mayors. President Clinton was addressing the meeting 
via videotape today. Cuomo will address the convention Saturday. 
</P>
<P>
	The report said that small cities and older, established suburbs  
right outside the cities' borders, have problems in crime and 
poverty and shouldn't allow jurisdictional boundaries hinder 
efforts to find regional solutions. 
</P>
<P>
	In the months before the report was finalized, Cuomo traveled to  
Gary, Ind., Appalachian towns in eastern Kentucky and other smaller 
communities to talk with local leaders and see why they were 
failing to share in the economic prosperity enjoyed by large 
communities. 
</P>
<P>
	For example, in Gary, 40 percent of residents fall below the  
federal poverty rate of $16,655 in annual income for a family of 
four. 
</P>
<P>
	``Our challenge now is to invest in building a brighter future  
for people and places left behind,'' Cuomo said. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990611.0142 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-11 20:00:20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Prosecutor Doubts Knight's Accuser </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BLOOMINGTON, Ind. (AP) -- Bob Knight most likely will learn  
Monday if he will face assault charges, but the prosecutor has 
questioned the credibility of the coach's accuser. 
</P>
<P>
	The Indiana coach is accused of making a racist remark in a  
restaurant near the campus Monday night, then choking a patron in 
the parking lot and challenging him to fight. 
</P>
<P>
	Monroe County prosecutor Carl Salzmann could decide to file  
assault and battery charges against the 58-year-old coach. 
</P>
<P>
	The complaint was made by Chris Foster, 38, and he faces  
possible provocation charges. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm beginning to doubt the credibility of the story,''  
Salzmann said. 
</P>
<P>
	The disturbance happened at a Mexican restaurant in  
Ellettsville. Foster said he had been listening to the conversation 
Knight was having with his family at a table across the room. 
</P>
<P>
	But Salzmann said Friday there were no thumb marks among the red  
welts on Foster's neck, which eliminates the possibility Knight 
lifted Foster off the ground. 
</P>
<P>
	``You have to have an opposable-thumb print,'' Salzmann said.  
</P>
<P>
	Investigators are now combing credit-card receipts seeking  
others who were at the restaurant at the time. They want to 
determine if Foster had been intentionally eavesdropping on the 
coach. 
</P>
<P>
	``It would mean the case leans more toward a provocation  
scenario, that this was intended to harass and annoy (Knight),'' 
Salzmann said. ``But I'm keeping an open mind.'' 
</P>
<P>
	A misdemeanor battery charge carries a maximum penalty of a  
$5,000 fine and six months in jail. A provocation charge carries a 
maximum $500 fine. 
</P>
<P>
	Knight, whose temper is notorious in college basketball, has  
been suspended or fined several times. 
</P>
<P>
	In 1979, Knight was tried and convicted in absentia and  
sentenced to six months in jail for hitting a Puerto Rican 
policeman at the Pan American Games. Indiana refused to extradite 
Knight and Puerto Rico eventually dropped attempts to get him back. 
</P>
<P>
	At the 1981 NCAA finals in Philadelphia, an LSU fan says Knight  
stuffed him in a garbage can. In 1985, he was ejected after 
throwing a chair across the court during a game against Purdue. 
</P>
<P>
	In the 1992 NCAA tournament, Knight playfully gave a mock  
whipping to Calbert Cheaney, a black player, during practice. 
Knight denied racial connotations to the prank. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990611.0143 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-11 00:30:15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Airlines Delay Passenger Rights Plan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Airlines hope to reach an agreement with  
Senate leaders on a plan for treating passengers better by as early 
as next week. 
</P>
<P>
	A news conference scheduled for Thursday was abruptly postponed  
after Senate leaders complained they had not signed off on the 
proposal. 
</P>
<P>
	The reversal left the chairman of United Airlines, Gerald  
Greenwald, with the chore of standing before a roomful of reporters 
and announcing that the announcement would be delayed. 
</P>
<P>
	``In the coming days we will be working to refine and improve  
our plan in conjunction with Sen. John McCain and other leading 
members of the House and Senate,'' said Greenwald, who also serves 
as chairman of the airline's trade group, the Air Transport 
Association. 
</P>
<P>
	Without taking questions, he disappeared behind the closed doors  
of the association's board room, where the nation's other top 
airline executives were waiting. 
</P>
<P>
	While the announcement triggered embarrassment among airline  
executives and chuckling on Capitol Hill, the parties agreed on a 
central point: The nation's major airlines and senators who have 
been complaining about the way they treat passengers are close to 
agreeing on a voluntary plan that would stave off congressional 
action. 
</P>
<P>
	Included in the package would be increased compensation for lost  
luggage, a promise to give passengers basic amenities when there 
are long on-board flight delays and a pledge to respond quickly to 
passenger complaints. 
</P>
<P>
	The elements are drawn from several bills proposed in the House  
and the Senate and by the Clinton administration after passenger 
complaints peaked over the New Year's holiday, when thousands of 
travelers were stranded at Midwestern airports after a snowstorm. 
</P>
<P>
	Northwest Airlines came under particularly harsh criticism for  
holding passengers for hours on one jet in Detroit despite a lack 
of food and water and an overflowing toilet. 
</P>
<P>
	Negotiations with the airlines have been led by McCain, R-Ariz.,  
chairman of the Senate Commerce Committee and co-sponsor of one of 
the passenger rights bills. Also participating have been McCain's 
co-sponsor, Sen. Ron Wyden, D-Ore., along with Sens. Slade Gorton, 
R-Wash.; Jay Rockefeller, D-W.Va.; Ernest Hollings, D-S.C.; and 
Frank Lautenberg, D-N.J. 
</P>
<P>
	The parties had planned to hold a news conference on Capitol  
Hill to make a joint announcement, but that was scrapped Wednesday 
after airline haggling over details. 
</P>
<P>
	On Thursday, the Air Transport Association announced that a  
consensus had been reached, and it scheduled a midday news 
conference. The timing was driven by the fact that the executives 
were in town for their quarterly meeting. When the appointed hour 
arrived, however, Greenwald announced the delay. 
</P>
<P>
	Spokesmen for several senators said support for the airline plan  
evaporated as senators read a headline in The Wall Street Journal 
saying the airlines were near an agreement with the White House. 
The headline bothered the senators because the Clinton 
administration had not been involved in the negotiations, the 
spokesmen said. 
</P>
<P>
	Several senators also said they wanted tougher language on  
several points, including policies on handling lost baggage, 
accommodating passengers who get ``bumped'' despite confirmed 
reservations and notifying the public when there are flight delays. 
</P>
<P>
	Don Marshall, a spokesman for Rockefeller, said an agreement was  
still possible despite the postponement. Several spokesman said it 
could come as early as next week. 
</P>
<P>
	``We think it's a good start, and we're continuing to work with  
the airlines to get something done here that will be in the best 
interests of passengers,'' he said. 

  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990611.0144 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-11 20:20:17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Obituaries in the News  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
                            *Ann L. Brown    	
</P>
<P>
	BERKELEY, Calif. (AP) -- Ann L. Brown, a professor whose work  
focused on how children learn and how they should be taught, died 
June 4 after a brief illness. She was 56. 
</P>
<P>
	Since 1988, Ms. Brown was an educational theorist at the School  
of Education at the University of California, Berkeley. Many of her 
ideas were tested in classroom environments and adopted by 
educational scholars. 
</P>
<P>
	She did not learn to read until she was 13, but graduated with  
honors from the University of London and later earned a Ph.D. in 
psychology. 
</P>
<P>
	Ms. Brown pioneered the field of metacognition, the study of how  
people observe and take responsibility for their own learning. In 
her teaching method, students learn from each other. 

</P>
<P>
                          *Kenneth S. Davis    	
</P>
<P>
	MANHATTAN, Kan. (AP) -- Kenneth S. Davis, an author and historian  
who had recently completed work on a fifth volume of his biography 
of Franklin D. Roosevelt, died Thursday. He was 86. 
</P>
<P>
	The first volume of his biography of Roosevelt, ``FDR: The  
Beckoning of Destiny,'' was published in 1974 and won the Francis 
Parkman Prize, considered one of the top awards in the field of 
history. 
</P>
<P>
	Later volumes chronicled the Roosevelt years from 1928-40 -- and  
he had just completed a fifth volume, ``The War Years,'' that has 
not been released. 
</P>
<P>
	He also wrote biographies of Adlai Stevenson, Dwight Eisenhower  
and Charles Lindbergh. 

</P>
<P>
                            *Rick Fields    	
</P>
<P>
	FAIRFAX, Calif. (AP) -- Rick Fields, a writer and close friend of  
Beat poet Allen Ginsburg who chronicled the rise of Buddhism in the 
United States, died Sunday of cancer. He was 57. 
</P>
<P>
	Fields wrote ``How the Swans Came to the Lake: A Narrative  
History of Buddhism in America'' in 1981. 
</P>
<P>
	He began writing at the Whole Earth Catalog in 1969, and later  
contributed regularly to the Yoga Journal and New Age Journal. He 
also founded the Loka Journal and taught at the Jack Kerouac School 
of Disembodied Poetics in Boulder, Colo. 

</P>
<P>
                          *DeForest Kelley    	
</P>
<P>
	LOS ANGELES (AP) -- DeForest Kelley, who played crusty Dr.  
Leonard ``Bones'' McCoy on ``Star Trek'' and brought a country 
flavor to outer space, died Friday after an extended illness. He 
was 79. 
</P>
<P>
	The conflict between McCoy's all-too-human character and Spock's  
cold logic provided grist for many of the series' lighthearted 
moments. ``I'm just a country doctor!'' McCoy would say when called 
on to cope with other-worldly illnesses and calamities. 
</P>
<P>
	Kelley reprised his Dr. McCoy role in six ``Star Trek'' films.  
</P>
<P>
	His earlier screen credits include ``Gunfight at the O.K.  
Corral'' and ``Raintree County.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In addition to ``Star Trek,'' he made appearances on dozens of  
television shows, including ``Gunsmoke'' and ``Bonanza.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Kelley is survived by his wife of nearly 55 years, Carolyn.  

</P>
<P>
                           *Bill Macklin    	
</P>
<P>
	PINE RIVER, Minn. (AP) -- Bill Macklin, who served as editor of  
The New Ulm Daily Journal for 28 years and worked for the 
Associated Press for 12 years, died Tuesday. He was 81. 
</P>
<P>
	Macklin was hired as editor of the Journal in 1951 and had the  
longest tenure of any Journal editor. 
</P>
<P>
	After college, he worked for a Springfield, Mo., newspaper for a  
short time before going to work in the AP's St. Louis bureau until 
he was drafted into the military in 1941. 
</P>
<P>
	After the war, he covered sports for the AP in London before  
returning to the United States to work in the AP's Kansas City 
bureau in 1949. Two years later, he went to work for the New Ulm 
Daily Journal as an editor. 
</P>
<P>
	Macklin is survived by his second wife, Judy, and three  
children. 

</P>
<P>
                          *Lawrence J. Nunn    	
</P>
<P>
	WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. (AP) -- Lawrence J. Nunn, who created the  
grinning Freddy the Alligator which still adorns canal bridges, 
water conservation pamphlets and Florida Turnpike toll booths, died 
Monday. He was 81. 
</P>
<P>
	In 1963, Nunn joined the flood control district, now known as  
the South Florida Water Management District, and worked there for 
20 years. 
</P>
<P>
	He created the alligator logo for the district and produced a  
film about the life of an alligator in the wild. He named the 
cartoon logo after Freddy, a real life baby gator who hatched in 
his film. 
</P>
<P>
	Nunn eventually gave the real gator to the Palm Beach Zoo and  
would visit him on lunch breaks. Freddy was killed by vandals in 
1985. 

</P>
<P>
                       *Rev. Harry Boone Porter    	
</P>
<P>
	BRIDGEPORT, Conn. (AP) -- The Rev. Harry Boone Porter, an  
Episcopalian theologian and scholar who played a leading role in 
modernizing the church's Book of Common Prayer, died Saturday of 
pneumonia. He was 76. 
</P>
<P>
	Porter was an influential member of the Standing Liturgical  
Commission, the panel of church experts who worked from 1960 to 
1976 to revise the wording of the holy communion service into 
plain, common, modern English. 
</P>
<P>
	In recent years, Porter had served as senior editor of The  
Living Church, a weekly magazine. He was the magazine's editor in 
Milwaukee from 1977 until 1990. 
</P>
<P>
	He is survived by his wife, Violet Monser Porter; three  
daughters; three sons and eight grand children. 

</P>
<P>
                           *Giles S. Rich    	
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Giles S. Rich, the oldest active federal judge  
in the nation's history and an authority on intellectual property 
rights and patent law, died Wednesday. He was 95. 
</P>
<P>
	Rich, a judge on the U.S. Court of Appeals for the Federal  
Circuit, served on the appellate bench since 1956. He became the 
nation's oldest active federal judge in March, 1997. 
</P>
<P>
	While a patent lawyer, Rich played an instrumental role in the  
drafting of the Patent Act of 1952, which helped form the 
foundation of current patent law. 
</P>
<P>
	Later, he was appointed to the Court of Customs and Patent  
Appeals by President Eisenhower. He also was one of 12 founding 
judges when that court was replaced by the U.S. Court of Appeals 
for the Federal Circuit. 

</P>
<P>
                            *Chen Xilian    	
</P>
<P>
	BEIJING (AP) -- Chen Xilian, a veteran of China's communist  
revolution and career military officer who served as vice premier, 
died Thursday. He was 84. 
</P>
<P>
	Chen joined the Red Army at the age of 14. Before the 1949  
communist victory, he served for 20 years under military commanders 
who would become some of China's most influential politicians. 
</P>
<P>
	Promoted to general in 1955, Chen oversaw military operations in  
China's northeast, known in the West as Manchuria, and then in 
Beijing. 
</P>
<P>
	He was named vice premier in 1975 and resigned five years later  
to make way for economic reformers favored by party leader Deng 
Xiaoping. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
