<DOCNO> APW19990611.0145 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-11 15:30:11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Drug Testimony Admitted in Lewis Suit </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BOSTON (AP) -- A college classmate of Reggie Lewis said in a  
deposition read in court Friday that he snorted cocaine and 
freebased with the Boston Celtics star, who died of an abnormal 
heart rhythm in 1993. 
</P>
<P>
	The testimony is key to the defense of Dr. Gilbert Mudge, a  
renowned cardiologist who is accused in a $117 million malpractice 
lawsuit of misdiagnosing and mistreating Lewis. 
</P>
<P>
	He says the 27-year-old player confessed to using cocaine two  
weeks before he died and maintains that belated admission made an 
accurate diagnosis of Lewis' heart condition impossible. 
</P>
<P>
	Lewis' widow, Donna Harris-Lewis, says the claim is a low blow  
intended only to distract the jury and tarnish the name of a dead 
star. 
</P>
<P>
	On Friday the judge ruled that defense attorneys may call five  
witnesses to testify about Lewis' alleged drug use. 
</P>
<P>
	Afterward, a deposition from one of them, Lewis' former  
Northeastern University classmate Wayne Brown, was read in court. 
</P>
<P>
	``We were snorting lines of cocaine and freebasing, both of us  
were smoking cocaine,'' Brown said in the deposition, adding that 
he did drugs with Lewis ``probably six'' times while they were in 
college in the 1980s. 
</P>
<P>
	Harris-Lewis' attorneys have called Brown as a loser and  
attacked his credibility by citing deposition statements in which 
he discussed how he frequently used and sold drugs and drank to the 
point of blacking out. 
</P>
<P>
	Such testimony is expected to increase the rancor in the trial,  
which was dominated this week by testimony about cocaine use. 
</P>
<P>
	Mudge brought Lewis' mother and wife into the fray when he  
testified that Harris-Lewis told him months after her husband's 
death -- when the widow and the doctor were still friends -- that 
Lewis had ``died of the poisons'' his mother, a former drug abuser, 
had battled. 
</P>
<P>
	Attorneys for Harris-Lewis have contended the drug allegations  
are not only untrue, but irrelevant. Even if Lewis snorted cocaine, 
they say, it doesn't matter: Mudge's responsibility was to treat a 
heart problem, no matter what its cause. 
</P>
<P>
	Shortly before Lewis' death, Mudge came under fire when he  
offered an opinion that went against that of a ``Dream Team'' of 
doctors from New England Baptist Hospital. They had diagnosed Lewis 
with a life-threatening, potentially career-ending cardiac 
arrhythmia after his collapse during a playoff game. 
</P>
<P>
	At a news conference at the time, Mudge announced that the  
athlete's heart was healthy, saying he suffered from a neurological 
condition that causes fainting spells. Lewis, he added, could 
probably return to professional basketball. 
</P>
<P>
	Two months later, the player dropped dead of an arrhythmia, or  
abnormal heart rhythm, while practicing jump shots. 
</P>
<P>
	Drug rumors have swirled in Boston's sports and medical  
communities ever since. It also has been a sensitive topic in the 
city since 1986, when Len Bias died of a cocaine overdose days 
after he became the Celtics' first-round draft pick. 
</P>
<P>
	After a 1995 Wall Street Journal article raised the possibility  
that Lewis had used cocaine, Harris-Lewis -- who claimed Mudge had 
been a source for the story, which he has denied -- embarked on what 
she said was a quest to clear his name. 
</P>
<P>
	She sued Mudge, along with cardiology consultants Drs. Mark  
Creager and Peter Friedman. A third consultant settled before trial 
for an undisclosed amount. 
</P>
<P>
	Harris-Lewis is asking for the money Lewis could have made had  
he lived -- as much as $117 million, according to testimony from a 
sports agent. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
