<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-11 18:30:13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> NL Suspends Mets' Valentine </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Now that the National League has seen through  
his disguise, Bobby Valentine admits he was the mysterious man in 
the mustache but says he never went back to his team's dugout. 
</P>
<P>
	The New York Mets manager was suspended for two games and fined  
$5,000 Friday by the NL for returning to the dugout in a disguise 
after being ejected Wednesday night. 
</P>
<P>
	``The picture looked like I was in the dugout, but they got it  
all wrong,'' Valentine said before showing reporters the spot 
between the runway and the dugout, where he stood with a fake 
mustache and glasses for the last two innings of Wednesday night's 
game against Toronto. 
</P>
<P>
	``I absolutely was never in the dugout,'' Valentine insisted.  
</P>
<P>
	Valentine was ejected in the 12th inning by plate umpire Randy  
Marsh for arguing a catcher's interference call on Mike Piazza. 
</P>
<P>
	Valentine said he then went into the trainers' room and came out  
with eye black on his upper lip. He showed it to a couple of his 
pitchers in the clubhouse who laughed and then gave him sunglasses 
and a hat. 
</P>
<P>
	He quickly was spotted in the dugout by a television camera.  
</P>
<P>
	``I wasn't fooling anyone with that disguise,'' he said. ``If  
Randy Marsh saw it, I believe he would have laughed. This had 
absolutely nothing to do with the umpires. I did it to lighten up 
the team.'' 
</P>
<P>
	NL president Len Coleman apparently didn't chuckle. He cited  
league rule 5.1, which says: ``When a manager, player, coach or 
trainer is put out of a game by an umpire, he shall leave the field 
immediately.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The rule goes on to say ejected personnel ``shall remain in the  
clubhouse until the game is ended or change to street clothes and 
either leave the park or take a seat in the grandstand well removed 
from the vicinity of his club's bullpen.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``I understand now that I wasn't supposed to be here,''  
Valentine said, standing one step away from the dugout. ``I had 
never read the rule before today. Now I know I need to be in the 
clubhouse. Every manager I've ever seen ejected has been standing 
in the runway.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Yankees manager Joe Torre, no stranger to turmoil, shook his  
head when asked about Valentine's penalty. 
</P>
<P>
	``See what happens when you manage in New York,'' Torre said in  
Miami. 
</P>
<P>
	``I was laughing. The disguise, it was comical to look at it,''  
Chicago Cubs manager Jim Riggleman said. ``Bobby's something. He's 
a character. He's a brilliant baseball man, extremely intelligent. 
I think Bobby was having some fun with it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The suspension was to start Saturday but Valentine appealed,  
meaning it will not begin until after a hearing before Coleman. The 
appeal likely will be heard next week in Cincinnati. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're just going to discuss it,'' Valentine said. ``I don't  
think anything is going to change.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Nothing appears to have changed, either, in the conflict between  
Valentine and Bobby Bonilla. After being told on Monday that he 
would not start for six days, the slumping Bonilla refused to pinch 
hit Tuesday. Valentine then refused to use him the next night. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't need to be compatible with the manager,'' said  
Bonilla, who was available to play Friday. ``I need to do my job. 
He's the guy in charge and I will do whatever he asks.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Bonilla claimed he learned about his benching from the  
newspapers as well as Valentine. The manager insists he told the 
player one day before it was reported in newspapers. 
</P>
<P>
	``I called him in my office Monday and told him other guys would  
play the outfield this week,'' Valentine said. ``There is no doubt 
in my mind that I told him, and there should be no doubt in his 
mind.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Bonilla, who is owed $9,575,411 through the 2000 season, is  
hitting .167 in 90 at-bats. He says he's not bothered by the 
situation and wants to stay with the Mets, even though they would 
like to dump him. 
</P>
<P>
	General manager Steve Phillips reportedly put him on waivers  
last week and said he is exploring trades. Bonilla's salary and 
inability to play the field make him unattractive to most teams. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm confident Steve Phillips will be able to work out some  
sort of deal to the satisfaction of the Mets and Bobby Bonilla,'' 
said Jeff Borris, one of the outfielder's agents. ``I know they're 
trying to put something together.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Phillips said he has the authority from ownership to release  
Bonilla, but that remains ``a last resort.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``It has been disruptive and we need to settle it down soon,''  
Phillips said. ``It's not a situation where the two of them need to 
go out for dinner. But they have to get along within the framework 
of the team to help us win. 
</P>
<P>
 *Notes:* The Mets activated RHP Greg McMichael and optioned INF  
Melvin Mora to Triple-A Norfolk. McMichael has missed the entire 
season with a sore shoulder. He gives Valentine 12 pitchers on the 
roster. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
