<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Workplaces Improve Safety Record </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ATLANTA (AP) -- Safety rules adopted after a series of disasters  
in the early 1900s have contributed to a more than 90 percent drop 
in the rate of workers killed on the job, federal health officials 
say. 
</P>
<P>
	The Centers for Disease Control and Prevention said Thursday  
that work-related deaths declined from 61 per 100,000 workers in 
1913 to four per 100,000 in 1997. 
</P>
<P>
	``There absolutely has been a substantial decline in deaths in  
the workplace this century, although you're still not risk-free and 
there's still a lot of work to be done,'' said Nancy Stout of the 
CDC's National Institute for Occupational Safety and Health. 
</P>
<P>
	An estimated 23,000 people died from work-related injuries in  
1913 compared with 5,100 in 1997, according to the National Safety 
Council and the U.S. Bureau of Labor Statistics. During this same 
period, the work force grew from 38 million to about 130 million. 
</P>
<P>
	Some of the largest declines have been in high-risk industries  
such as mining, where the average death rate was 329 per 100,000 
from 1911 to 1915, compared with 25 per 100,000 in 1996-97, the CDC 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	``Workers now realize they don't have to accept the risk of  
injury as part of a job,'' Ms. Stout said. 
</P>
<P>
	Among steelworkers, there were 17 deaths nationwide in 1997  
compared with 195 in 1906 and 1907 in one Pennsylvania county 
alone. 
</P>
<P>
	It took calamities like the 1907 coal mine explosion in  
Monongah, W.Va., that killed at least 360 people to help pave the 
way for workplace safety laws. The explosion led to passage in 1910 
of the Organic Act, which established the U.S. Bureau of Mines. 
</P>
<P>
	A 1911 New York City garment factory fire claimed 146 lives,  
mostly young women, because there were no alarms or sprinklers and 
the exits were inadequate. The fire led to some of the nation's 
most stringent workplace safety laws. 
</P>
<P>
	Today, industries with the highest rates for fatal workplace  
accidents include mining, agriculture/forestry/fishing and 
construction. 
</P>
<P>
	The leading causes of workplace deaths involve motor vehicles,  
homicides and machine-related injuries. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
