<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Stocks Fall; Dow Down 163.37 / Wall Street Report  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Stocks fell sharply today after a tame inflation  
report failed to temper concerns that the Federal Reserve will 
raise interest rates to slow down the robust U.S. economy. 
</P>
<P>
	At 3 p.m. on Wall Street, the Dow Jones industrial average was  
down 163.37 at 10,457.90. The blue-chip index rose almost 70 points 
in early trading before retreating. 
</P>
<P>
	Broader stock indicators also widened their losses. The Nasdaq  
composite index, which has been battered in recent weeks amid a 
selloff in technology shares, was down 36.97 at 2,447.65, and the 
Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 index was down 13.99 at 1,288.83. 
</P>
<P>
	Stocks initially rose as investors cheered only a slight gain in  
the Producer Price Index last month. The index, which measures 
inflation before it reaches the consumer, rose just 0.2 percent in 
May, down sharply from the 0.5 percent advance in April. 
</P>
<P>
	The inflation report gave investors some reassurance that the  
Fed might not feel the need to raise interest rates at its next 
policy-making meeting, scheduled for June 29 and 30, to prevent the 
economy from overheating and driving inflation higher. Higher rates 
would raise corporate borrowing costs and eat into profits. 
</P>
<P>
	But the advance on Wall Street stalled out as robust growth in  
other economic reports released today renewed concerns about a rate 
hike. Traders said rumors were circulating that the Fed may even 
convene a special, early meeting to debate a rate increase. 
</P>
<P>
	The speculation was fueled after the Commerce Department  
reported that retail sales -- which represent about a third of the 
nation's economic output -- rose 1 percent in May, extending a long 
string of gains. 
</P>
<P>
	In addition, the University of Michigan's consumer sentiment  
index rose to better-than-expected levels, showing that Americans 
remain upbeat thanks to the strong U.S. economy. 
</P>
<P>
	``The market is very confused today,'' said Alfred E. Goldman,  
director of market analysis at A.G. Edwards &AMP; Sons Inc. in St. 
Louis. ``It liked the PPI number, but didn't like the retail sales 
or the Michigan survey.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Internet shares were mostly lower. CMGI fell 10 9/16 to 90 15/16  
after the Internet holding company announced higher-than-expected 
third-quarter losses. 
</P>
<P>
	EBay, an online auctioneer, plunged 15 5/16 to 167 3/8 after its  
system crashed, forcing it to halt operations. 
</P>
<P>
	Declining issues outnumbered advancers by a 7-to-5 margin on the  
New York Stock Exchange, where volume came to 564.92 million 
shares, up from 556.00 million shares on Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	The NYSE composite index was down 4.91 at 617.94, and the  
American Stock Exchange composite index was down 2.76 at 765.49. 

  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
