<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Saga Urges OK of Takeover Offer </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	OSLO, Norway (AP) -- Saga Petroleum ASA on Friday advised its  
shareholders to accept a takeover offer from the Norwegian state 
oil company Statoil and Norsk Hydro ASA after the companies outbid 
France's Elf Aquitaine. 
</P>
<P>
	Statoil and 51-percent state-owned Norsk Hydro bid 135 kroner  
($17.69) per share in stocks and cash for their smaller rival, 10 
kroner ($1.28) more than Elf's bid. The joint bid values Saga at 
about 20 billion kroner ($2.65 billion). Elf said its own bid for 
Saga stands. 
</P>
<P>
	After a four-hour meeting Friday, a majority of Saga Petroleum's  
board recommended the Norwegian bid even though it means breaking 
up Norway's third largest oil company. 
</P>
<P>
	``I am not satisfied with the solution overall, but I think it  
is a good solution for the stockholders,'' said Saga's managing 
director Diderik Schnitler. ``It is not a good solution for 
continuing the organization.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In a separate news release, labor unions at Saga expressed deep  
disappointment over the vote and said Saga employees would stage a 
two-hour protest strike on June 17. 
</P>
<P>
	The Norsk Hydro-Statoil bid is contingent on acceptance by 70  
percent of Saga's shareholders by June 18, endorsement by Norsk 
Hydro's owners and government approval. 
</P>
<P>
	Saga Petroleum, which employs about 1,500 people, was founded in  
1972 as a privately owned alternate to the country's two 
state-controlled oil companies. However, it reported losses last 
year and was planning severe cutbacks. 
</P>
<P>
	In the 1970s, Saga benefited from a government policy giving the  
three Norwegian companies preferential treatment when oil licenses 
were awarded for sectors off the country's coast. Saga now controls 
petroleum reserves of roughly 1.5 billion barrels of oil 
equivalents. 
</P>
<P>
	On May 10, Norsk Hydro offered to trade one of its own shares  
for three Saga shares. It also made a deal with Statoil, Saga's 
largest shareholder with 19.4 percent, to split Saga's assets so 
that Statoil will end up with 25 percent and Norsk Hydro the rest. 
They upped their offer after Elf bid. 

  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
