<DOCNO> APW19990611.0164 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-11 13:00:25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Mayors Push for Tough Gun Safety Law </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW ORLEANS (AP) -- The U.S. Conference of Mayors is urging House  
Speaker Dennis Hastert to press for swift passage of legislation 
requiring higher age restrictions for all firearms buyers and 
background checks for all customers at gun shows. 
</P>
<P>
	The mayors' proposal, contained in a letter to the Illinois  
Republican, is more stringent than pending House legislation. Their 
plan includes raising the legal age of gun buyers from 18 to 21 and 
limiting purchases to one gun a month. 
</P>
<P>
	``The time is ripe for meaningful change,'' New Orleans Mayor  
Marc Morial told a news conference Friday, the opening day of the 
mayors' 67th annual meeting. 
</P>
<P>
	``We are engaged in a multifront movement. In this letter we are  
focusing on the United States House of Representatives. We want a 
meaningful bill with teeth,'' Morial said. 
</P>
<P>
	Leaders of more than 300 communities gathered for the five-day  
meeting to discuss such topics as urban development, health and 
human services, welfare reform and fair housing. 
</P>
<P>
	But no issue was expected to draw more attention than the search  
for ways to defuse the lethal mix of guns and young people. 
</P>
<P>
	Spurred to action by the high school shootings in Littleton,  
Colo., President Clinton and congressional leaders have wrangled 
over the best way to balance safety concerns and gun owners' 
rights. 
</P>
<P>
	Attorney General Janet Reno criticized the pending House  
legislation Friday, saying it would undermine the Senate's 
``common-sense'' effort to stop criminals from buying weapons at 
gun shows. 
</P>
<P>
	The House bill, she told reporters, would narrow the definition  
of ``gun show'' and restrict the time police have to complete 
background checks of prospective gun buyers at such events. In 
addition, she said, the bill would not cover many places where guns 
are often sold, such as flea markets. 
</P>
<P>
	The mayors maintain they are central to the debate, the first  
line of government to bear the social costs when a young person 
fires a gun at school or when an innocent is shot in the streets. 
</P>
<P>
	``We live with these tragedies every day,'' Morial said.  
</P>
<P>
	Clinton told the mayors in a videotaped message shown here that  
House Republicans ``seem intent on ignoring the lessons of 
Littleton.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``We want more police on the street and fewer guns in the hands  
of criminals and children. They want more guns on the street and 
fewer cops,'' Clinton said. 
</P>
<P>
	Scott King, mayor of Gary Ind., said the conference's gun  
violence task force has met twice with firearm industry 
representatives to discuss ways to limit easy access to guns. 
</P>
<P>
	``They went back on what they committed to do,'' said King. ``We  
are going to put faces on the statistics. I have had to bury a 
2-year-old child and a police officer. We say enough is enough.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The spread of gun violence outside urban areas has keyed the  
nation's quest for greater gun safety, said St. Louis Mayor 
Clarence Harmon. 
</P>
<P>
	``Now that we are seeing the violence move from the inner city  
to become a suburban issue and now a rural issue, it is beginning 
to galvanize the public,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Since last year's mayors meeting, 20 cities including New  
Orleans, Chicago, Cleveland, Boston and Newark have sued gun makers 
on grounds that they failed to incorporate available safety 
features on the weapons such as locking devices. 
</P>
<P>
	``The technology needed for safer guns is out there,'' said  
Morial, who filed the first gun industry lawsuit but saw the 
Louisiana state legislature pass a law making it illegal for 
individual cities to sue the gun industry. Morial plans to pursue 
the suit anyway, saying legislation that seeks to nullify a 
previously filed lawsuit ``is destined for a swift constitutional 
death in the courts.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990611.0165 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-11 09:00:27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Sports Cars a Big Hit in Japan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	TOKYO (AP) -- With the nation battling its worst recession since  
World War II, most Japanese are worried about just keeping their 
heads above water. Others are going out and buying sports cars. 
</P>
<P>
	Sports car sales are soaring, the solitary glimmer of hope in an  
otherwise plunging auto market. Domestic automakers are the biggest 
winners in the fad, but European models are selling briskly as 
well. American brands are once again a hard sell. 
</P>
<P>
	Taizo Uno is a typical buyer.  
</P>
<P>
	The college student scrounged and saved while working at a  
McDonald's to buy his dream car, a $28,000 silver Honda S2000 
convertible. ``Driving through the mountains with the top down -- 
it's the ultimate,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	The two-seat S2000, which marks Honda Motor Co.'s return to the  
sports car market after 30 years, has drawn more than 5,800 orders 
since rolling into showrooms in mid-April, though Honda plans to 
sell only 500 of the roadsters a month. 
</P>
<P>
	The S2000 will go on sale next fall in the United States, where  
it also is expected to sell well. More sedate models with a sporty 
look, like the Toyota Altezza that will be sold as a Lexus in the 
United States next year, also are proving to be hot sellers here. 
</P>
<P>
	Eager to keep abreast of the sports car blitz, Toyota Motor  
Corp. is likely to bring to Japan soon its soft-top roadster, the 
MR-Spyder. A concept version was unveiled at Chicago's auto show in 
February. The roadster is scheduled to go on sale in the United 
States in early 2000. 
</P>
<P>
	European brands, which are considered more stylish and  
high-status by Japanese drivers, are holding steady with their 
sports car sales. All 50 of the new $113,000 BMW M5 sports car 
available here, for example, were sold out when orders were taken 
in April. 
</P>
<P>
	Mazda Motor Corp., in which Ford Motor Co. has a controlling  
share, has managed to do well with the new RX-7 sports car that 
went on sale in January with greater horsepower and a lower price 
tag of $24,000, down from $27,000. 
</P>
<P>
	RX-7 sales have now hit about 2,000.  
</P>
<P>
	``The sports car genre is so hot now, simply coming out with a  
new model guarantees buyers are going to snatch it up,'' Mazda 
spokesman Hideo Azuma said. 
</P>
<P>
	But American sports cars generally have stirred little  
excitement here -- yet another chapter in the chronic tale of U.S. 
automakers' battle against their clunker image in this notoriously 
finicky market. 
</P>
<P>
	Just 287 of the General Motors Corp. Chevrolet Corvettes were  
sold here over the last year. Even Ford's reskinned Mustang sports 
coupe, which arrived in Japan last month, has attracted only 30 
orders so far. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm not interested in American cars,'' said businessman  
Kazuyuki Sakai, who just bought a Honda S2000 and also owns an Alfa 
Romeo. 
</P>
<P>
	Earlier this month, the Clinton administration said sales of  
U.S.-made cars in Japan fell by 35 percent in 1998 and declined 29 
percent during the first quarter of this year compared with the 
first quarter of 1998. 
</P>
<P>
	U.S. imports from General Motors, Ford and DaimlerChrysler AG  
still comprise a mere 1 percent of Japan's auto market. 
</P>
<P>
	Washington says the reason behind the U.S. automakers'  
difficulty in making headway in Japan is the closed market. The 
government and U.S. automakers have continued to prod Tokyo to ease 
regulations. 
</P>
<P>
	American car companies tend to see the sports car market here as  
too small a niche to be worth their while and haven't brought many 
over. A couple of years ago, the former Chrysler Corp. said it 
planned to bring to Japan the Dodge Viper sports car -- a powerful 
image booster. It never did. ``It's important in the auto industry 
to have image vehicles in the product lineup,'' said Steve Usher, 
an auto analyst with Jardine Fleming in Tokyo. ``People walk in a 
showroom and see the S2000 and walk out with an Accord.'' 


  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
