<DOCNO> APW19990611.0166 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-11 16:40:13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Canada To Hold Hydrogen Fuel Test </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	VANCOUVER, British Columbia (AP) -- Proponents of pollution-free  
hydrogen fuel-cell cars took a major step towards commercialization 
Friday, announcing a pilot project to develop the essential 
refueling network. 
</P>
<P>
	The five-year agreement involves oil company Petro-Canada,  
fuel-cell developer Ballard Power Systems and Methanex Corp., the 
world's biggest supplier of methanol -- a prime candidate to become 
the fuel source for hydrogen-powered vehicles. 
</P>
<P>
	Safe, convenient refueling will be crucial to the success of  
such vehicles. 
</P>
<P>
	Ballard's partners, Ford Motor Co. and DaimlerChrysler AG, say  
they plan to begin selling hydrogen fuel-cell cars by 2004. They 
would be powered by fuel cells that make electricity by chemically 
combining hydrogen and air without combustion. 
</P>
<P>
	Ballard chairman Firoz Rasul said the automakers hope that by  
2010, as much as 25 percent of their production will be fuel-cell 
cars. 
</P>
<P>
	When pure hydrogen is used, the only byproducts are water and  
heat. For now, vehicles will get hydrogen by on-board conversion 
from other fuels, including natural gas, gasoline or methanol. 
</P>
<P>
	Supporters of methanol, manufactured from natural gas, see it as  
nearly ideal because it can be distributed and pumped much like 
gasoline. 
</P>
<P>
	Indy racing cars burn pure methanol and a methanol-gasoline  
blend is already sold as an alternate fuel for specially adapted 
vehicles. 
</P>
<P>
	Pierre Choquette, chief executive of Methanex, said  
methanol-powered fuel-cell cars will generate some carbon dioxide, 
but will produce no smog-creating pollutants such as carbon 
monoxide and oxides of nitrogen. 
</P>
<P>
	Rasul said the first stage of the program will be to study  
possible locations for methanol pumps. The most likely initial 
spots are gas stations in the Vancouver area, where both Ballard 
and Methanex are based. 
</P>
<P>
	Rasul said it's hoped automakers will decide within 12 months to  
join the project and supply vehicles for the testing phase, similar 
to a fuel-cell demonstration program announced in California. 
</P>
<P>
	Both Ford and DaimlerChrysler have fuel-cell prototype cars that  
run on methanol. Testing so far indicates they can travel up to 300 
miles on a single tank, comparable to gasoline-powered cars. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990611.0167 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-11 07:29:30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> S. Korea Navy Repels N. Korea Ships </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SEOUL, South Korea (AP) -- South Korean patrol boats bumped three  
North Korean vessels today, forcing them out of disputed waters on 
the fourth day of a tense armed standoff. 
</P>
<P>
	But after initially retreating, four North Korean warships  
sailed back into the disputed zone, confronting eight South Korean 
navy ships, South Korea's Defense Ministry said. 
</P>
<P>
	There was no gunfire when the vessels collided earlier, but the  
ships trained their guns on each other and it nearly became an 
armed clash, South Korean lawmaker Han Young-soo said. 
</P>
<P>
	The confrontation came after South Korea began massing  
destroyers and other combat ships early today to end the standoff. 
</P>
<P>
	North Korean warships have been sailing in and out of rich crab  
fishing areas in the disputed waters since Tuesday. Their main 
mission appears to be guarding northern fishing vessels operating 
in the area, ministry officials said on condition of anonymity. 
</P>
<P>
	Six North Korean patrol boats again took up positions in the  
area before dawn today, escorting about a dozen fishing boats, the 
officials said. 
</P>
<P>
	Four South Korean high-speed patrol boats intentionally bumped  
into the North Korean ships, said a South Korean Navy lieutenant 
commander who gave only his last name, Han. Three northern ships 
suffered ``substantial damage'' and retreated along with the other 
three, he said, adding that one southern ship suffered a hole in 
its hull. 
</P>
<P>
	``The situation came close to an armed clash,'' lawmaker Han  
Young-soo told reporters after a closed-door briefing by navy 
officials. ``After the collision, the North Korean ships trained 
their guns at us, and we responded in kind. It was a close call.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Defense Ministry spokesman Brig. Gen. Cha Young-koo said South  
Korea aims ``to resolve the issue peacefully, but we can't let the 
situation drag on ... We'll use all means to end it at whatever 
cost.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Ministry officials said scores of frigates, destroyers and other  
combat ships will be sent to the area. The army and air force will 
provide support in case of emergency, officials said. 
</P>
<P>
	The disputed waters lie south of a U.N.-imposed sea border,  
midway between the North Korean mainland and five South Korean 
islands, 60 miles northwest of Seoul. North Korea has contested the 
sea border since the late 1970s. 
</P>
<P>
	The American-led U.N. Command, for the second time this week,  
asked North Korea to hold a border military meeting to discuss the 
situation. North Korea had rejected an earlier request by the 
command. 
</P>
<P>
	The two Koreas, divided into the communist North and the  
capitalist South in 1945, remain technically at war, with no peace 
treaty signed at the end of the 1950-53 Korean War. Their border is 
the world's most heavily armed, with nearly 2 million troops 
deployed on both sides. 
</P>
<P>
	The U.N. Command and North Korea signed the armistice that ended  
the Korean conflict. But they never agreed on a border in the 
Yellow Sea off the western coast. 
</P>
<P>
	The U.N. Command unilaterally demarcated the maritime frontier  
in 1953 and created a buffer zone south of it to avoid armed 
clashes. 
</P>
<P>
	North Korea has been sending fishing boats and naval ships into  
the zone 20 to 30 times a year. But when challenged by South Korean 
patrol boats, they usually withdrew quickly. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
