<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Sweepstakes Co. Violated Agreement </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	RALEIGH, N.C. (AP) -- A federal judge has found American Family  
Publishers in contempt for violating a deal in which the company 
agreed to tone down its contest promotions mailed to North Carolina 
households. 
</P>
<P>
	Chief U.S. District Judge Terrence Boyle found the sweepstakes  
company in civil contempt of a 1993 settlement that ended a lawsuit 
against the company's practices. 
</P>
<P>
	The settlement said American Family Publishers would stop using  
``language of congratulations or other prizewinning declarations 
which, when considered in context ... represents that the recipient 
of the envelope has won a prize.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The judge's order became public Monday. A hearing to address  
potential damages will be held June 29. 
</P>
<P>
	Spokeswomen for the Jersey City, N.J., company and its Raleigh  
attorneys did not immediately return phone calls seeking comment 
Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	The envelope Attorney General Mike Easley found objectionable  
stated: ``If you have the winning number, please be advised ... 
IT'S DOWN TO A 2 PERSON RACE FOR $11,000,000 -- YOU AND ONE OTHER 
PERSON IN N. CAROLINA WERE ISSUED THE WINNING NUMBER (number) -- 
WHOEVER RETURNS IT FIRST WINS IT ALL!'' 
</P>
<P>
	The company had argued that the lead-in phrase in uncapitalized  
type qualified the conditions to be a sweepstakes winner and showed 
it was abiding by the settlement. Boyle said he didn't buy it. 
</P>
<P>
	Sweepstakes firms defended their industry at a congressional  
hearing in March, saying most Americans understand that no purchase 
is needed to win. Congress is considering a bill that would levy 
stiff fines against companies that mislead consumers. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
