<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Preparedness Expo Readies for Y2K </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	FORT WASHINGTON, Pa. (AP) -- Militia man John Trochmann says the  
whole Y2K craze was staged by the federal government. 
</P>
<P>
	So with the millenium less than seven months away, Trochmann  
believes you might as well be prepared for the worst. And his book 
stand at Preparedness Expo '99 in suburban Philadelphia is the 
perfect place to start, he says. 
</P>
<P>
	``There are certain elements of the government that planned (the  
Y2K craze) this way. It doesn't take a rocket scientist to figure 
that out,'' says Trochmann, a Navy veteran and a member of the 
Militia of Montana. 
</P>
<P>
	Trochmann was one of about 200 vendors who set up shop at the  
Fort Washington Expo Center on Friday for the opening of the 
weekend-long exposition, which is designed to offer products that 
help people prepare for emergencies. 
</P>
<P>
	Aisles were lined with showcases on everything from freeze-dried  
foods to power generators to first-aid kits and holistic healing 
remedies. 
</P>
<P>
	Promoter Dan Chittock, who has helped set up the event since its  
first year in Salt Lake City 10 years ago, says the expo has 
attracted extra attention lately. 
</P>
<P>
	``We have been especially busy this year because of the Year  
2000 computer glitch problem,'' Chittock says. ``People are coming 
because if you are prepared, you don't have to be worried about 
it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Chittock promotes the Preparedness Expo, which is making nine  
stops around the country, as an event ``for peace of mind in our 
changing world.'' 
</P>
<P>
	It usually attracts outdoors enthusiasts, health-conscious  
people, and those who work in the emergency management field, he 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	Lately, more Y2K worriers have been in attendance. Many believe  
computers will break down and malfunction when the calendar hits 
2000 because they were originally programmed to interpret the 
``00'' as 1900. 
</P>
<P>
	Some think that could lead to electricity being cut off and bank  
accounts wiped out. Others think it could even lead to a breakdown 
in social order. 
</P>
<P>
	``I feel that the media is downplaying the whole issue,'' said  
expo attendee Michael Leon, 36, of Hempstead, N.Y. ``We can't rely 
on the government because they won't be able to help.'' 
</P>
<P>
	So Leon strolled the aisles looking for items he said he could  
stockpile in case of disaster. 
</P>
<P>
	One stand sold unusual items such as ``The Miracle Trigger'', a  
$20 device resembling a water pistol that vendor Mary Enna, of 
Divide, Colo. said uses a brief electrical pulse to ``break the 
cycle of pain'' -- which she said could be useful in an emergency 
situation. 
</P>
<P>
	Nearby, representatives of Long Beach, Calif.-based Organic by  
Nature talked about their plant-based dried juice products. Some of 
the main ingredients include grass and barley. 
</P>
<P>
	``It taste like tea or spinach, depending on who you ask,''  
operations manager Amy Veneer said. ``But add it in with apple 
juice and it tastes real good.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Critics say shows like Chittock's unjustly feed into Y2K  
paranoia. Organizations like the American Red Cross advise the 
public to prepare for the millenium by stocking disaster supplies 
for several days and keeping some extra cash on hand. 
</P>
<P>
	Richard Landis of Boston University's Center for Millenial  
Studies said the attention being paid today to the Y2K problem is 
part paranoia, part legitimate. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is the greatest deadline in the history of mankind,''  
Landis said. ``It looks like it may not be disastrous, but we're 
not out of the woods yet.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
