<CATEGORY> political </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Americans Favor 1st Lady Senate Run </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- It's fine for a president's spouse to run for  
office, say three out of four Americans surveyed for an Associated 
Press poll. And when it comes to Hillary Rodham Clinton and New 
York's Senate seat, a majority, though a smaller one, says she 
should run. 
</P>
<P>
	The drop-off to 54 percent who favor a run by Mrs. Clinton is  
largely due to the attitudes of GOP voters. 
</P>
<P>
	The poll, conducted by ICR of Media, Pa., found that 65 percent  
of Republicans said seeking elective office was appropriate for a 
presidential spouse, while 34 percent said this particular 
presidential spouse should run. Among Democrats, 85 percent said 
running for office was appropriate in general, and 77 percent said 
Mrs. Clinton should run. Half of independent voters said she should 
run. 
</P>
<P>
	Mrs. Clinton recently said she would form an exploratory  
committee to help her decide whether to seek the Senate seat held 
by Democrat Daniel Patrick Moynihan, who is retiring. She was 
running neck and neck with New York City Mayor Rudolph Giuliani, a 
Republican, in polls of New York voters taken late this spring. 
</P>
<P>
	Elizabeth Dole, a candidate for the GOP presidential nomination  
and wife of 1996 Republican nominee Bob Dole, said in an interview 
with The Associated Press this week that Mrs. Clinton should be 
able to run ``if that's what she wants to do and if the people of 
New York want her to do it. ... She's certainly a very bright lady. 
That's up to her.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The telephone poll of 1,016 American adults was taken Friday  
through Tuesday. The margin of sampling error was plus or minus 3 
percentage points. 
</P>
<P>
	Mrs. Clinton's approval rating stood at 58 percent in the poll  
while President Clinton got a mixed review, with 48 percent saying 
they had a favorable opinion of him, 44 percent unfavorable. 
</P>
<P>
	``She's qualified, a smart lady. She's gone to law school. She's  
got a lot of ideas and had some nice health ideas,'' said Andrew 
Eckman, a 46-year-old manager of a comedy basketball team in 
Springfield, Mass. ``I pursue my dreams. She should be able to.'' 
</P>
<P>
	But some who thought it was appropriate for a president's spouse  
to run for office didn't want Mrs. Clinton to run for the Senate. 
</P>
<P>
	``If a person grew up in a state and then came back and wanted  
to run, that would be OK,'' said Leo Wiser, a 44-year-old carpenter 
in North Charleston, S.C., who was born near Binghamton, N.Y. 
``Every time I've heard Mrs. Clinton asked about what's going on in 
New York, she gravitates towards the city. I wonder if maybe she 
should try for representative of the city.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The sentiment for Mrs. Clinton to run and the number who think  
it is appropriate for a president's spouse to run dropped for 
respondents 55 and older. 
</P>
<P>
	``She should be a writer and lecturer,'' said Elizabeth  
Smothers, a 57-year-old Republican from Boaz, Ala. ``She'd be out 
there for everybody who wanted to pay to see her, but I would never 
have to hear from her again.'' 
</P>
<P>
	About one-third of those polled said they thought Mrs. Clinton  
would be most effective as a senator, with the remainder divided on 
whether she would have more influence as the head of a foundation, 
writer and lecturer or lawyer. Women and people with lower incomes 
were more likely to think senator would be her most effective role. 
</P>
<P>
	Mrs. Clinton's campaign would be ``so unique that I don't think  
it will tell us anything generally about women in politics,'' said 
Jean Bethke Elshtain, a professor of social and political ethics at 
the University of Chicago and specialist on women in politics. 
``She's a known figure, has instant recognizability and can draw on 
enormous resources from her husband's network.'' 
</P>
<P>
	But her out-of-state background could be a vulnerable point in  
New York, said Lee Miringoff, director of the Marist College 
Institute of Public Opinion in Poughkeepsie. 
</P>
<P>
	``Over half in our poll said this concerned them a great deal or  
somewhat. This will be one of the main targets of attack.'' 
</P>
<P>
	So far the race looks like the typical match-up between a  
Republican and a Democrat, he said, noting the natural strength of 
Democrats in New York City and the Republican base upstate. Since 
both are well-known, the campaign strategy will be more crucial for 
both than winning name recognition. 
</P>
<P>
	``Millions of dollars will be spent working on each other's  
negatives in a way that might be off the charts,'' he said. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
