<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Bond Prices Fall Again / Bonds  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Bond prices tumbled Friday, pushing up yields on  
30-year Treasury issues to the highest level in 19 months. 
</P>
<P>
	The price of the benchmark 30-year Treasury bond fell 1 3/16  
points, or $11.88 per $1,000 in face value. Its yield, which moves 
in the opposite direction, shot up to 6.16 percent from 6.06 
percent on Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	That was the highest closing yield for the long-term bonds since  
the 6.20 percent of Nov. 7, 1997. 
</P>
<P>
	Once again, fears of the Federal Reserve raising interest rates  
led to a selloff in bonds. 
</P>
<P>
	Traders, already nervous about the prospect that the Fed would  
push rates higher at a meeting at month's end, were further 
unsettled as rumors circulated that the Fed would act as quickly as 
Friday afternoon. There was also talk that Tiger Management LLC, a 
hedge fund, was seeking help from the Fed. 
</P>
<P>
	A Fed spokesman declined to comment, but traders said both  
rumors were quickly shot down. 
</P>
<P>
	The bond market has been preoccupied with the Fed amid concern  
that it will move to prevent the economy from overheating by 
pushing up interest rates. 
</P>
<P>
	If rates rise in the open market, the value of bonds already in  
circulation would fall. 
</P>
<P>
	There were fresh signs Friday of strength in an economy that  
already is in the longest peacetime expansion ever. 
</P>
<P>
	The Commerce Department reported that retail sales rose 1  
percent in May, extending a long string of gains. Also, the 
University of Michigan's consumer sentiment index rose to 
better-than-expected levels, showing that Americans remain upbeat 
thanks to the strong U.S. economy. 
</P>
<P>
	In the broader market, prices of short-term Treasury securities  
were off by between 3/16 point and 7/32 point and intermediate 
maturities were off between 9/32 point and 3/4 point, reported Bridge 
Telerate, a financial information service. 
</P>
<P>
	Yields on three-month Treasury bills were 4.72 percent as the  
discount surged 0.07 percentage point from Thursday to 4.60 
percent. Six-month yields were 5.08 percent, as the discount added 
0.06 percentage point to 4.88 percent. One-year yields were 5.12 
percent as the discount rose 0.03 percentage point to 4.87 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	Yields are the interest bonds pay by maturity, while the  
discount is the interest at which they are sold. 
</P>
<P>
	The federal funds rate, the interest on overnight loans between  
banks, fell to 4.75 percent from 4.81 percent late Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	In the tax-exempt market, the Bond Buyer index of 40 actively  
traded municipal bonds fell 19/32 to 119 1/16. The average yield to 
maturity rose to 5.54 percent from 5.51 percent late Thursday. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
