<DOCNO> APW19990611.0174 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-11 23:10:12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Jury Awards Ex-Boxer $10.7M in Suit </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NASHVILLE, Tenn. (AP) -- The actual fight lasted just 70 seconds.  
The legal battle took several years. And Randall ``Tex'' Cobb won a 
$10.7 million purse. 
</P>
<P>
	A jury on Friday ordered Time Inc. to pay $10.7 million to  
ex-heavyweight boxer for a 1993 Sports Illustrated article that 
said he fixed a fight and shared cocaine with the loser. 
</P>
<P>
	``Tex has been a prisoner of this article for six years and  
there's no better feeling in the world than to have a jury come in 
and set the record straight,'' attorney George Bochetto said. 
``This jury set this man free.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Cobb, 46, said the story headlined ``The Fix Was In'' ended his  
boxing career and nearly sidelined his acting pursuits. The jury 
deliberated about four hours before awarding him $2.2 million in 
punitive damages on top of the $8.5 million in compensatory damages 
it awarded Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	The article described the 1992 bout between Cobb and Sonny  
Barch, a journeyman fighter and former Memphis State football 
player. The magazine said Cobb and Barch discussed how to throw the 
fight, with Cobb complaining of an injured shoulder and hoping to 
end the match quickly. 
</P>
<P>
	In the article, Barch said he told Cobb: ``I'm going to have to  
hit you to make it look good. But I won't hit your shoulder.'' 
Barch said that Cobb responded: ``Bubba, I appreciate it. I'll make 
it up to you,'' according to the article. 
</P>
<P>
	Barch allowed Cobb to hit him three times, dropping to a knee  
each time and triggering the three-knockdown rule, Sports 
Illustrated reported. Cobb was declared the winner by technical 
knockout 70 seconds into the fight. 
</P>
<P>
	The magazine also reported that Barch said he, Cobb and a fight  
promoter shared cocaine after the bout. Sports Illustrated reported 
that both Barch and Cobb had flunked post-fight drug tests and the 
fight was declared a no-contest. In a follow-up, Sports Illustrated 
said that Cobb had tested positive for marijuana. 
</P>
<P>
	Juror Steve Reynolds, a Nashville schoolteacher, said the story  
was unfair, slanted and ``based on a shady individual.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Steve Robinson, managing editor of CNN-SI and a former Sports  
Illustrated senior editor who worked on the story, said the verdict 
``shocked us.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``Our position is the story is accurate. The jury findings are  
not supported by the evidence,'' he said. ``We're very confident we 
will prevail on appeal.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Cobb, a former Nashville resident who now lives in Philadelphia,  
has had roles in several movies, including ``Liar, Liar,'' 
``Raising Arizona,'' ``Uncommon Valor'' and ``The Golden Child.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The $2.2 million in punitive damages is approximately how much  
Sports Illustrated made in net income per issue last year, 
according to testimony. Sports Illustrated, a subsidiary of Time 
Inc., published 52 issues last year and reported earnings of more 
than $112 million. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
