<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> FCC Looks To Improve Rural Internet </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Federal Communications Commission will  
consider ways to ensure high-speed Internet access in rural areas, 
including subsidizing the improvements and easing government 
regulations, the panel's chairman says. 
</P>
<P>
	The Internet ``is as important to rural America as the highway  
system was in the 1940s and 1950s and the railroads were at the 
turn of the century,'' Bill Kennard said Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	Kennard met for an hour with a group of farm-state Senate  
Democrats, led by Minority Leader Tom Daschle of South Dakota, who 
are pushing the FCC to subsidize high-speed Internet access in 
rural communities. Kennard said the commission would consider the 
idea but left a brief news conference without taking questions on 
the proposal. 
</P>
<P>
	The FCC will ask telecommunications companies whether it needs  
to ease regulations to improve Internet access in rural areas. The 
agency also plans to hold field hearings, he said. 
</P>
<P>
	He did not say what regulatory changes the commission would  
consider. 
</P>
<P>
	Under a 1996 law, rural areas are supposed to have  
telecommunications services that are ``reasonably comparable'' to 
those in cities, but it was left up to the FCC to decide how to do 
that. 
</P>
<P>
	The government already is handing out nearly $1.7 billion in  
subsidies to schools and libraries this year, including those in 
rural areas and inner cities, for a variety of telecommunications 
needs, including Internet access. 
</P>
<P>
	The FCC recently voted to boost that funding to $2.25 billion,  
despite concerns that it would cause higher telephone charges. The 
money is collected from phone companies, which usually pass on the 
fees to customers. 
</P>
<P>
	The senators say farmers, rural businesses and small-town  
health-care facilities need access to high-speed Internet services 
for transmitting graphics and large amounts of data. 
</P>
<P>
	``As the revolution in telecommunications continues to advance,  
we cannot let our country be divided into technological haves and 
have-nots,'' said Sen. Paul Wellstone, D-Minn. 
</P>
<P>
	Sen. Bob Kerrey, D-Neb., said, ``There are hundreds of thousands  
of jobs at stake. There's a way of life at stake in rural areas.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
