<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Retail Sales Up by 1 Percent in May </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Retail sales jumped by 1 percent in May as  
Americans got ready for summer with purchases from shorts to patio 
furniture. 
</P>
<P>
	The sales -- which represent about a third of the nation's  
economic output -- rose last month to a seasonally adjusted $242.2 
billion, the Commerce Department said today. 
</P>
<P>
	The May increase followed an April rise that, at a revised 0.4  
percent, was better than initially estimated, the government said. 
</P>
<P>
	Retail sales have climbed or held steady for 10 months running  
and were 7.8 percent higher than May of last year. 
</P>
<P>
	Unemployment near a 29-year low, steady income growth and stock  
market gains have whetted Americans' appetite for shopping. 
</P>
<P>
	The spending spree helped keep the U.S. economy growing at a  
strong 4.1 percent annual rate during the first three months of 
this year, despite economic turmoil elsewhere around the globe. 
</P>
<P>
	However, a 0.7 percent rise in consumer prices in April, the  
most in nearly nine years, has some analysts wary that if inflation 
continues, consumers might begin to trim their spending in 
response. 
</P>
<P>
	Gas prices have risen most sharply, and sales at gasoline  
service stations did drop in May, by 0.8 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	But most other retail categories showed strong increases in  
sales last month. 
</P>
<P>
	Sales of durable goods -- items expected to last three years or  
more -- jumped 1.8 percent in May, after slipping in March and 
April. 
</P>
<P>
	Automotive sales, up a big 2.5 percent, were a major factor.  
However, even without the often volatile autos category, total 
retail sales climbed 0.5 percent in May. 
</P>
<P>
	Furniture stores saw their sales increase by 1.1 percent in May.  
Building supply, hardware and garden stores' sales fell 0.5 
percent, but had been buoyed by a 1.5 percent April gain and remain 
strong. 
</P>
<P>
	Sales of nondurable goods, such as food and fuel, were up 0.3  
percent in May. 
</P>
<P>
	At apparel and accessory shops, sales have risen every month so  
far this year and in May were up by 0.5 percent. Department and 
general merchandise store sales recovered with a 0.9 percent 
increase, after dropping 0.3 percent in April. 
</P>
<P>
	Food and grocery store sales were up 0.7 percent in May, while  
bar and restaurant patronage held steady. At drug and other 
proprietary stores, sales increased 0.6 percent. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
