<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Pilot Guilty of Conspiracy in Crash </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	FORT STEWART, Ga. (AP) -- An Army pilot was convicted Friday of  
taking his wife and the wife of a co-pilot on an unauthorized 
helicopter ride in the Bahamas that ended in a crash that killed 
both women. 
</P>
<P>
	A military judge spared 38-year-old Chief Warrant Officer David  
Guido from prison time and dismissal from the Army, instead giving 
him a reprimand and a total of $10,000 in fines and forfeited pay. 
</P>
<P>
	Guido testified that he took his wife on the flight to reward  
her for her support and to share his love of flying with her. 
</P>
<P>
	``She knew how much aviation meant to me,'' he said through  
tears. ``She was an active participant in my career. I have never 
known a more supportive woman. Yes, it clouded my judgment and, 
yes, I paid the price.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The judge, Col. Kenneth Pangburn, found Guido guilty of  
conspiracy, misappropriating an aircraft and violating an Army 
regulation in the July 6 accident on Grand Exuma Island. 
</P>
<P>
	Guido's wife, Pam, and Rebecca Riddell, the wife of his  
co-pilot, Chief Warrant Officer Daniel Riddell, were killed when 
the UH-60 Blackhawk went down. 
</P>
<P>
	The men, assigned to Hunter Army Airfield in Savannah, were in  
the Bahamas on a drug-fighting mission. 
</P>
<P>
	Guido, of North Haven, Conn., was accused of conspiring with  
Riddell and a technician to sneak his wife and Mrs. Riddell aboard 
the helicopter. 
</P>
<P>
	Guido, a 19 1/2-year Army veteran, was acquitted of a charge of  
conduct unbecoming an officer. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think the judge saw the conduct for what it was and I  
appreciate his fairness,'' Guido said after the sentencing, as 
supporters shook hands and wiped away tears of joy. 
</P>
<P>
	Riddell pleaded guilty to wrongful violation of a military order  
and willful dereliction of duty. He still faces charges of 
conspiracy, making a false statement, wrongful appropriation of a 
military aircraft and conduct unbecoming an officer. He is awaiting 
court-martial June 29. 
</P>
<P>
	Sgt. William Westgate, who also was on the flight, was seriously  
injured in the crash. No date has been set for his court-martial. 
</P>
<P>
	During a hearing in March, one investigator testified the  
accident was caused by a ``pitch-back attack,'' a flying maneuver 
that causes the helicopter to abruptly change directions by 
spinning the tail. 
</P>
<P>
	Defense lawyers have said a mechanical failure was to blame and  
that the pilots did nothing dangerous. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
