<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Dollar Down As Stocks Fall </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- The dollar fell broadly Friday as traders got  
skittish watching weak foreign economies start to mend coupled with 
U.S. stocks and bonds falling as inflation prospects increased. 
</P>
<P>
	``With better performances outside of this country and prospects  
for tightening that were hitting the markets ... you saw the dollar 
falling as well,'' said Guillermo Estebanez, a foreign exchange 
economist at the Bank of America in San Francisco. 
</P>
<P>
	In late New York trading, the dollar was quoted at 118.08  
Japanese yen, down from 118.84 late Thursday. The euro was quoted 
at $1.0535, up from $1.0489. 
</P>
<P>
	Investors have bet on the dollar for months because of the  
strength of the U.S. economy and the weakness of the world's second 
and third largest economies. 
</P>
<P>
	Japan is suffering from its worst recession in 50 years and the  
11 European nations using the euro as their single currency are 
under stress because of double-digit unemployment and other 
economic ills. 
</P>
<P>
	Yet both Japan, the No. 2 economy, and Germany, the third  
largest economy and the economic engine of the European Union, 
received reports this week showing strong gross domestic product 
numbers. 
</P>
<P>
	``Immediately, that gives a better tone for those currencies,''  
Estebanez said. 
</P>
<P>
	Meanwhile, the Commerce Department reported Friday that retail  
sales rose a strong 1 percent in May, the 10th month of rising or 
steady sales, that made May 1999's retail sales report 7.8 percent 
higher than that of May 1998. 
</P>
<P>
	Even though economists note that other U.S. economic data are  
mild, they are concerned that consumer spending could touch off 
inflation. 
</P>
<P>
	Federal Reserve policy-makers are expected to consider raising  
interest rates at their next meeting, June 29-30, to slow the 
economy and fight inflation. They've already said publicly they 
have a bias toward raising rates because of the economy's 
direction. 
</P>
<P>
	While higher interest rates normally help support a country's  
currency, in this case higher rates would be perceived as a signal 
of an economy in trouble. 
</P>
<P>
	Stock and bond markets took all of those hints Friday. The Dow  
Jones industrial average fell 130.76 points to 10,490.51, sinking 
309.33 points, or 2.9 percent, for the week. U.S. Treasurys sold 
off steeply, sending the 30-year bond's yield to 18-month highs. 
</P>
<P>
	In other late trading, the dollar was quoted at 1.5141 Swiss  
francs, down from 1.5225, and 1.4618 Canadian dollars, down from 
1.4624. The British pound rose to $1.6176 from $1.6054. 
</P>
<P>
	Currencies of the 11 countries participating in the euro are no  
longer traded separately and are tied to the euro by a fixed rate. 
Based on the euro's latest exchange rate, the dollar was worth: 
1.8567 German marks, down from 1.8646; 6.2267 French francs, down 
from 6.2539; and 1,838.24 Italian lire, down from 1,845.02. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
