<HEADLINE> Ex-Prison Guard Settles Case </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	FRESNO, Calif. (AP) -- A former prison guard who claimed he was  
forced to retire after alerting authorities to brutality at a 
California prison has won a $1.7 million settlement from the state. 
</P>
<P>
	The Department of Corrections reached the settlement with  
Richard Caruso on Wednesday, after negotiations that involved Gov. 
Gray Davis. The department did not admit wrongdoing. 
</P>
<P>
	Caruso, 35, alleged in his lawsuit that prison officials forced  
him out after he and another officer went to the FBI in 1994 with 
evidence of brutality at Corcoran State Prison. 
</P>
<P>
	Caruso presented records surrounding the fatal shooting of  
inmate Preston Tate during a fight, a revelation that led to an 
investigation into violence at all 33 state prisons. 
</P>
<P>
	Caruso was a gun post officer assigned to Corcoran's notorious  
Security Housing Unit. Among his allegations were claims that 
guards staged fights between prisoners. 
</P>
<P>
	``His coming forward opened a Pandora's box to a prison  
subculture that was running amok,'' said Senate Majority Leader 
Richard Polanco, a Democrat. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
