<DOCNO> APW19990611.0183 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-11 12:50:19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Hechinger Co. files for Protection </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LARGO, Md. (AP) -- Hechinger Co., the home improvement retailer  
that has been struggling against rivals such as Home Depot, filed 
today for protection from creditors under Chapter 11 of the federal 
bankruptcy law. 
</P>
<P>
	The company will close 89 stores in 36 markets to reduce  
operating losses and focus on a core of healthier stores. The 
closures will leave about 117 stores operating in 21 states. 
</P>
<P>
	Hechinger said it will focus on larger stores and its Home  
Quarters outlets. The company said it will convert its remaining 16 
Builders Square stores to the Home Quarters format. 
</P>
<P>
	The company failed to make a $4.7 million interest payment on  
its unsecured debt May 15 and recently reported a loss of $228 
million for its quarter ended in April 3. 
</P>
<P>
	Analysts have said nervous suppliers are cutting back on credit,  
which has only intensified Hechinger's cash crunch. They say the 
retailer is clearly having trouble stocking store shelves during 
the warm months when homeowners are most eager to spend money for 
house and garden improvement projects. 
</P>
<P>
	In a related development, Kmart Corp. said today it will set  
aside $230 million to cover costs stemming from lease guarantees 
resulting from its 1997 sale of the Builders Square chain of stores 
to Hechinger. 
</P>
<P>
	Builders Square was one of four subsidiaries that Kmart sold or  
spun off a few years ago as part of a refocusing on its discount 
retail stores. Under that deal, Kmart said it would guarantee 
leases now worth $1.2 billion, of which $761 million is for 
Builders Square stores. 
</P>
<P>
	Largo, Md.-based Hechinger combined Builders Square with two  
other chains to create the third-largest home-improvement retailer 
behind Home Depot Inc. and Lowe's Cos. 
</P>
<P>
	Since then, Home Depot and Lowe's have added stores and boosted  
profits, while Hechinger has struggled. The company has been 
remodeling stores and shedding others, ending April with 206 
locations. 
</P>
<P>
	Kmart said today that up to 115 former Builder's Square  
locations may become Kmart's responsibility. Chairman Floyd Hall 
said the company would try to sublease most or all of the 
properties. 
</P>
<P>
	``While the precise outcome of the legal process remains to be  
seen, Kmart believes that, in light of the Hechinger's filing, it 
is appropriate to take charge at this time,'' Hall said. 
</P>
<P>
	Founded in 1911, Hechinger opened its first store in Washington,  
D.C., in 1919. The family-owned business grew into a local 
institution and one of the first large-scale home-improvement 
chains in the nation. 
</P>
<P>
	But the retailer is losing shoppers, just as the residential  
real estate and home-improvement markets are booming. 
</P>
<P>
	By the early 1990s, it was clear that the Hechinger family had  
failed to recognize the emerging threat posed by Home Depot and 
Lowe's, which were beginning to dot the countryside with 
superstores. When both rivals entered Hechinger's markets, the 
company lost valuable market share and never managed to win it 
back. 
</P>
<P>
	Hechinger was sold two years ago for $507 million to Leonard  
Green &AMP; Partners, a Los Angeles investment group. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990611.0184 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-11 07:30:28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Pope Addresses Polish Parliament </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WARSAW, Poland (AP) -- Pope John Paul II celebrated his  
homeland's decade of freedom today with an unprecedented speech in 
parliament, receiving a hero's welcome from Solidarity and 
ex-communist deputies alike. 
</P>
<P>
	``Oh, look what's happened to us!'' he exclaimed to ``all my  
dear fellow Poles,'' his hands outstretched in a gesture of wonder 
at the peaceful transformation from communism to democracy that his 
papacy helped inspire. 
</P>
<P>
	The packed chamber, including former communist leader Gen.  
Wojciech Jaruzelski and Solidarity founder Lech Walesa, gave him 
lengthy standing ovations and sang the national anthem, followed by 
the traditional ``Sto lat,'' or ``May he live 100 years,'' for the 
country's most beloved figure. 
</P>
<P>
	Even former communists knelt and crossed themselves as John Paul  
walked slowly into the marble-walled chamber to a throne-like chair 
set up just for him. 
</P>
<P>
	It was the first address by the Roman Catholic pontiff to a  
national parliament, and he offered the most political comments so 
far of his 13-day pilgrimage to Poland. 
</P>
<P>
	He gave the Vatican's full endorsement to Poland's efforts to  
join the European Union, a plan drawing growing public opposition 
due to the painful economic reforms necessary to qualify. 
</P>
<P>
	At the same time, John Paul said politics and economic  
development must be based on ethical principles and spirituality, a 
theme with particular resonance in a country where many people 
equate national identity with Catholicism. 
</P>
<P>
	``As we rejoice together at the positive changes taking place in  
Poland before our eyes, we cannot fail to recognize as well that in 
a free society, there also must be values which guarantee the 
supreme good of man in his totality,'' the pope said. ``Every 
economic change must help to build a world that is more human and 
more just.'' 
</P>
<P>
	At the end, he echoed his prayer from his first pilgrimage home  
20 years earlier, when he asked the Holy Spirit to ``renew the 
face'' of Poland. Those words are credited with helping spark the 
birth of Solidarity a year later, leading to the end of communism 
in 1989. 
</P>
<P>
	Stooped and slowed by age and frail health, John Paul spoke  
strongly today, the seventh day of his longest pilgrimage to a 
single country. His sometimes slurred speech and a shaking left 
hand have prompted speculation he may suffer from Parkinson's 
disease -- never confirmed by the Vatican -- but he has handled the 
rigorous schedule so far without problem. 
</P>
<P>
	After his visit to parliament, the pope met briefly with local  
religious leaders. 
</P>
<P>
	Poland's chief rabbi, Pinchas Menachem Joskowicz, asked the pope  
to remove a 26-foot cross from property bordering the former Nazi 
death camp Auschwitz. 
</P>
<P>
	Jews say the cross infringes on the memory of more than 1  
million Jews killed at Auschwitz and the nearby Birkenau camp. 
</P>
<P>
	Joskowicz thanked Polish officials for recently removing 300  
smaller crosses that had been erected near the large cross by 
radical Catholics. 
</P>
<P>
	``I have a favor to ask of Mr. Pope, to call on his people to  
also take this cross out of the camp,'' Joskowicz said. 
</P>
<P>
	John Paul's brief reply was inaudible.  
</P>
<P>
	The Vatican has repeatedly refused to get involved in the  
controversy. 
</P>
<P>
	Later today, the pope will pay tribute to Jewish victims of the  
Holocaust at Umschlagplatz monument in Warsaw, where thousands 
gathered along his route on streets decorated with huge banners and 
Vatican and Polish flags. 
</P>
<P>
	Religious unity has been a constant refrain of the pontiff's  
visit, and John Paul expanded that to call for social unity today. 
In Poland, miners, farmers and others are rebelling against 
widespread economic reforms intended to complete the transition 
from communism and prepare the country to join the European Union. 
</P>
<P>
	While abundant goods and a new geopolitical role in Western  
Europe -- which Poles have always considered their proper 
neighborhood -- represent improvements over the communist era, 
workers feel threatened by the unemployment and uncertainty 
accompanying the reforms. 
</P>
<P>
	``The exercise of political authority, whether in the community  
or in the institutions of the state, ought to be a generous service 
to man and to society, not a pursuit of gain by individuals or 
groups,'' John Paul said to applause. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990611.0185 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-11 07:30:28 </DATE_TIME>
