<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-11 21:10:16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> How To Prepare for Fed Rate Hike </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- It isn't just Wall Street that's jittery about  
whether Federal Reserve policy-makers will hike interest rates 
later this month to fight inflation. 
</P>
<P>
	Specifically, home buyers have been rushing to lock in mortgage  
rates, still historically low, before they have time to move 
higher. At the same time, home builders are said to be concerned 
about how a change in rates will affect their business, while also 
feeling the pinch of higher prices for construction materials. 
</P>
<P>
	``It is driving people in the market at a very brisk pace,''  
said Dorcas Helfant, who runs Coldwell Banker-Helfant Realty, a 
large residential brokerage firm in Virginia Beach, Va. 
</P>
<P>
	Helfant, also a former president of the National Association of  
Realtors in Washington, reports a sharp increase in buying activity 
during the month of June, with families snapping up homes and 
locking in mortgage rates earlier than usual for this time of year, 
something she believes makes prudent sense during economic 
uncertainty. 
</P>
<P>
	``They don't know what's going to happen in the next couple of  
weeks,'' she said. ``They're getting concerned.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Fed left an unclear picture about interest rates at the  
Federal Open Market Committee meeting on May 18, deciding against 
raising them for the time being but adopting a ``bias'' in favor of 
higher rates if inflation resurfaces. 
</P>
<P>
	Two FOMC meetings are planned for the summer -- June 29-30 and  
Aug. 24. 
</P>
<P>
	Some economic experts think that if the Fed does anything, it  
will be during the latter of the two dates and include only a 
modest upward adjustment in short-term rates. 
</P>
<P>
	They say there have been no clear signs that inflation is, in  
fact, getting out of hand. However, there has been some reason to 
worry, they noted. 
</P>
<P>
	The government reported last month that consumer prices rose  
sharply last spring, and this past week, the Japanese government 
reported a higher-than-expected increase in economic growth, which 
set off fears that Japanese demand for U.S. goods might swell. 
</P>
<P>
	``There's a greater chance than not that they'll keep rates  
steady at the next meeting unless there's a big inflation number,'' 
Michael Carliner, an economist for the National Association of Home 
Builders in Washington, said this past week. 
</P>
<P>
	``But clearly the bond market doesn't agree with our  
forecasts.'' 
</P>
<P>
	To be sure, the bond and stock markets have been rattled lately,  
with the Dow Jones industrial average losing nearly 300 points 
since mid-May and the Treasury's 30-year bond now yielding 6.16 
percent as of Friday, its highest level since Nov. 7, 1997. 
</P>
<P>
	As a result, mortgage rates have been heading higher.  
</P>
<P>
	The most recent weekly national survey of rates by Freddie Mac,  
the mortgage company, found 30-year fixed-rate mortgages climbed to 
7.51 percent for the week ending June 11, the highest level in 
nearly two years. 
</P>
<P>
	Rates have been rising for the past two months. Their low for  
the year was 6.74 percent at the end of January. 
</P>
<P>
	That's still historically low, noted Paul Havemann, vice  
president of HSH Associates, a Butler, N.J.-based mortgage research 
firm. Even so, he said, any increase is likely to hurt prospective 
home buyers who may be only marginally qualified for a mortgage. 
</P>
<P>
	``They may not be able to afford a higher rate,'' he said.  
``Every half a percent increase in rates will increase your 
mortgage payment about $50,'' based on a $100,000 mortgage at 
prevailing rates. 
</P>
<P>
	While low rates have helped spur housing sales to record levels  
in recent years, some economists think a slowdown might not be so 
bad for the overall economy right now. 
</P>
<P>
	``The housing market in some areas is pretty much overheated,''  
said Carliner, noting that home builders, while concerned about how 
higher rates will impact their business, have seen an increase in 
the cost of construction materials in recent months. 
</P>
<P>
	``A little bit of a slowdown probably won't be such a bad thing  
(to curb inflation).'' 
</P>
<P>
	Higher rates will help stem inflation by raising borrowing  
costs, which can ultimately hurt corporate profits. 
</P>
<P>
	All eyes on both Main Street and Wall Street will likely be on  
the next Consumer Price Index for the month of May, which will be 
released on Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	The most recent CPI index, which measures inflation on the  
consumer level, showed a 0.7 percent rise during the month of 
April, the biggest jump in about nine years. That put the inflation 
rate at 3.3 percent, vs. a 1.6 percent rate for all of 1998. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
