<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-11 07:20:29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Man Convicted in Big Pyramid Scheme </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- In what prosecutors called the biggest pyramid  
scheme in U.S. history, a businessman was convicted of cheating 
22,000 investors across the country out of $700 million. 
</P>
<P>
	Patrick Bennett and his wife sobbed after a federal jury found  
him guilty Thursday of 42 counts, including securities fraud and 
laundering more than $1 billion. The jury did not reach a verdict 
on 11 counts, including the most serious charge of conspiracy. 
</P>
<P>
	Bennett, 46, was held on no bail and faces at least 20 years in  
prison at his Sept. 13 sentencing. 
</P>
<P>
	``Clearly this trial has showed that Patrick R. Bennett is a  
total amoral individual who engaged in any criminal conduct that 
benefits him in any way,'' U.S. District Judge John Martin Jr. 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	Martin said the evidence showed Bennett ``has absolutely no  
respect for any law of any kind.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Prosecutors said the Bennett Funding Group enticed people in 46  
states to invest in office equipment leases that did not exist. 
</P>
<P>
	Bennett pocketed more than $13 million for himself, buying a  
racetrack near Syracuse and spending lavishly on gambling ventures, 
including $19 million for a gambling barge. He put the rest of the 
money into a variety of business ventures, some of which went 
bankrupt. 
</P>
<P>
	Defense lawyers maintained Bennett was overwhelmed by a mountain  
of confusing financing and was not running a massive pyramid scheme 
in which early investors are paid with money from newer investors. 
</P>
<P>
	Bennett's case spanned two trials. In the first, a jury  
convicted Bennett of perjury and obstructing a federal 
investigation of his company, but could not reach a verdict on the 
rest of the charges. 
</P>
<P>
	He admitted he lied to the Securities and Exchange Commission  
after the agency began investigating his company in 1993. 
Prosecutors said those lies stalled the SEC until 1996, causing 
investors to lose hundreds of millions of dollars. 
</P>
<P>
	``This scheme was particularly egregious because it victimized  
thousands of investors who believed the investments were among the 
most secure available in our securities markets,'' U.S. Attorney 
Mary Jo White said. 
</P>
<P>
	Bennett's brother, Michael Bennett, and seven other people have  
pleaded guilty to criminal charges in the case. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990611.0197 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-11 15:28:52 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Home Improvement Chain Files Ch. 11 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LARGO, Md. (AP) -- Hechinger Co., the home improvement chain that  
has struggled against rivals Home Depot Inc. and Lowe's Cos., plans 
to close 89 stores under a Chapter 11 reorganization plan filed 
Friday with U.S. Bankruptcy Court in Delaware. 
</P>
<P>
	The Largo-based retailer said it will focus on a core of 117  
healthier stores in 21 states. 
</P>
<P>
	One of the big victims was Kmart Corp., which sold its Builders  
Square chain two years ago to a venture that was combined with 
Hechinger. 
</P>
<P>
	Separately, Kmart said Friday it was reducing its earnings by  
about $230 million after taxes because it had guaranteed the 
Builders Square leases. It said that up to 115 former Builders 
Square locations may become Kmart's responsibility. 
</P>
<P>
	Hechinger said it will concentrate on larger Hechinger stores  
and its HQ-Home Quarters Warehouse outlets; the vast majority of 
the planned store closing are Builders Square stores. The company 
also plans to convert its remaining Builders Square stores to the 
Home Quarters format, under the Chapter 11 filing, which is subject 
to Bankruptcy Court approval. 
</P>
<P>
	``Filing for Chapter 11 and closing these unprofitable locations  
is the crucial first step in our efforts to remake Hechinger,'' 
said chairman Mark Adams. 
</P>
<P>
	Analysts have said nervous suppliers are cutting back credit,  
intensifying Hechinger's cash problems. The credit problems come at 
a bad time for Hechinger, which is having trouble stocking store 
shelves just as homeowners are most eager to spend money for home 
and garden improvements, analysts said. 
</P>
<P>
	Kenneth M. Gassman Jr., an analyst with Davenport &AMP; Co. in  
Richmond, Va., predicted that the reorganization would give 
Hechinger three years of life. 
</P>
<P>
	``They're getting to the point where they're not going to be  
able to compete successfully,'' Gassman said. ``I think they'll 
implode further.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Hechinger listed $1.3 billion in assets with liabilities  
totaling $1.4 billion. Those liabilities included $323 million in 
bond debt. The company said it would also seek up to $700 million 
in financing from BankBoston Retain Finance Inc. to continue normal 
business operations during reorganization. 
</P>
<P>
	The company failed to make a $4.7 million interest payment on  
its unsecured debt May 15 and reported a loss of $228 million for 
the quarter ending April 3. 
</P>
<P>
	Builders Square was one of four subsidiaries that Kmart sold or  
spun off as part of a plan to refocus on its discount retail 
stores. Under that deal, Kmart said it would guarantee leases now 
worth $1.2 billion, of which $761 million is for Builders Square 
stores. 
</P>
<P>
	Scott Campbell, an analyst for Detroit-based Roney &AMP; Co., said  
the deal would not hurt Kmart badly, noting many of the stores are 
in desirable locations with spaces large enough to lure warehouse 
retailers such as Sam's Club or Costco. 
</P>
<P>
	``The (retailers) would love to get these spaces,'' Campbell  
said. 
</P>
<P>
	Kmart stock dipped 6 1/4 cents Friday to close at $14.87 1/2 a share  
on the New York Stock Exchange. 
</P>
<P>
	Founded in 1911, Hechinger grew into a Washington, D.C.  
institution and one of the first large-scale home-improvement 
chains in the nation. 
</P>
<P>
	By the early 1990s, however, it was clear that the Hechinger  
family had failed to recognize the threat posed by Home Depot and 
Lowe's, which were beginning to dot the suburbs with superstores. 
</P>
<P>
	Hechinger was sold two years ago for $507 million to Leonard  
Green &AMP; Partners, a Los Angeles investment group. At the same time, 
Hechinger combined Builders Square with two other chains to create 
the third-largest home-improvement retailer behind its two rivals. 
</P>
<P>
	Since then, Home Depot and Lowe's have added stores and boosted  
profits, while Hechinger has struggled. The company has remodeled 
stores while closing others and had 206 locations in May. 
</P>
<P>
	Gassman said Hechinger erred by not building more large stores  
in far-flung, developing suburbs and by concentrating on 
established locations closer to big cities, which suffered from 
suburban sprawl. 
</P>
<P>
	Many Hechinger outlets also suffer from undersized  
lawn-and-garden centers, narrow, poorly lit aisles, disorganized 
stock and employees that aren't knowledgeable about the company's 
products, Gassman added. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think Hechinger did not listen closely enough to their  
customers,'' Gassman said. ``Those are the kinds of things that 
turn people off.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
