<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 7:50 p.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Russian Troops Enter Kosovo  
</P>
<P>
	PRISTINA, Yugoslavia (AP) -- An armored Russian column rolled  
into the Kosovo capital of Pristina to the cheers of crowds early 
Saturday, as NATO massed its own peacekeeping troops along the 
border apparently set to enter at dawn. There was shouting and 
fireworks as thousands of people crowded the main street of the 
city to greet the Russian soldiers, who arrived aboard trucks and 
troop transports. British and French NATO troops waited in 
Macedonia on Kosovo's southern border to enter as part of an 
international peacekeeping force authorized by the United Nations. 

</P>
<P>
	Clinton: U.S. Peacekeepers Due  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Peacekeeping troops should arrive in Kosovo  
soon, President Clinton said today, in order ``not to let some big 
vacuum develop.'' He spoke on PBS' ``NewsHour With Jim Lehrer'' in 
an interview from the Oval Office, after he returned from greeting 
American fliers at Whiteman Air Force Base in Missouri. Clinton 
expressed no concern about surprise Russian troop movements in the 
region. ``They were just prepositioning,'' Clinton said. 

</P>
<P>
	Albright Meets Refugees in Macedonia  
</P>
<P>
	SKOPJE, Macedonia (AP) -- Secretary of State Madeleine Albright  
assured ethnic Albanian refugees packed in a sweltering camp that 
NATO peacekeepers would help them return home ``to live a decent, 
normal life.'' To cheers, Albright declared Yugoslav President 
Slobodan Milosevic and the Serbs have given up control of Kosovo. 
``All the world knows about your suffering,'' she assured them. As 
Albright toured the Stenkovic camp, NATO troops made preparations 
to move into Kosovo to protect the returning ethnic Albanians. The 
deployments could begin Saturday. 

</P>
<P>
	Bush Launches Presidential Bid  
</P>
<P>
	CHICAGO (AP) -- Texas Gov. George W. Bush today launched his  
campaign for the Republican presidential nomination with two 
Midwest fund-raisers. ``See you in Iowa,'' he said after a private 
$1,000-a-plate luncheon at a Chicago hotel. Tomorrow, Bush visits 
Iowa, site of the nation's first caucuses. On Monday, he goes to 
New Hampshire, site of the first primary. 

</P>
<P>
	Actor DeForest Kelley Dead at 79  
</P>
<P>
	LOS ANGELES (AP) -- Actor DeForest Kelley, who played crusty Dr.  
Leonard ``Bones'' McCoy on ``Star Trek,'' died today. He was 79. 
Kelley died after an extended illness, said the Motion Picture and 
Television Country Home and Hospital. ``He represented humanity and 
it fitted him well,'' said Leonard Nimoy, who played Mr. Spock on 
the science fiction series. ``He was a decent, loving, caring 
partner and will be deeply missed.'' 

</P>
<P>
	Senators Disclose Their Assets  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- According to financial disclosure forms  
released today, many senators and their spouses are worth millions, 
a select few many times that. Among the richest in 1998 were John 
D. Rockefeller IV, D-W.Va.; Herb Kohl, D-Wis.; Edward M. Kennedy, 
D-Mass.; Frank Lautenberg, D-N.J., and freshman Peter Fitzgerald, 
R-Ill. The rank-and-file salary is $136,700, with floor leaders 
earning $151,800. 

</P>
<P>
	FBI Probes Computer E-Mail Bug  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- The FBI today tried to track the author of a  
file-destroying computer virus that has hit some of the nation's 
biggest corporations and infected tens of thousands of machines. 
Software companies posted new virus-killing programs on their Web 
sites to attack the Worm.Explore.Zip virus, which is disguising 
itself as a friendly piece of e-mail. It hit systems at companies 
such as Compaq Computer and Motorola and other major companies, 
including AT&AMP;T, Boeing and General Electric. 

</P>
<P>
	Computer Crash Halts eBay  
</P>
<P>
	SAN JOSE, Calif. (AP) -- A computer crash forced the online  
auction house eBay to suspend all bidding, frustrating millions of 
customers of one of the hottest businesses on both the Internet and 
Wall Street. The halt came after eBay tried to launch a revamped 
version of its Web site. The computer server went down last night, 
and eBay was still trying to reconstruct the data to get it running 
again this afternoon. 

</P>
<P>
	Dow Ends Down 130.76  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Stocks fell sharply today after a tame inflation  
report failed to temper worry that the Federal Reserve will hike 
interest rates. The Dow industrials ended down 130.76 at 10,490.51. 
On the NYSE, losers led gainers 1,712-1,304. The Nasdaq fell 36.74 
points to 2,447.88. 

</P>
<P>
	NL Suspends Mets Mgr. for 2 Games  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- The National League today suspended manager  
Bobby Valentine of the New York Mets for two games and fined him 
$5,000. After being ejected last night for arguing a catcher's 
interference call, he returned to the dugout with a fake mustache 
and glasses. The suspension was to start tomorrow, but Valentine 
appealed the ruling. 

</P>
<P>
	AP NewsBrief by HOWARD SINER  

  	   	
</P>
