<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 4:35 p.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NATO Troops Prepare To Enter Kosovo  
</P>
<P>
	BLACE, Macedonia (AP) -- NATO today said a ``substantial'' force  
will be in place in Kosovo by tomorrow afternoon. Britain's King's 
Royal Hussars Battle Group will enter Kosovo at dawn to move into 
the southern town of Urosevac and the provincial capital of 
Pristina, officials said. A media pool report said a British rapid 
deployment force had been put on alert earlier today to head off a 
possible landing by Russian forces ahead of NATO troops. In Moscow, 
U.S. Deputy Secretary of State Strobe Talbott was given new 
assurances the Russians will not move into Kosovo until details are 
agreed upon with NATO. 

</P>
<P>
	Clinton Praises U.S. Pilots  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- President Clinton today said Americans should  
be proud of the successful air campaign against Yugoslavia, but 
must be prepared for possible casualties as the difficult work of 
peacekeeping begins. In a visit today to Whiteman Air Force Base in 
Missouri, Clinton thanked B-2 pilots who flew 30-hour roundtrips to 
the Balkans. ``Thanks to you, the century is ending not with 
helpless indignation over such unspeakable cruelty, but with its 
opposite -- a ringing affirmation by free people of human dignity,'' 
Clinton said. 

</P>
<P>
	Senators List Financial Assets  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Senate has its share of multimillionaires  
with such familiar names as Rockefeller and Kennedy, but its 
leaders are far less wealthy, according to financial disclosure 
forms released today. The forms also disclose other nuggets, for 
example Hall of Famer Jim Bunning's baseball card-signing income 
and the value of 96-year-old Strom Thurmond's South Carolina burial 
plots. Their rank-and-file salary is $136,700, with floor leaders 
earning $151,800. Over in the House the speaker makes $175,400. 

</P>
<P>
	Mayors Push for Tough Gun Safety Law  
</P>
<P>
	NEW ORLEANS (AP) -- The U.S. Conference of Mayors is urging House  
Speaker Dennis Hastert to press for swift passage of legislation 
requiring higher age restrictions for all firearms buyers and 
background checks for all customers at gun shows. The mayors' 
proposal is more stringent than pending House legislation. Their 
plan includes raising the legal age of gun buyers from 18 to 21 and 
limiting purchases to one gun a month. 

</P>
<P>
	Economy Not Helping Smaller Cities  
</P>
<P>
	NEW ORLEANS (AP) -- The government's third annual ``State of  
Cities'' report says smaller American communities are not sharing 
in the economic boom enjoyed by mega-cities like New York and Los 
Angeles. Smaller and medium-sized cities are experiencing slower 
population growth, higher unemployment and growing poverty compared 
to larger communities, said Andrew Cuomo, secretary of the 
Department of Housing and Urban Development. The report was issued 
here in advance of the 67th annual Conference of Mayors. 

</P>
<P>
	Vatican, Lutherans End Dispute  
</P>
<P>
	GENEVA (AP) -- The Roman Catholic and Lutheran churches have  
ended a nearly 5-century-old dispute over how people achieve 
salvation, officials announced today. The accord represents ``a 
decisive step forward in the process of reconciliation,'' said Rev. 
Ismael Noko, general secretary of the Lutheran World Federation. 
The two sides crafted a compromise on ``justification,'' or how 
humankind achieves salvation. For the Lutherans, salvation depends 
on the grace of God, while Catholics maintain that good works are 
also involved. The declaration states that divine forgiveness comes 
``solely by God's grace'' and that good works flow from that. 

</P>
<P>
	Computer Crash Halts eBay Auctions  
</P>
<P>
	SAN JOSE, Calif. (AP) -- eBay, the online auction site, crashed  
this morning, suspending all bidding on the site. The so-called 
``personal trading community'' with more than 3 million users in 50 
countries was in limbo as the company struggled to rebuild a 
corrupted computer server. The halt, which came after eBay tried to 
launch a revamped version of its site, disrupted bidding on 
millions of collectibles and curios, from military medals to 
mandolins. Bidding was stopped last night and is not expected to 
start up again until this afternoon. 

</P>
<P>
	Dow Ends Down 130.76  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Stocks fell sharply today after a tame inflation  
report failed to temper worry that the Federal Reserve will hike 
interest rates. The Dow industrials ended down 130.76 at 10,490.51. 
On the NYSE, losers led gainers 1,712-1,304. The Nasdaq fell 37.06 
points to 2,447.56. 

</P>
<P>
	New Spring Football League Forms  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Five NFL cities will make up the 13-team, new  
spring football league called the International Football 
Federation. New York, Chicago, Detroit, Boston and Denver are the 
existing pro towns. The others include two in the Los Angeles area 
and franchises in Toronto, San Jose, Calif., Texas, Toronto and 
Connecticut -- and a last-minute entry -- Honolulu. The league hopes 
to start in February. 

</P>
<P>
	AP NewsBrief by JEROME MINERVA  
  	   	
