<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Fla. Congresswoman Investigated </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The House ethics committee on Friday announced  
an investigation into ties between Rep. Corrine Brown, D-Fla., and 
a wealthy West African businessman convicted of trying to bribe a 
customs agent. 
</P>
<P>
	The committee will look into the businessman's gift of a $50,000  
Lexus automobile to Brown's daughter in 1997, the panel said in a 
statement. 
</P>
<P>
	It said it will also investigate ``lodging provided in 1997'' to  
Brown by the businessman, Foutanga Dit Babani Sissoko. An 
investigative subcommittee, to be headed by Rep. Dave Camp, 
R-Mich., was named to conduct a formal inquiry. 
</P>
<P>
	At the same time, the committee said it was dropping a variety  
of ``other issues'' that it had been investigating. It did not 
elaborate, but they apparently included Brown's acceptance of a 
$10,000 check from an indicted church leader and allegations of 
improper employment practices. 
</P>
<P>
	Brown, of Jacksonville, said in a statement late Friday that she  
was pleased the panel had dropped those ``groundless suggestions.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``Now, with the organization of the subcommittee to examine the  
only two remaining allegations, I can look forward to the 
resolution at long last of this whole matter,'' she said in the 
statement. ``I am confident that these charges, like so many others 
dismissed today, will also be finally put to rest.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The ethics committee said it wanted to determine ``the  
relationship, if any, between the lodging or car and Rep. Brown's 
status or actions as a member of Congress.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Federal laws prohibit members of Congress from receiving gifts  
in return for an official act. 
</P>
<P>
	Sissoko pleaded guilty in January 1997 to making a $30,000  
payoff to a U.S. Customs Service agent to improperly export two 
helicopters and was sentenced to a four-month prison term and house 
arrest. 
</P>
<P>
	Brown, 52, whose nine-county district runs from Jacksonville to  
Orlando, wrote two letters to Attorney General Janet Reno, lobbied 
colleagues in Congress and met with foreign diplomats on behalf of 
Sissoko. She later visited him in prison. 
</P>
<P>
	She allegedly stayed in a luxurious high rise condominium near  
Miami while trying to keep Sissoko out of prison. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
