<DOCNO> APW19990611.0201 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-11 14:49:39 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Aerospace Firms Seek Air Show Boost </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PARIS (AP) -- Fallout from the conflict in Yugoslavia and a drop  
in demand for commercial airliners have cast a shadow over the 
prospects of aerospace companies participating in the world's 
biggest air show, which opens Saturday near Paris. 
</P>
<P>
	Business for suppliers of fighter jets could suffer because  
Western governments face steep bills for their military involvement 
in the Balkans and may have less cash to upgrade air forces. 
</P>
<P>
	``My worry is that ultimately the whole Kosovo thing could kill  
the `peace dividend,' '' said Sash Tusa, a defense industry analyst 
with Goldman Sachs in London. 
</P>
<P>
	But companies are competing for expected replacement orders for  
bombs and missiles used in the conflict as well as spare parts for 
the fighters that flew thousands of sorties over Yugoslavia. 
</P>
<P>
	The battle for commercial aircraft business also is  
intensifying. Sales of civilian aircraft appear to have peaked, 
with the world's main builders of large passenger planes -- Boeing 
Co. and Europe's Airbus Industrie -- struggling to match last year's 
record of 1,200 airliners sold. 
</P>
<P>
	Amid this uncertainty, the Paris Air Show at Le Bourget airport  
north of the French capital will offer aviation companies one of 
their best opportunities to impress potential customers. 
</P>
<P>
	The event has attracted 1,765 exhibitors from 40 countries.  
French President Jacques Chirac is to inaugurate it, underscoring 
the aerospace industry's strategic and political significance. 
</P>
<P>
	The show, held every other year, will be an occasion for some  
companies to announce new contracts. Lockheed Martin Corp. of 
Bethesda, Md., even jumped the gun, announcing Thursday that it has 
awarded contracts worth $200 million to British suppliers of parts 
used in its C-130J Hercules heavy transport. 
</P>
<P>
	However, sales of aircraft and aviation equipment are normally  
completed after lengthy negotiations, and the weeklong show is less 
a place for participants to strike deals than to show off. 
</P>
<P>
	Among the potential crowd-pleasers: ergonomic pilot seats,  
rocket propulsion systems, unmanned surveillance aircraft and a 
device billed as the world's first miniature airborne VCR. 
</P>
<P>
	Seattle-based Boeing will hold flight demonstrations of its new  
100-seat aircraft, the 717-200, and visitors can see the 
Eurofighter, a jet built by a four-nation European consortium. 
</P>
<P>
	At stake are shares in an increasingly competitive industry.  
</P>
<P>
	``The export market is looking pretty dodgy as far as I can  
see,'' said Sanjay Jha, an analyst with the London-based brokerage 
Williams de Broe. 
</P>
<P>
	Demand for civilian aircraft is slackening in Europe and North  
America. The effects of financial crises continue to linger in East 
Asia, where air travel is just beginning to return to levels seen 
three years ago, and low oil prices have sapped the purchasing 
power of buyers in the Middle East. 
</P>
<P>
	``It appears that we may have reached a peak in the order cycle  
in 1998,'' said Dick James, head of Boeing's operations in Europe. 
</P>
<P>
	Boeing plans to deliver 620 planes to customers this year but  
only 480 in 2000, a decrease of 23 percent. James said he expects 
the slackening in global demand to persist until 2002, further 
pinching the company's profit margins after the past two ``very 
difficult'' years. 
</P>
<P>
	Boeing had a loss of $178 million in 1997 and earnings were  
depressed in 1998. It has acknowledged that it is wasting billions 
of dollars on unprofitable businesses, which are under review. But 
profit surged in the first quarter of this year. 
</P>
<P>
	The market for military planes and equipment is tough as well,  
but for different reasons. 
</P>
<P>
	Western governments were just starting to place their first  
major aircraft orders since the Cold War when NATO bombers took to 
the air over Yugoslavia, causing a significant drain on spare parts 
and munitions. 
</P>
<P>
	``Every missile that's been fired has to be replaced,'' said  
Zafar Khan an aerospace analyst in London with the French bank 
Societe Generale. 
</P>
<P>
	One business that stands to benefit is Raytheon Co. of  
Lexington, Mass., maker of Tomahawk cruise missiles. Raytheon said 
last week that it expects to sell $1 billion in cruise missiles and 
other munitions as a direct result of the Kosovo conflict. 
</P>
<P>
	Producers of laser-guided bombs and other so-called ``smart''  
weapons also are likely to get a boost, and the 78 straight days of 
sorties flown by NATO jets suggest that alliance members will be 
spending large sums on maintenance work and engine overhauls. 
</P>
<P>
	As a result of these expenses, however, analysts say that  
tightfisted Western governments are unlikely to order lots of new 
planes. 
</P>
<P>
	Countries in Asia, Africa and Latin America look equally  
reluctant to splurge. 
</P>
<P>
	``None of these countries is awash in cash,'' said Jha, the  
analyst at Williams de Broe. ``The issue is, what is the threat? 
There are more pressing issues.'' 

  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
