<CATEGORY> political </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Hillary Clinton boosts Gephardt </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ST. LOUIS (AP) -- Hillary Rodham Clinton hasn't decided whether  
she wants to join Congress next year, but she left no doubt Friday 
about her choice to lead it. 
</P>
<P>
	The first lady spoke at a fund-raiser on behalf of House  
Minority Leader Dick Gephardt, heir to the speaker's chair if 
Democrats gain six more seats in November 2000. 
</P>
<P>
	Mrs. Clinton didn't mention her possible interest in the vacant  
U.S. Senate seat in New York, and Gephardt only hinted at it. 
</P>
<P>
	``Whatever she does, she will make a mark,'' said Gephardt, who  
is in his 12th congressional term representing St. Louis. 
</P>
<P>
	The event coincided with a fundraiser in west St. Louis County  
for Texas Gov. George W. Bush, a leading candidate for the 
Republican presidential nod. While both dinners were by invitation 
only, the Bush event also excluded the media. 
</P>
<P>
	Some contributors spent $1,000 each to see Bush earlier in the  
evening at a private estate and then hurried downtown to the 
America's Center to pay the same price for the Gephardt rally. 
</P>
<P>
	If the crowd at the Gephardt event was bipartisan, it didn't  
sound like it. There were cheers every time the term ``Speaker 
Gephardt'' came up and hisses when a video showed former Republican 
Speaker Newt Gingrich. 
</P>
<P>
	Gephardt staff members said the event, which featured a  
30-minute concert by singer Natalie Cole, set a state record by 
raising more than $2 million. 
</P>
<P>
	About half of that money will go to Gephardt's re-election  
campaign, and half will go to other Democratic candidates. 
</P>
<P>
	Mrs. Clinton's speech was brief but full of praise for Gephardt  
and assurances that Missouri would benefit from having a Democratic 
speaker represent the state in Congress. 
</P>
<P>
	``That's what sets him apart from a lot of people in Washington  
who seem to get where they're going but then forget where they've 
come from,'' she said. 
</P>
<P>
	Gephardt called for lawmakers to ``stop destroying one  
another.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``We're going to have a new politics in your House of  
Representatives, of trust and decency and idealism, which is what 
we need in this country again,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Bill Federer, Gephardt's Republican challenger in 1998 and  
likely challenger next year, said the congressman shouldn't forget 
he has to stay in the House in order to become speaker. 
</P>
<P>
	Gephardt received only 55 percent of the vote against Federer  
last time despite far outspending him. 
</P>
<P>
	``This fund-raiser is a sign Gephardt knows he's going to need  
all the money he can get because I'm going to be like a bulldog 
after him,'' Federer said in a phone interview. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
