<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Woman Accused in Cosby Case Released </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	DUBLIN, Calif. (AP) -- Autumn Jackson was whisked out of prison  
by relatives without saying a word about her overturned conviction 
or the 14 months she spent in prison for allegedly trying to 
blackmail Bill Cosby. 
</P>
<P>
	``She's on her way home,'' said her New York attorney, Robert  
Baum, after the family drove up from Los Angeles to meet Ms. 
Jackson on Thursday at the minimum-security women's prison in this 
east San Francisco Bay suburb. 
</P>
<P>
	Among those greeting Ms. Jackson was her mother, Shawn Upshaw,  
who had an affair with Cosby in the 1970s and accepted more than 
$100,000 in financial support from him over the years. 
</P>
<P>
	Ms. Jackson, 24, had served 14 months of a 26-month sentence for  
extortion, conspiracy and crossing state lines to commit a crime. 
She had allegedly tried to blackmail Cosby out of $40 million, 
threatening to tell tabloid newspapers that she was his 
illegitimate daughter. 
</P>
<P>
	But the 2nd U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals ruled Wednesday that  
the trial judge incorrectly instructed the jury on the law of 
extortion. The court also overturned the convictions of two 
accomplices for the same reason, ordering a retrial. 
</P>
<P>
	Ms. Jackson made no public comments at the prison. At her  
sentencing in December 1997, she made a tearful apology, saying she 
should have stopped the plot. 
</P>
<P>
	``I knew Mr. Cosby held great expectations for me,'' Ms. Jackson  
said then. ``I let him down.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The case tarnished Cosby's wholesome image as America's faithful  
husband and father when he was forced to disclose the affair. 
</P>
<P>
	But he repeatedly denied he is Ms. Jackson's father. Cosby took  
a paternity test after the trial to try to settle the dispute, but 
Ms. Jackson and her mother declined to take blood tests. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
