<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Lawyer: Morgan Stanley Payment Legal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Morgan Stanley Dean Witter broke no federal or  
state laws when it paid $10,000 to an informant to set up a sting 
against a former employee, a company-sponsored investigation has 
found. 
</P>
<P>
	However, the law firm that examined the circumstances  
surrounding the operation against former junior analyst Christan 
Curry said that Morgan Stanley ``could have been more timely, 
cooperative and forthright'' in communicating with the Manhattan 
district attorney's office about the payment made to C. Joseph 
Luethke. 
</P>
<P>
	The latest chapter in what has become a public relations  
nightmare for the prominent Wall Street firm has resulted in two 
key personnel changes. 
</P>
<P>
	Christine Edwards, an executive vice president, managing  
director and the firm's chief legal officer, has stepped down from 
those positions, but will remain with the firm in a part-time 
advisory role, the financial services firm said Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	Monroe Sonnenborn, the managing director and general counsel of  
litigation and regulatory affairs -- and the senior-most employee 
directly involved with the payment, according to Morgan Stanley -- 
has resigned. 
</P>
<P>
	In a memo distributed to employees on Thursday, Morgan Stanley  
chairman and CEO Philip Purcell and president and chief operating 
officer John Mack said they were ready to move forward, according 
to a company statement. 
</P>
<P>
	``There is no denying that this has been a difficult time for a  
firm, requiring painful decisions by some of our best people,'' 
Purcell and Mack wrote. ``But with the completion of the thorough 
investigation ... we are ready to put this matter behind us and 
move on.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Curry, 25, who was fired by Morgan Stanley in April 1998, sued  
the firm in May for $1.35 billion, saying he was fired because of 
his race and because of nude photos of him that had appeared in a 
gay men's magazine. Morgan Stanley said he was fired for expense 
account abuses. 
</P>
<P>
	Four months after they fired Curry, company officials told  
police he was plotting to plant racist and homophobic e-mail in 
their computers. Curry was arrested last August on charges of 
forgery, coercion and computer trespass. 
</P>
<P>
	But the Manhattan district attorney's office dropped charges  
against Curry last month, and is now investigating Morgan Stanley 
and Luethke, in part because the firm had neglected to tell 
investigators immediately about the $10,000 payment to Luethke. 
</P>
<P>
	Subsequently, Morgan Stanley suspended Sonnenborn and Carol  
Bernheim, a principal in the firm's law department. On Thursday, 
the firm said Ms. Bernheim had been reinstated. 
</P>
<P>
	Wesley McDade, a spokesman for Morgan Stanley, said the internal  
investigation was completed and no more personnel moves would 
occur. 
</P>
<P>
	Morgan Stanley said it would continue to cooperate with the  
Manhattan district attorney and also defend itself against 
Christian Curry's lawsuit, which it said had no merit. 
</P>
<P>
	A message left for Curry's attorney, Earl Rawlins, was not  
immediately returned. 
</P>
<P>
	The outside law firm hired by Morgan Stanley-- Paul, Weiss,  
Rifkind, Wharton and Garrison -- said that Luethke presented himself 
to the firm in 1998 with information that he knew of a plot by 
Curry to plant racist and homophobic messages in the firm's e-mail 
system. 
</P>
<P>
	Luethke was a college acquaintance of Curry's who put Curry in  
touch with a computer hacker -- actually an undercover police 
officer -- at the same time he told Morgan Stanley about the plot. 
</P>
<P>
	He told Morgan Stanley he was putting himself at personal risk  
by exposing the plot, and that because the information about the 
fabricated evidence would save the firm some costly litigation and 
embarrassment, he was entitled to some compensation, Paul, Weiss 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	Rawlins has previously said that Curry paid a hacker $200 to  
plant phony e-mail. 
</P>
<P>
	Sonnenborn, after checking with another law firm, determined  
that as long as Luethke was not a witness to the Curry case, that a 
payment would be legal. Morgan Stanley eventually paid Luethke 
$10,000 ``in recognition of his assistance.'' 
</P>
<P>
	However, Paul, Weiss also determined that the district  
attorney's office was not made aware of the payment until six weeks 
after it had been made, saying it could ``find no satisfactory 
explanation for the failure to keep the district attorney informed 
of developments in the case.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Paul, Weiss said Mrs. Edwards, the chief legal officer, was  
unaware of a number of aspects regarding the payment, though she 
was informed about the payment about 24 hours before it occurred. 
She did not know until last month that the district attorney had 
issued two grand jury subpoenas to the firm in October 1998, the 
law firm said. 
</P>
<P>
	Paul, Weiss also said that neither of Morgan Stanley's top two  
officials, Mack and Purcell, were aware of the payment until April 
1999, eight months after it occurred. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990611.0213 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-11 18:30:13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Runner Marion Jones Returns to N.C. </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	RALEIGH, N.C. (AP) -- In Europe, fans ask for Marion Jones'  
autograph and the media crowds around her. 
</P>
<P>
	But in Raleigh, where she trains for track and field meets,  
physical education students and joggers pass her on the track with 
hardly a glance. 
</P>
<P>
	``We can go home to Raleigh and train in peace ... get on the  
plane and in six or seven hours you step off the plane -- you're a 
superstar,'' Jones, 23, said. 
</P>
<P>
	The world's top-ranked women's sprinter and long jumper competes  
mainly in Europe, which explains her relative anonymity at home. 
This week, she was in Finland and England. 
</P>
<P>
	But on Saturday, Jones and several other prominent U.S. athletes  
will share the spotlight in Raleigh at the Pontiac Grand Prix 
Invitational. The event will be at North Carolina State, where 
Jones trains six days a week. 
</P>
<P>
	Jones will compete only in the long jump. Her rivals include  
1996 Olympian Shana Williams. 
</P>
<P>
	Jones won the women's 200 meters at Helsinki Thursday night in  
21.91 seconds, .1 second off her seasonal best of 21.81. 
</P>
<P>
	``Everybody wants to see me run the sprints because those are  
the premier events,'' Jones said. ``This year ... we've made it a 
point to spend a lot of time on the long jump. 
</P>
<P>
	``I've improved on my technique, and I'm looking forward to  
jumping. It's great because I train in Raleigh every day. I'm quite 
familiar with that board and that pit, so this should be a good 
result.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Jones' best in the long jump is 23 feet, 11 3/4 inches. The U.S.  
record of 24-7 was set twice by now-retired Jackie Joyner-Kersee. 
The world record of 24-8 1/4 was set in 1988 by Galina Chistyakova of 
the then-Soviet Union. 
</P>
<P>
	Saturday's meet is the fourth in USA Track &AMP; Field's five-meet  
Golden Spike Tour. The tour culminates with the USA Championships 
June 24-27 at Eugene, Ore. The men will compete in the 100, 200 and 
400 sprints and the 110 and 400 hurdles. The women will compete in 
the 400 and 800, the pole vault and the long jump. 
</P>
<P>
	The meet will be held within the framework of the outdoor  
championships for high school athletes. 
</P>
<P>
	Jones, who plans to try for five gold medals at the 2000  
Olympics, hopes her success in the sprints and long jump will 
improve her sports' popularity in the United States. 
</P>
<P>
	She muses about the day when ``American athletes can stay at  
home and choose to go over to Europe and not have to go to 
Europe,'' she said. 
</P>
<P>
	``I would love to be able to stay in the U.S. for most of the  
year,'' she said. ``Right now, we don't have that option.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990611.0214 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-11 07:20:29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Sprouting Clover Seeds Recalled </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Fearing possible salmonella contamination,  
Pinetree Garden Seeds has voluntarily recalled its Sprouting Clover 
seeds. 
</P>
<P>
	The seeds, packaged in a 3 oz. plastic bag, were sold via mail  
order from the company's 1999-2000 seed catalog to customers in the 
United States and Canada. The individual bags were labeled ``SP9, 
Packed for 1999 Sprouting Clover'' and also were sold as part of 
the Sprouting for Health Gift Set. 
</P>
<P>
	The company, based in Gloucester, Maine, said Thursday that the  
seeds have been implicated by the Centers for Disease Control and 
Prevention in a salmonella outbreak in Colorado. 
</P>
<P>
	The company has not received any reports of illness. But it said  
customers should destroy any seeds purchased as well as any sprouts 
produced from the seeds. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990611.0215 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-11 15:00:18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Computer Crash Halts eBay Auctions </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SAN JOSE, Calif. (AP) -- MarGee Charlier knew her business was in  
trouble when she logged in first thing Friday morning and saw that 
eBay, the venerable online auction site, had crashed. 
</P>
<P>
	``Devastation,'' she said. ``Disaster.''  
</P>
<P>
	Charlier, of Kewaunee, Wis., supports her small business by  
selling between 50 to 100 antiques -- bringing in between $2,000 and 
$4,000 -- each day through the site. But not on Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	All bidding was suspended at eBay as the so-called ``personal  
trading community'' with more than 3 million users in 50 countries 
struggled to rebuild a corrupted computer server. 
</P>
<P>
	The halt, which came after eBay tried to launch a revamped  
version of its site, disrupted bidding on millions of collectibles 
and curios, from military medals to mandolins. 
</P>
<P>
	``We do realize how frustrating this is for our community, and  
we are doing our best to ensure that the system is restored as 
quickly and efficiently as humanly possible,'' said eBay spokesman 
Kevin Pursglove on Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	Bidding was stopped Thursday around 11 p.m. EDT and is not  
expected to start up again until Friday afternoon. As of 5:30 p.m. 
EDT, however, the site remained down. 
</P>
<P>
	EBay users were met at the site with a continuing stream of  
updates and apologies from management. ``Thank you so much for your 
patience as we resolve this unfortunate situation,'' said one 
message Friday morning. 
</P>
<P>
	The apologies weren't worth much to Sharon Doney in Severn, Md.,  
who is trying to raise $250,000 this year through online auctions 
of records and books to cover medical bills for her failing liver. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is frustrating,'' she said. ``Say you were at a real  
auction and the auctioneer just walked away for a while. It just 
doesn't work.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Doney said that problems on eBay -- short crashes, slowdowns and  
postponed auction endings -- during the past few months have already 
prompted her to branch out into other auction sites, including eBay 
competitors Amazon.com and Yahoo! 
</P>
<P>
	John Dodge, editor of PC Week, said the company has had ``daily  
failures every few weeks, but this one is the biggest.'' 
</P>
<P>
	One of eBay's worst previous outages, which lasted about six  
hours, prevented the company from holding auctions of just-released 
merchandise tied to the latest ``Star Wars'' movie. 
</P>
<P>
	The site outage was unrelated to the Worm.Explore.Zip computer  
bug, which began infecting systems across the country this week. 
</P>
<P>
	Andrew Bartels, senior research analyst at Cambridge,  
Mass.-based Giga Information Group, said outages should be expected 
in this type of burgeoning emerging technology. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's actually not that big of a deal,'' he said. ``This is  
still new technology and these high transaction sites will 
periodically go down.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Bartels said that eBay traders have less to lose than online  
stock brokers, who have also experienced site crashes in recent 
weeks. 
</P>
<P>
	But eBay users said the effect of the crash radiated well beyond  
the people who buy and sell trinkets on eBay. 
</P>
<P>
	Jeff Schlicht of San Mateo, Calif., whose software program  
called AuctionPoster makes it easy to list dozens or hundreds of 
items on eBay, said his customers thought there must be something 
wrong with his own program. 
</P>
<P>
	``EBay is definitely having growing pains, and that's a big  
problem for me,'' he said. ``I can't make excuses for them, but I 
depend on them.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``This is going to be a big boost for Amazon,'' he added.  
``Every single time stuff like this happens, customers start asking 
me when I'm going to design a system for another auction site.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Casual users appeared less affected, however.  
</P>
<P>
	Frank DeCaro, a writer in New York City who has bought  
everything from diet books to super hero glasses through eBay, said 
the crash would save him time and money. 
</P>
<P>
	``When you're buying junk, it's almost a blessing in disguise  
that you can't get to it,'' he said. ``It's really another day with 
a little less clutter for me.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Ebay is supposed to run 24 hours a day, seven days a week. It  
lists more than 2 million items, including antiques, books, 
computers, toys and sports memorabilia that can be purchased 
through a bidding process. 
</P>
<P>
	The company has struggled to keep up with a huge surge in demand  
-- registered users went from 1.2 million last fall to 3.8 million 
as of March 31. Those users bought and sold more than $541 million 
in merchandise through 22.9 million separate transactions during 
the first quarter of this year. EBay makes its money by taking a 
percentage on each sale. 
</P>
<P>
	For the first quarter of its 1999 fiscal year, eBay reported the  
increased volume on its Web site boosted its quarterly profit to 
$5.9 million, or 5 cents per share, making it one of the few 
consistently profitable Internet companies. 
</P>
<P>
	The company's stock has been traded publicly since late  
September, and its stock rocketed from $8.43 3/4 a share to $234 by 
April, but has since fallen by more than 20 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	News of the site outage sent shares tumbling more than 9 percent  
Friday. Ebay closed down $16.81 1/4 at $165.87 1/2 on the Nasdaq Stock 
Market. 


  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
