<DOCNO> APW19990611.0216 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-11 10:13:53 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Judge Considers Damages in SI Case </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NASHVILLE, Tenn. (AP) -- A federal judge is deciding whether  
Sports Illustrated alone is responsible for paying punitive damages 
for former boxer Randall ``Tex'' Cobb. 
</P>
<P>
	The issue is whether the magazine's parent, Time Inc., also can  
be held liable for the damages. 
</P>
<P>
	A jury has already awarded Cobb $8.5 million in compensatory  
damages as a result of his libel suit against the magazine. The 
jury was to begin determining punitive damages today. 
</P>
<P>
	U.S. District Judge Robert Echols heard arguments today over  
whether the damages should come from just Sports Illustrated or 
from its parent. 
</P>
<P>
	Sports Illustrated's attorneys told the judge the lawsuit was  
solely against Sports Illustrated, which has its own accounting 
division. 
</P>
<P>
	But Cobb's attorney said the magazine can not be separated from  
Time Inc. and that several of the parent company's resources were 
used in researching the story. 
</P>
<P>
	The jury must decide how much more the magazine should pay Cobb  
as punishment for a 1993 article that said the boxer fixed a fight 
and shared cocaine with the loser. 
</P>
<P>
	The jury awarded the compensatory damages Wednesday.  
</P>
<P>
	Cobb, 46, had asked for $50 million in compensatory damages and  
$100 million in punitive damages. Cobb, who declined to comment 
Thursday, has said the article ended his boxing career and nearly 
ended his acting career. 
</P>
<P>
	``Tex has been a prisoner of this article for six years and  
there's no better feeling in the world than to have a jury come in 
and set the record straight,'' Cobb's attorney, George Bochetto, 
said Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	An attorney for the magazine, Eddie Wayland, had no comment  
Thursday about the award. 
</P>
<P>
	Cobb sued in 1994 over an article headlined ``The Fix Was In.''  
The story began with an anecdote about the 1992 bout between Cobb 
and Sonny Barch, a journeyman fighter and former Memphis State 
football player. 
</P>
<P>
	The magazine reported that Cobb and Barch discussed how to throw  
the fight. The story said Cobb had an injured shoulder and wanted 
it to end as quickly as possible. 
</P>
<P>
	In the article, Barch said he told Cobb: ``I'm going to have to  
hit you to make it look good. But I won't hit your shoulder.'' 
Barch told Sports Illustrated that Cobb responded: ``Bubba, I 
appreciate it. I'll make it up to you.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Barch allowed Cobb to hit him three times, dropping to a knee  
each time and triggering the three-knockdown rule, Sports 
Illustrated reported. Cobb was declared the winner by technical 
knockout. 
</P>
<P>
	The magazine also reported that Barch said he, Cobb and a fight  
promoter shared cocaine after the bout. Sports Illustrated said 
Cobb had tested positive for cocaine use, but said in a follow-up 
item that it was marijuana. 
</P>
<P>
	Wayland told the jury that the article by writers William Nack  
and Sonja Steptoe was accurate and that any damage done to Cobb's 
reputation was the result of his own actions. 
</P>
<P>
	``They believed the story was true. They believed it then and  
they believe it now,'' Wayland said. 
</P>
<P>
	However, Ms. Steptoe testified last month she had little  
evidence that Cobb was a willing participant in a fixed fight with 
Barch. 
</P>
<P>
	Since he quit fighting, Cobb has had roles in several movies,  
including ``Liar, Liar, ``Raising Arizona,'' ``Uncommon Valor'' and 
``The Golden Child.'' He has also been in the TV shows 
``Moonlighting'' and ``MacGyver.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
