<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Ford Europe Operations Get New Head </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	DETROIT (AP) -- Ford Motor Co. named the architect of Jaguar Cars  
Ltd.'s revival to head its struggling European automotive 
operations Friday, the latest move aimed at improving the No. 2 
automaker's lackluster performance in what was once one of its 
biggest profit centers. 
</P>
<P>
	Nick Scheele, most recently vice president for marketing, sales  
and service at Ford of Europe, replaces James D. Donaldson as 
president of the unit. Donaldson in turn was named group vice 
president in charge of global business development. The changes are 
effective July 1. 
</P>
<P>
	Ford has been fighting the steady erosion of its market share in  
Europe for the past few years. In the first quarter, its European 
operations only managed to break even. 
</P>
<P>
	``Ford has had a very disappointing performance for quite a  
substantial time now,'' said Charles Young, an industry analyst 
with J.D. Power-LMC International Ltd. in London. 
</P>
<P>
	The automaker this year has been expanding with a series of  
European acquisitions, led by the purchase of Sweden's Volvo Car 
Corp. It also bought Kwik-Fit, a British chain of service shops, a 
controlling stake in Norwegian electric-car manufacturer Pivco AS, 
and a share in the largest group of Ford dealers in the United 
Kingdom. 
</P>
<P>
	Donaldson also recently launched an effort to reorganize Ford of  
Europe and bring the new units into a more integrated structure. 
Ford president Jac Nasser said Scheele was ``committed to 
continuation of the policies started by Donaldson.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Details of the reorganization have yet to be worked out, but  
Donaldson suggested in a recent interview with the trade weekly 
Automotive News that Ford will return to a more autonomous European 
operation. Under the Ford 2000 global reorganization launched four 
years ago, Ford of Europe lost its regional autonomy 
</P>
<P>
	Ford has suffered in part from an aging product lineup as  
competitors, such as Germany's Volkswagen AG, have come out with 
hit new models. One exception is the Focus subcompact, but analysts 
say it hasn't been on the market long enough to determine if it 
will be a long-term success. 
</P>
<P>
	``The early indications are not entirely encouraging,'' Young  
said. ``What is very clear is that in all the other market segments 
they are losing share quite seriously.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Nasser acknowledged recently that Ford's European performance  
has been disappointing. 
</P>
<P>
	``Volvo helps, without any question, because it gives us greater  
economies of scale within Europe,'' Nasser said last month. ``It 
gives us a brand between Ford and Jaguar that we did not have 
before.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Scheele, 55, is highly regarded in the industry for the  
turnaround he engineered at Jaguar, the once-failing British 
producer of trouble-prone luxury cars. He was chairman and chief 
executive of Jaguar for seven years before moving to Ford of Europe 
in March. 
</P>
<P>
	Since Ford's purchase of Jaguar in 1989 for $2.5 billion, it has  
managed to maintain the unique styling and feel of Jaguar cars 
while improving their reliability, the result of its $3.5 billion 
overhaul of Jaguar's aged manufacturing system and model line. 
</P>
<P>
	Donaldson, 56, will be in charge of overseeing the direction of  
Ford's future automotive and non-automotive businesses. ``It is 
imperative to have a seasoned, experienced business person with a 
global perspective working on strategic issues affecting the 
company,'' Nasser said. 

  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
