<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Va. and Md. Plan High-Tech Corridor </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Business leaders will endorse an educational  
curriculum designed to encourage students to enter the high-tech 
industry and a new road and rail connection linking the technology 
corridors of northern Virginia and suburban Maryland. 
</P>
<P>
	Business leaders, public officials and educators, led by America  
Online Chief Executive Steve Case, also are expected to approve 
today a $30 million venture-capital fund to invest in local 
bioscience companies. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're not just a government town, in fact almost as many  
people are employed by private sector high technology firms as 
there are in the area's federal workforce,'' said Michael Heyman, 
secretary of the Smithsonian Institution. 
</P>
<P>
	He is among 250 executives invited to the Ronald Reagan  
International Trade Center in Washington to hear about the series 
of initiatives aimed at helping to make the region rival northern 
California's Silicon Valley. 
</P>
<P>
	``We've got the jobs, and the science, and when Congress wants  
to look at cutting edge technology they can stay right here,'' said 
Mary Anne Reynolds, the spokeswoman for the Washington Board of 
Trade. 
</P>
<P>
	Business leaders attending the conference will be asked to  
pledge at least $5 million initially to move the agenda forward, 
The Washington Post reported. 
</P>
<P>
	The Post quotes conference participants who said the resources  
of technology executives have energized a regional planning effort 
long stymied by the political rivalries dividing the District of 
Columbia, Maryland and Virginia. 
</P>
<P>
	According to a Potomac KnowledgeWay-Washington Board of Trade  
study, the information-communications sector of the regional 
economy now employs one out of seven workers in the greater 
Washington area. 
</P>
<P>
	The 328,000 jobs and 25,000 current openings eclipse the 340,000  
federal jobs the District of Columbia and 15 northern Virginia and 
suburban Maryland counties. 
</P>
<P>
	The more than 3,000 high-tech firms in Maryland, Washington and  
northern Virginia have annual sales of $90 billion, according to 
the Board of Trade. 
</P>
<P>
	Since last January, business leaders, elected officials, and  
educators have worked to identify ways to mobilize the area's 
academic and corporate institutions toward activism. 
</P>
<P>
	``We want employees who are stuck in traffic everyday to put  
more pressure on elected officials to force more cooperation on 
solving these gridlock problems,'' Reynolds said. 

  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
