<DOCNO> APW19990611.0226 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-11 16:40:13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Potato, Dancing Raisins Cut a Deal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CHARLOTTE, N.C. (AP) -- Spencer Sweetpotato and the dancing  
California raisins have declared a truce: Spencer will ditch the 
shades and saxophone and become a pugnacious cancer-fighter. 
</P>
<P>
	``I love Spencer,'' said Sue Johnson-Langdon, executive director  
of the N.C. Sweet Potato Commission. ``I loved the saxophone image. 
But it's not worth $100,000.'' 
</P>
<P>
	That's what court costs would have run had the commission  
decided to take on the California Raisin Marketing Board, she 
estimated Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	The North Carolina sweet potato promoters had used Spencer as  
its marketing mascot for two years without a peep of protest. 
</P>
<P>
	But then the raisin board last fall spotted Spencer with his  
saxophone and sunglasses in two trade newspapers. It complained 
that he looked suspiciously like its raisins, which the board spent 
$100 million promoting in the late 1980s. 
</P>
<P>
	``One guise of our ex-grapes is playing the saxophone with  
high-top sneakers,'' said raisin board spokeswoman Kathy Moulthrop. 
``We have that trademarked.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The raisin board, which is considering bringing back the dancing  
raisins, warned the commission in North Carolina, the nation's 
biggest producer of sweet potatoes, to cease and desist. 
</P>
<P>
	``We never did think Spencer looked like the dancing raisin,''  
said Johnson-Langdon, but the Sweet Potato Commission decided 
Spencer's image wasn't worth diverting one-fourth of the 
commission's entire yearly budget for legal fees. 
</P>
<P>
	The raisin lawyers talked to the sweet potato lawyers, and they  
came to an understanding. 
</P>
<P>
	Instead of a saxophone, Spencer will sport boxing gloves and  
become a cancer fighter. 
</P>
<P>
	The legal paperwork should be signed in the next two weeks,  
Johnson-Langdon said. 
</P>
<P>
	Celia Batchelor, whose 1995 fourth-grade class at the former  
Elvie Street Elementary in Wilson helped persuade lawmakers to make 
the sweet potato the state vegetable, admits she thought the 
sax-playing Spencer looked like the raisins. 
</P>
<P>
	``But I thought, hey, if you can get away with it, go for it.''  
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
