<HEADLINE> 1st Lady Cheers Yankees in D.C. </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Potential Senate candidate Hillary Rodham  
Clinton declared herself a fan of the New York Yankees and donned a 
baseball cap to show her allegiance to the pinstriped Bronx 
Bombers. 
</P>
<P>
	But the Yankees' owner said it's New York City Mayor Rudolph  
Giuliani, Mrs. Clinton's possible GOP rival in next year's Senate 
race, who's the real fan. 
</P>
<P>
	``He's a great fan. They don't come any better,'' George  
Steinbrenner said after a White House ceremony Thursday to honor 
the Yankees for their World Series title last year. 
</P>
<P>
	The sudden, keen interest in sports came after Mrs. Clinton  
spent a day in upstate New York, where she was greeted with signs 
reading ``Carpetbagger Go Home.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The first lady, who has never lived in the state, in considering  
running for the seat Sen. Daniel Patrick Moynihan will vacate when 
he retires next year. 
</P>
<P>
	Surrounded by Yankees at the White House event Mrs. Clinton  
beamed as shortstop Derek Jeter presented her with a team pendent. 
The first lady, who grew up rooting for the Chicago Cubs, smoothed 
down her hair and gamely tugged on a Yankees cap. President Clinton 
received a pinstripe jersey. 
</P>
<P>
	But despite the warm reception, Yankees pitcher David Cone had  
to agree with Steinbrenner in the battle of the fans. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think Mayor Giuliani probably has the edge right now, he's a  
lifelong Yankees fan,'' Cone said. 
</P>
<P>
	White House officials insisted it was just a coincidence that  
the event to honor the Yankees -- who won the series almost eight 
months ago -- had come just as Mrs. Clinton prepared to form an 
exploratory committee for the Senate race. 
  	   	
</P>
