<HEADLINE> Jury Awards Damages in Cobb Case </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NASHVILLE, Tenn. (AP) -- A jury today awarded Randall ``Tex''  
Cobb $2.2 million in punitive damages for a Sports Illustrated 
story saying the boxer fixed a fight and shared cocaine with the 
loser. 
</P>
<P>
	The U.S. District Court jury deliberated Cobb's demand for up to  
$100 million after Judge Robert Echols ruled that the panel could 
consider the financial resources of Time Inc., the magazine's 
parent, in determining the figure. 
</P>
<P>
	On Wednesday, the jury awarded Cobb $8.5 million in compensatory  
damages from Sports Illustrated. 
</P>
<P>
	When the award was announced today, Cobb shook hands with his  
attorney, who patted him on the head. 
</P>
<P>
	Cobb contended the 1993 magazine article ended his boxing career  
and nearly ended his acting career. 
</P>
<P>
	``Tex has been a prisoner of this article for six years and  
there's no better feeling in the world than to have a jury come in 
and set the record straight,'' Cobb attorney George Bochetto said. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
