<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Oil Prices Fall on Weak Demand </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LONDON (AP) -- Weaker global demand for oil offset production  
cuts by oil exporters, causing the price of crude to drop last 
month by more than $2 per barrel, the International Energy Agency 
reported Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	Oil inventories fell more slowly than expected, even though  
compliance with agreed production cuts by oil-producing countries 
improved to 90 percent from April's level of 82 percent, the agency 
said in a report faxed from its Paris headquarters. 
</P>
<P>
	Global crude production fell last month by 400,000 barrels per  
day to a new total of 73 million barrels per day. 
</P>
<P>
	However, a decline in seasonal demand for heating oil and other  
products together with uninterrupted exports from Iraq helped 
depress prices. OPEC's benchmark price for a barrel of crude 
dropped to $12.66 a barrel in May from $15 in April, the IEA said. 
</P>
<P>
	Last month's price decrease followed a $7 per barrel run-up  
during the previous 2 1/2 months. That earlier price jump resulted 
from an agreement by OPEC members and other producers to slash 
production by 2.1 million barrels per day in an effort to boost 
prices. 
</P>
<P>
	The IEA forecast that global demand for oil would rise this year  
to an average of 75 million barrels per day, an increase of 1.4 
percent above 1998. Much of the reason would be continued economic 
recovery in Asia, particularly in Japan and South Korea, it said. 
</P>
<P>
	Among OPEC's 11 members, only Nigeria, Kuwait and Algeria  
increased production in May, the IEA reported. 
</P>
<P>
	The IEA is part of the Organization for Economic Cooperation and  
Development, a group of the world' most developed nations. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990611.0242 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-11 02:00:12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Sunburn Kills Woman in Arizona </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PHOENIX (AP) -- An 86-year-old Alzheimer's patient was left on a  
nursing home patio in the Arizona sun long enough to suffer a 
sunburn that killed her. 
</P>
<P>
	Mary Miles, a patient at the SunRise Thunderbird Care and  
Rehabilitation Center, died Sunday from burns she suffered May 18 
to her feet, legs, arms and neck. Doctors had amputated her legs in 
trying to save her. 
</P>
<P>
	Investigators are trying to determine whether workers at the  
nursing home are culpable in the death. 
</P>
<P>
	Workers told state investigators that Ms. Miles was on the patio  
for an hour at most. Doctors said it would take at least several 
hours of sun exposure to get the third-degree burns she suffered, 
police said Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	The Department of Health Services is investigating how long Ms.  
Miles was in the sun and whether she was taking any drugs that 
would have made her more sensitive to light. 
</P>
<P>
	Workers said Ms. Miles was dressed in a T-shirt, pants and  
slippers, said Judy Sgrillo, who oversees nursing home licensing 
for the agency. 
</P>
<P>
	The nursing home's parent company, New Mexico-based Sun  
Healthcare Group, expressed sympathy for Ms. Miles' family and 
pledged to cooperate with the investigation. 
</P>
<P>
	``A part of what we have to do is deal with incidents like  
this,'' company spokeswoman Karen Gilliland told The Arizona 
Republic. ``It's important not to jump to conclusions when you hear 
about things. It's always more complicated than it seems.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In a separate incident, the state also is looking into beatings  
suffered by two men at the nursing home during the past month. A 
probe into the November death of another patient who had severe 
bedsores could not find enough evidence to reach a conclusion, the 
department said. 
</P>
<P>
	The department investigated at least 16 other complaints of  
abuse or substandard care at the facility in the past 18 months, 
records show. Investigators ruled that one complaint was unfounded, 
referred one case of verbal abuse of patients to prosecutors and 
could not find enough evidence to rule on the other 14 complaints. 

  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
