<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> St. Peter Seminary Moving to Neb. </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	DENTON, Neb. (AP) -- The only Roman Catholic seminary in the  
nation still emphasizing the celebration of Mass in Latin is moving 
from Pennsylvania to a conservative Nebraska diocese whose bishop 
once ordered people excommunicated for belonging to certain 
organizations. 
</P>
<P>
	The 60-student seminary of the U.S. branch of the Priestly  
Fraternity of St. Peter has outgrown the rented motel it uses in 
Paupack, Pa. The order broke ground in October for a new seminary 
on a hill near Lincoln and plans to start classes next year. 
</P>
<P>
	The site is in the diocese led by Bishop Fabian Bruskewitz, who  
in 1996 stirred controversy by ordering Catholics to quit groups 
such as Planned Parenthood, Catholics for a Free Choice and Masonic 
organizations. He threatened them with excommunication, the 
spiritual equivalent of the death penalty. 
</P>
<P>
	Many theologians criticized the decree as too broad; no other  
bishops followed his example. And the bishop himself said people 
must use their conscience to know whether they are affected; no one 
was publicly refused the sacraments. 
</P>
<P>
	The fraternity's leader, the Rev. Arnaud Devillers, said  
Bruskewitz's excommunication order did not affect his decision to 
relocate to Nebraska. But he defended the decree, saying some of 
the groups involved deceived people by claiming they were fully 
approved by the church. 
</P>
<P>
	Devillers' group serves people who dislike changes in the church  
brought about by the Second Vatican Council in the 1960s. Known as 
Vatican II, the council said that Mass should be said in local 
languages instead of Latin and that modern culture should be 
embraced. 
</P>
<P>
	The fraternity still offers Mass in Latin, with priests facing  
away from the congregation in a ceremony that stresses the mystery 
surrounding the belief that bread and wine in the Communion 
ceremony become Jesus Christ's body and blood. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990611.0246 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-11 22:40:11 </DATE_TIME>
