<HEADLINE> Grains Lower; Soybeans Higher / Board of Trade  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CHICAGO (AP) -- Grain futures prices fell and soybean rose  
slightly in trading Friday on the Chicago Board of Trade. 
</P>
<P>
	Analysts say grain traders were reacting to predictions of  
rainfall and milder temperatures across the Midwest. Such weather 
should promote early growth and potentially larger crops. 
</P>
<P>
	Farmers also are winding up the last of spring plantings.  
</P>
<P>
	Wheat also faced pressure by expected drying in winter wheat  
growing regions, which should allow harvesting of that crop to get 
back on track. 
</P>
<P>
	Soybean futures prices, while pressured by the weather, got a  
late boost when soyoil prices rallied. 
</P>
<P>
	In trading Friday, wheat for July delivery fell 1 1/4 cents to  
$2.58 1/2 a bushel; July corn fell 3 cents to 217 1/4 a bushel; July oats 
fell 3/4 cent to $1.24 a bushel; July soybeans rose 1 3/4 cents to 
$4.70 1/4 a bushel. 
</P>
<P>
	Meat and livestock futures were mixed on the Chicago Mercantile  
Exchange. 
</P>
<P>
	August live cattle rose .62 cent to 65.02 cents a pound; August  
feeder cattle rose .63 cent to 77.95 cents a pound; July lean hogs 
rose .58 cent to 53.95 cents a pound; July pork bellies fell .45 
cent to 47.17 cents a pound. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
