<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> College World Series Notebook </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	OMAHA, Neb. (AP) -- In high school, Jason Jennings was a catcher.  
In college, he became Baylor's ace pitcher and the Bears' top 
hitter. And on Thursday, Jennings was named Baseball America's 
player of the year. 
</P>
<P>
	Jennings, selected as the 16th overall pick in last week's  
amateur draft by the Colorado Rockies, also was named player of the 
year by Collegiate Baseball. 
</P>
<P>
	Baylor coach Steve Smith touted Jennings' skills as a cleanup  
hitter and a pitcher. Jennings hit .368 with 17 home runs and 68 
RBIs this spring and was 13-2 with a 2.58 ERA. The Rockies want him 
as a pitcher. 
</P>
<P>
	``I've been a two-way player my whole life,'' he said. ``But  
from here on out, I'll be a pitcher. I'm looking forward to it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Smith said he is looking forward to the day when the Rockies let  
Jennings hit. 
</P>
<P>
	``Jason is a great, great pitcher, but he is a hitter. They're  
never going to be able to take that out of him,'' Smith said. ``I'd 
like to see the look on the opposing pitcher's face when he leans 
back and plants his foot ... and opens up that wide stance. I think 
he's going to take some people by surprise.'' 
</P>
<P>
	If pitching -- and hitting -- don't work out in Colorado, Jennings  
said he has another alternative. 
</P>
<P>
	``I loved being a catcher,'' he said. ``If for some reason  
pitching doesn't work out, maybe I can ... make a last-gasp effort 
to be a catcher.'' 
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	 *SWEET 64:* The expanded NCAA tournament, from 48 to 64 teams,  
drew raves from the College World Series' eight coaches. 
</P>
<P>
	``The teams here are the hottest teams,'' Stanford coach Mark  
Marquess said. ``That's because of the new format. You can have one 
or two hot weekends and get here.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Oklahoma State coach Tom Holliday said the expanded format, in  
which 64 teams vie for the trip to Omaha at regional and then super 
regional sites, made the road to the CWS more difficult. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's a tougher road than it has been in the last 19 or 20  
years,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	``The new setup is fantastic,'' Marquess said. ``It's going to  
create more interest in our great game.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Cal State-Fullerton coach George Horton had complained after the  
Titans didn't land a super regional site. On Thursday, he said he 
welcomed the new system. 
</P>
<P>
	``For their first time through, they (the NCAA) did a fabulous  
job,'' Horton said. ``The right guys are here at this point in the 
season.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Seven of the top eight teams in the NCAA tournament reached the  
College World Series. The exception was Oklahoma State, whch was 
seeded second in the Wichita, Kan., regional. 
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	 *GLASS HOUSES:* The four Cal State-Fullerton players suspended  
from their team's super regionals for throwing rocks watched the 
series at home, on television and in uniform, Horton said. 
</P>
<P>
	Horton said he made the players -- who include pitcher Adam  
Johnson, scheduled to start Saturday against Stanford -- break the 
news of their suspensions to their teammates. 
</P>
<P>
	``It was a very emotional meeting,'' he said. ``The players  
promised to continue the season so they (the suspended players) 
could play again with the team. They met the rest of the team at 
the airport and there were tears and hugs.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Horton said the incident had received too much publicity,  
however, and the Titans are eager to get back to business. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's behind us now,'' he said.  
</P>
<P>
	Johnson, pitcher Marco Hanlon and infielders David Bacani and  
Chad Olszanski were suspended after throwing stones at cars during 
the team's regionals in South Bend, Ind. 
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	 *DEATH BY DOGPILE:* It is a football school, after all.  
</P>
<P>
	Three Florida State players were injured -- including freshman  
pitcher Blair Varnes, who tore a knee ligament -- during a 
celebration after the Seminoles' come-from-behind super regional 
victory over Auburn. 
</P>
<P>
	Pitcher Nick Stocks was kicked in the face, and the resulting  
swelling was deemed to be a glandular problem that required 
medication. A backup catcher's hand was injured and swelled. 
</P>
<P>
	``Other than that, it was a pretty good night,'' coach Mike  
Martin said. 
</P>
<P>
	Martin said Kevin Cash missed the super regionals -- and the  
treacherous victory celebration -- after he was hit in the eye 
during batting practice. He has been cleared to play in the College 
World Series. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
