<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Former QB Thanks NY Legislators </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) -- Two years after revealing that his infant  
son suffers from a debilitating disease, former Buffalo Bills 
quarterback Jim Kelly returned to the state Capitol to thank 
lawmakers for supporting medical research into the illness. 
</P>
<P>
	Hunter Kelly has Krabbe's disease, a degenerative disorder of  
the nervous system. It starts in the brain and impairs motor 
skills. 
</P>
<P>
	In 1997, the state Legislature allocated $25,000 for the  
Institute for Basic Research on Staten Island to study the illness 
after Kelly made a personal appeal for the financing. 
</P>
<P>
	``Right now, there is no treatment,'' Kelly said Thursday. But  
he said researchers were making progress and a cure would one day 
be found. 
</P>
<P>
	``There's no doubt,'' he said. ``And we're going to keep working  
until there is.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Kelly has helped raise more than $3 million for Krabbe's  
(pronounced Kra-BAZE) research with his Hunter's Hope Foundation. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
