<DOCNO> APW19990611.0264 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-11 15:40:12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> US To Test European Egg Products </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- No egg products from Belgium, France or the  
Netherlands, or animal feed made anywhere in Europe, can enter the 
United States without special safety testing, the government 
ordered Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	Belgian beef, poultry, pork, milk and byproducts were banned by  
most nations, including the United States, last week after it was 
discovered that large quantities had been contaminated by 
cancer-causing dioxin. The contamination apparently was caused by 
dioxin-laced animal feed. 
</P>
<P>
	The Food and Drug Administration, which oversees the safety of  
certain imported foods, had ordered eggs detained at the U.S. 
border in certain circumstances, too. But Friday's action upgrades 
that safeguard, the FDA said. 
</P>
<P>
	Under the tightened policy, importers would have to conduct  
certain special laboratory tests proving their products were not 
contaminated with dioxin or other carcinogens known as PCBs before 
they could be sold. 
</P>
<P>
	Aside from Belgium, the FDA added egg products from France and  
the Netherlands, and animal feed, pet food and animal feed 
ingredients from any European country because of questions about 
where the originally contaminated products were shipped. 
</P>
<P>
	The FDA called the move a precaution, calling it unlikely that  
U.S. consumers were exposed to harmful chemical levels. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
