<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Winter Wheat Output Falls 14 Percent </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Winter wheat production is down 14 percent  
from last year, primarily because of sharp drops in Kansas and 
other Southern Plains states, the Agriculture Department said 
today. 
</P>
<P>
	The nation's orange crop also is off sharply, down 28 percent  
from last year's record of 13.7 million tons. Florida's production 
is down 20 percent, while California's is off by half. 
</P>
<P>
	A steep drop in wheat prices last year spurred many farmers to  
turn to other crops. 
</P>
<P>
	Farmers are expected to harvest 36 million acres of winter wheat  
nationwide this year, 1 percent less than USDA forecast a month 
ago. 
</P>
<P>
	Production in Kansas is down nearly 100 million bushels this  
year, to 395.6 million. Production in Oklahoma is off 50 million 
bushels to 148.5. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
