Nasdaq Composite Index        2,447.56  - 37.06
Gold(final) -    $261.50    troy oz., NY Comex spot month Fri.
Silver(final) -   UNCH    troy oz., NY Comex spot month Thu.

</P>
<P>
	Computer Crash Halts eBay Auctions  
</P>
<P>
	SAN JOSE, Calif. (AP) -- All bidding was suspended at eBay today  
as the so-called ``personal trading community'' with more than 3 
million users in 50 countries struggled to rebuild a corrupted 
computer server. The halt, which came after eBay tried to launch a 
revamped version of its site, disrupted bidding on millions of 
collectibles and curios, from military medals to mandolins. Bidding 
was stopped yesterday around 11 p.m. EDT and was not expected to 
start up again until later today. The company's stock has been 
traded publicly since late September, and its stock rocketed to 
$234 by April, but has since fallen by more than 20 percent. News 
of the outage sent it tumbling today, down 16 13/16 at 165 7/8. 

</P>
<P>
	FBI Probes Computer E-Mail Bug  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- The FBI today tried to trace the source of a  
file-destroying software bug that has hit tens of thousands of 
computers, while software companies posted new virus-killing 
programs on their Web sites. The Worm.Explore.Zip bug disguises 
itself as a friendly piece of e-mail, similar to the recent Melissa 
virus, which infected hundreds of thousands of machines. However, 
there were signs today that it may not be spreading as fast as 
Melissa. Computer security experts were still trying to assess the 
outbreak, which even infiltrated computer systems at technology 
leaders such as Compaq Computer and Motorola, as well as major 
companies including AT&AMP;T, Boeing and General Electric. 

</P>
<P>
	Wholesale Inflation Eases in May  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Gasoline prices at the wholesale level fell  
2.7 percent in May, after rising a record 29.1 percent the month 
before. The sharp decline helped slow the overall wholesale price 
rise for May to 0.2 percent, down from 0.5 percent in April. Many 
analysts believe the moderation in wholesale prices will be 
reflected next Wednesday, when the consumer price report comes out. 

</P>
<P>
	Retail Sales Jump in May  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Retail sales jumped by 1 percent in May as  
U.S. consumers got ready for summer with purchases from shorts to 
patio furniture. The sales -- which represent about a third of the 
nation's economic output -- rose last month to a seasonally adjusted 
$242.2 billion, the Commerce Department said today. The May 
increase followed an April rise that, at a revised 0.4 percent, was 
better than initially estimated, the government said. 

</P>
<P>
	U.S. Panel OKs Tariff on Japan Steel  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- U.S. steel producers won a crucial ruling when  
the U.S. International Trade Commission approved punitive tariffs 
to combat low-priced Japanese shipments. Tariffs ranging from 18 
percent to 67 percent will be ordered by the Clinton administration 
within weeks. Those tariffs will effectively make Japanese steel 
more expensive to sell in the United States. The trade commission 
ruled 6-0 that Japanese pricing practices on hot-rolled carbon 
steel, the industry's main product, have or could hurt domestic 
producers. The Commerce Department previously declared the pricing 
illegal. 

</P>
<P>
	Delta Defers Delivery Boeing 777s  
</P>
<P>
	ATLANTA (AP) -- Delta Air Lines is deferring its remaining orders  
for new Boeing 777 planes because of a standoff in negotiations 
with its pilots' union. Delta began flying two of the wide-body 
jets May 1, but has already canceled four orders because of a lack 
of agreement with pilots who are seeking up to $319 an hour to fly 
the planes, based on their revenue-generating potential. A total 11 
orders have now been halted, Delta announced today. The carrier 
said it won't be able to schedule 777 flights after Nov. 1 because 
union rules allow the pilots to refuse to fly a new plane after six 
months without an agreement. 

</P>
<P>
	Delta Air Lines Offers Web Discount  
</P>
<P>
	ATLANTA (AP) -- Delta Air Lines is offering a 10 percent discount  
on flights to five southeastern U.S. states that are booked through 
the company's Web site. The discount, announced today, is subject 
to a three-day advance purchase requirement. It applies on 
economy-class flights to Alabama, Florida, Georgia, Mississippi and 
South Carolina. The online promotion lasts through Wednesday. Delta 
stock was down 1/4 at 57. 

</P>
<P>
	Aerospace Firms Seek Air Show Boost  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Fallout from the conflict in Yugoslavia and a  
drop in demand for commercial airliners have cast a shadow over the 
prospects of aerospace companies participating in the world's 
biggest air show, which opens tomorrow near Paris. Business for 
suppliers of fighter jets could suffer because Western governments 
face steep bills for their military involvement in the Balkans. But 
companies are competing for expected replacement orders for bombs 
and missiles used in the conflict as well as spare parts for the 
fighter planes. The show, held every other year, will be an 
occasion for some companies to announce new contracts. Lockheed 
Martin Corp. of Bethesda, Md., even jumped the gun, announcing it 
has awarded contracts worth $200 million to British suppliers of 
parts used in its C-130J Hercules heavy transport. 

</P>
<P>
	Hechinger Co. Files for Protection  
</P>
<P>
	LARGO, Md. (AP) -- Hechinger Co., the home improvement retailer  
that has been struggling against rivals such as Home Depot, filed 
today for protection from creditors under Chapter 11 of the federal 
bankruptcy law. The company will close 89 stores in 36 markets to 
reduce operating losses and focus on a core of healthier stores. 
The closures will leave about 117 stores operating in 21 states. 
Hechinger said it will focus on larger stores and its Home Quarters 
outlets. The company failed to make a $4.7 million interest payment 
on its unsecured debt May 15 and recently reported a loss of $228 
million for its quarter ended in April 3. 

</P>
<P>
	Ford Europe Operations Get New Head  
</P>
<P>
	DETROIT (AP) -- Ford Motor Co. named the architect of Jaguar Cars  
Ltd.'s revival to head its struggling European automotive 
operations, the latest move aimed at improving the No. 2 
automaker's lackluster performance in what was once one of its 
biggest profit centers. Nick Scheele, most recently vice president 
for marketing, sales and service at Ford of Europe, replaces James 
D. Donaldson as president of the unit. Donaldson in turn was named 
group vice president in charge of global business development. The 
changes are effective July 1. Ford has been fighting the steady 
erosion of its market share in Europe for a few years. 

</P>
