<DOCNO> APW19990611.0270 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-11 10:17:26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Russia To Reopen Hot Line With U.S. </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MOSCOW (AP) -- Russia's security chief said Friday he would  
resume contacts with his U.S. counterpart that were suspended when 
NATO launched airstrikes against Yugoslavia, a news agency 
reported. 
</P>
<P>
	Vladimir Putin, the secretary of President Boris Yeltsin's  
Security Council, said he would reopen a hot line link with U.S. 
national security adviser Sandy Berger, the Interfax news agency 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	The agreement was reached Friday between Putin and visiting U.S.  
Deputy Secretary of State Strobe Talbott. 
</P>
<P>
	Putin welcomed NATO's decision to suspend the bombing, and  
voiced hope that Russia and the United States would be able to 
develop better understanding and cooperation on key security 
issues. 
</P>
<P>
	``Whatever our differences on the most important issues, we  
agree that Russia and the United States should work actively to 
rectify and expand bilateral relations,'' Putin said, according to 
Interfax. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
