<DOCNO> APW19990611.0271 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-11 15:06:34 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Sabres Want To Give Buffalo a Title </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BUFFALO, N.Y. (AP) -- Jim Kelly knows all about the sting of  
defeat in championship games, and he's heard all the jokes about 
Buffalo and the Bills. 
</P>
<P>
	Now, he hopes, the Buffalo Sabres will put that to rest for  
good. 
</P>
<P>
	``People are always ragging on the Bills and the people of  
Buffalo about those Super Bowls,'' the ex-Bills quarterback said. 
``Maybe this will shut some people up.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Not since the Bills earned their fourth consecutive Super Bowl  
trip in 1994 have fans in these parts been so pumped, anticipating 
that ever elusive title. 
</P>
<P>
	A Stanley Cup win wouldn't erase the pain of the Super Bowl  
losses, but it could boost the psyche of a city dealt blow after 
blow for its perceived sports failures, harsh winters and economic 
hardships. 
</P>
<P>
	The possibility of a title started as the Memorial Day weekend  
was winding down. The roars of celebration pierced the night air, 
and few had to wonder what the fuss was about. 
</P>
<P>
	The Sabres had just scored on Dixon Ward's shot to the Toronto  
Maple Leafs' empty net. The Sabres were on their way to the Stanley 
Cup finals for the first time in 24 years. 
</P>
<P>
	``You could hear people screaming in the streets because they  
were so excited, and kids were yelling, and it was 10 o'clock at 
night,'' recalled Dave Pietrowski, who, like so many fans in 
western New York, had been riveted to the game on TV. 
</P>
<P>
	A week after Buffalo clinched the Stanley Cup berth, Dallas  
emerged as the Sabres' opponent. Dallas. The city that had broken 
Buffalo's heart not once, but twice, with consecutive Super Bowl 
victories after the 1993 and 1994 seasons. 
</P>
<P>
	Worse yet, the Dallas Stars, who were the NHL's best  
regular-season team, went into the finals heavily favored. The 
Sabres finished the regular season just seventh in their conference 
and have been underdogs throughout the playoffs. 
</P>
<P>
	Stars center Mike Modano openly wondered if the Stanley Cup  
finals, already awarded to Dallas in the minds of many, might prove 
a letdown. 
</P>
<P>
	Fan Bob Young was among the many who thought the Colorado  
Avalanche, the Stars' Western Conference rival, would have been the 
more desirable opponent. Simply put, if a Buffalo team falls again 
to a Dallas team, Young said, ``I don't want to hear about it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	After the Avalanche's Game 7 loss to Dallas, Woody Paige wrote  
in the Denver Post: ``It could be worse. We could live in Buffalo 
for obvious reasons and because (Buffalo) has never won a Super 
Bowl, an NBA championship, a World Series or a Stanley Cup (and 
likely won't again this season). Buffalo falls more than Niagara.'' 
</P>
<P>
	All that bashing takes a toll on a community's self-esteem.  
</P>
<P>
	``A Stanley Cup championship would give Buffalo a positive  
image; then, by inference, people would begin to think that there 
is something special about the city,'' said Arun Jain, a marketing 
professor at the University at Buffalo. ``After they take a longer 
look at Buffalo, they'll learn that the city has a lot to offer 
beyond professional sports.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Plus, it would just make the city's long-suffering fans feel  
better. 
</P>
<P>
	``I am the consummate loser,'' declared Pietrowski, a Sabres and  
Bills season-ticket holder. ``I went to Syracuse University. I've 
been to two Final Fours, a Sugar Bowl, four Super Bowls, and my 
team has never won.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The memories are hardly bad, though, he said, recalling the  
parties and camaraderie. And, win or lose the Stanley Cup, Buffalo 
fans aren't likely to start hurling themselves from the Peace 
Bridge over another missed chance. 
</P>
<P>
	``When the Bills are 8-8 or 16-0, it's virtually the same  
audience,'' Pietrowski said, pointing to the team's regular 
sellouts. ``It's the same thing with the Sabres. It wasn't too long 
ago we were drafting first in the draft and we finished last, but 
there were still 12,000 people at every game.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Rick Martin, a member of the last Sabres team to compete for the  
Stanley Cup, still lives in the area. He's not convinced a 
championship would do much for the city's image. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's a great town but the media likes to beat up on Buffalo.  
Even if they win it somebody will come up with some kind of 
negative spin,'' he said. ``They'll find a way to downplay 
Buffalo.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990611.0272 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-11 15:06:34 </DATE_TIME>
