<DOCNO> APW19990611.0275 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-11 08:00:32 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Abu-Jamal Asked To Tape Speech </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	OLYMPIA, Wash. (AP) -- A decision by Evergreen State College  
students to invite a Pennsylvania death row convict to send a taped 
speech for today's commencement has angered many -- from the slain 
policeman's widow to a powerful congressman. 
</P>
<P>
	Mumia Abu-Jamal is awaiting execution for the 1981 slaying of a  
Philadelphia police officer. The prison journalist and former Black 
Panther claims he was railroaded and has become a symbol for 
anti-death penalty groups. 
</P>
<P>
	House Majority Whip Tom DeLay, R-Texas, asked for a moment of  
silence on the House floor Thursday to protest the invitation, his 
spokeswoman said. 
</P>
<P>
	``America wonders why there are shootings in schools,'' DeLay  
said at a news conference this morning. ``Well, irresponsible 
institutions making celebrities out of killers are part of our 
problem.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``There is no justifiable reason for an institution of higher  
learning to have a convicted murderer speak to its students,'' 
DeLay said earlier. 
</P>
<P>
	DeLay said his ``heart goes out'' to Maureen Faulkner, widow of  
Officer Daniel Faulkner. Ms. Faulkner has said she plans to attend 
the commencement with a picture of her husband. 
</P>
<P>
	Evergreen President Jane Jervis said students chose Abu-Jamal to  
address the 800 graduates due to his efforts ``to galvanize an 
international conversation about the death penalty, the 
disproportionate number of blacks on death row and the relationship 
between poverty and the criminal justice system.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Gov. Gary Locke canceled plans to attend ceremonies at the  
state-supported school in deference to police. A group of local 
off-duty officers planned to protest the event. 
</P>
<P>
	Pennsylvania Attorney General Mike Fisher wrote to Jervis on  
Thursday, asking her to cancel the speech. 
</P>
<P>
	``It is an affront to the memory of Officer Faulkner, his family  
and all victims of violent crime for your institution to glorify 
this cop killer,'' he wrote. 
</P>
<P>
	Evergreen's student body has an activist legacy. Hundreds  
occupied a chamber at the state Capitol at the start of the Gulf 
War. Last year, students supporting Abu-Jamal attempted to shout 
down Vice President Al Gore as he spoke at a city park. 
</P>
<P>
	Abu-Jamal has appealed his case to the U.S. Supreme Court.  
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990611.0276 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-11 19:40:14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Washington St. Players Plead Guilty </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	COLFAX, Wash. (AP) -- Kevin Brown, a 1,000-yard rusher last  
season, and two other Washington State football players were 
sentenced to 30 days in jail after pleading guilty to felony 
residential burglary on Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	Brown, who ran for 1,046 yards as a sophomore last season; Ramin  
White, a freshman defensive back; and Jason White, a redshirt 
freshman wide receiver pleaded guilty in a plea agreement to 
stealing $1,900 worth of electronic gear from another student's 
apartment on May 16. The Whites are not related. 
</P>
<P>
	Under the plea bargain, prosecutors dropped a lesser count of  
felony theft. 
</P>
<P>
	Washington State coach Mike Price suspended the players after  
their arrest and has said that he'd kick them off the team if they 
pleaded guilty or were found guilty. Price was out of town Friday 
and unavailable for comment. 
</P>
<P>
	Each player was sentenced to 30 days in the Whitman County Jail,  
two years probation and 240 hours of community service. Each must 
pay $450 in restitution. 
</P>
<P>
	``This wasn't really much of a plea bargain,'' Whitman County  
prosecutor Jim Kaufman said. ``We felt this was a serious incident 
and we had a good case.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Prosecutors had recommended 90 days in jail.  
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990611.0277 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-11 07:30:47 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> DVD Cos. Allowed To License Patents </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Looking to technology that appears destined to  
replace VCRs and compact discs, the Justice Department gave the 
go-ahead Thursday for six manufacturers jointly to license patents 
so other companies can produce digital video discs and players. 
</P>
<P>
	Under an arrangement approved by the Justice Department's  
antitrust division, companies that make DVD-Video and DVD-ROM discs 
and players can use the technology owned by the six manufacturers. 
</P>
<P>
	Pooling the patents held by the six businesses will reduce costs  
for obtaining the technology, while raising little possibility of 
competitive harm, said Joel I. Klein, assistant attorney general in 
charge of the department's antitrust division, in a letter. 
</P>
<P>
	A DVD -- which is the same size as a CD but with seven times the  
capacity -- can hold a two-hour feature film. Nintendo's 
next-generation video game player will have DVD technology, as will 
Sony Corp.'s next-generation Playstation video game system. 
</P>
<P>
	Matsushita Electric Industrial Co. Ltd. -- one of the six  
companies -- will make DVD drives for Nintendo. Matsushita is the 
world's largest maker of consumer electronics with brands such as 
Panasonic and Quasar. 
</P>
<P>
	Toshiba Corp. will offer licenses on behalf of Hitachi Ltd.,  
Matsushita, Time Warner Inc., and Victor Co. of Japan Ltd. 
</P>
<P>
	The six companies plus four others established specifications  
for players to read the discs and convert them into images for 
screen display. 
</P>
<P>
	It is the second request for the Justice Department to approve a  
DVD-Video and DVD-ROM patent pool. 
</P>
<P>
	Last December, the department approved the pool formed by  
Koninklijke Philips Electronics N.V., Sony Corp. of Japan and 
Pioneer Electronic Corp. of Japan. 
</P>
<P>
	Sony is moving to DVDs for its next-generation of video games.  
</P>
<P>
	Under Justice Department procedures, organizations submit  
proposals to the antitrust division headed by Klein and receive a 
statement on whether the government will challenge the action. 

  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990611.0278 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-11 15:40:12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Manufacturer Recalls Drink Mixes </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	DETROIT (AP) -- About 12,500 cases of diet drink mixes, iced-tea  
mixes and sugar replacements are being recalled in Michigan, eight 
other states and Hungary because the products may contain pieces of 
aluminum metal, the U.S. Food and Drug Administration said. 
</P>
<P>
	Manufacturer Ontario Foods Inc. of Albion, N.Y., notified the  
FDA early last month and began recalling the product from store 
shelves in Michigan, Florida, Illinois, Massachusetts, Maryland, 
Nebraska, New Jersey, Ohio, Pennsylvania, and Hungary. 
</P>
<P>
	The recall is posted on the FDA's Web site.  
</P>
<P>
	Last week, the FDA determined the metal could cause at least a  
``temporary health problem'' to consumers. Because of this, it 
asked the manufacturer to conduct a Class 2 recall, which requires 
the product be removed from store shelves without requiring public 
notification. 
</P>
<P>
	``This does not present a serious health risk,'' Mark Leunig,  
vice president of Genesee Corp., owner of Ontario Foods, told the 
Detroit Free Press. 
</P>
<P>
	The products recalled are:  
</P>
<P>
	-- Meijer EXTRA Thin Quick Vanilla Creme, 15 ounces, lot 10599VA,  
case code 10599A. 
</P>
<P>
	-- ULTRA Diet Quick Vanilla Creme, 15 ounces, lot 9074VA/E0900,  
case code 9074A. 
</P>
<P>
	-- American Fare Low Fat Extra Thin &AMP; Trim Healthy Shake, 30  
ounces, lot V EXP 09/00A, case code 9076A and Lot V EXP 09/00A, 
case code 9081A. 
</P>
<P>
	-- Food Club Ultra Diet Plan, Vanilla Creme, 15 ounces, lot  
07199VA, case code 07199A. 
</P>
<P>
	-- American Fare Low Fat Extra Thin &AMP; Trim Healthy Shake, 30  
ounces, lot C EXP 09/00A, case code 9076A and Lot C EXP 09/00A, 
case code 9081A. 
</P>
<P>
	-- Food Club Ultra Diet Plan, Dutch Chocolate, 15 ounces, lot  
07199CA, case code 07199A. 
</P>
<P>
	-- Ultra Diet Quick, Dutch Chocolate, 15 ounces, lot  
9071CA/E0900, case code 9071A. 
</P>
<P>
	-- Ultra Diet Quick, Strawberry Delight, 15 ounces, lot  
9074SA/E0900, case code 9074A. 
</P>
<P>
	-- Shop Rite Natural Lemon Flavored Iced Tea Mix, 24 ounces, lot  
031101LTA, case code 031101A and Lot 041601LTA, case code 04160A. 
</P>
<P>
	-- Sprinkle Sweet Sugar Replacement, 2 ounces, lot 9067A, case  
code C908A. 
</P>
<P>
	-- Food Club Sweet Measure Sweetener with Aspartame, 2 ounces,  
lot 9069A, case code 9069A. 
</P>
<P>
	-- Stop &AMP; Shop Sweet Measure, two ounces, lot 9069A, case code  
9069A, lot 9070A, case code 9070A, and lot 9095A, case code 9095A. 
</P>
<P>
	-- Kroger Sweet Servings, 2 ounces, lot 030901A1, case code 9068A  
and lot 030901A2, case code 9068A. 
  	   	
</P>
