<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-11 18:50:16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Latin American Briefs /  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	QUITO, Ecuador (AP) -- Some 250 species of mammals, birds and  
reptiles are in danger of extinction in the mountains and jungles 
of Ecuador, ecologists said Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	Among the species facing extinction are condors, jaguars,  
otters, lizards, snakes and parrots, said Deborah Chiriboga, a 
biologist with the Nature Foundation. 
</P>
<P>
	The wildlife is threatened by the incursion of humans into their  
jungle habitat, she said. More than 120 mammal species and 150 bird 
species have become extinct in Ecuador since the 17th century. 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	MEXICO CITY (AP) -- More than 1,200 Mexicans have been driven  
from their homes by recent hailstorms and flooding, according to 
reports Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	Hail pelted neighborhoods in the Michoacan state capital of  
Morelia on Wednesday, blasting holes in laminated roofing and 
forcing some people to hide under tables for protection, the 
newspaper Reforma reported Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	Police in that western city said some 1,000 people were forced  
from their houses. Another 200 people in the north-central state of 
Zacatecas were also forced to evacuate due to flooding late 
Wednesday, the newspaper reported. 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	MEXICO CITY (AP) -- After spending 20 months in jail, four  
policemen have been cleared of charges that they participated in 
the death of six young men in 1997, newspapers reported Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	Judge Cleofas Lucas Perez on Thursday found the four men  
innocent after their attorneys established that they were not at 
the scene of the crime. 
</P>
<P>
	The six youths were taken into custody after a Sept. 8 shootout  
in a slum in central Mexico City. Their bodies were found days 
later with signs of torture and gunshot wounds. 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	SAO PAULO, Brazil (AP) -- A group of female inmates overpowered a  
lone male guard on Friday and escaped from an overcrowded precinct 
jail, police said. 
</P>
<P>
	Precinct chief Estela Cristina Bonjardim said 23 of the jail's  
50 prisoners escaped shortly after midnight from the two-cell 
facility in Sao Bernardo do Campo, an industrial suburb on the 
outskirts of Sao Paulo. The jail was built to hold no more than 16. 
</P>
<P>
	``One prisoner feigned illness and when the guard went to check,  
the women overpowered him, took his gun away and handcuffed him 
inside the cell,'' Bonjardim said. 
</P>
<P>
	None of the escapees, mostly drug dealers and petty thieves,  
have been recaptured, Bonjardim said. 
</P>
<P>
