<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Congress KO's Kosovo Fund Cutoff </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- President Clinton is promising Congress he'll  
soon be seeking funds to pay for U.S. participation in peacekeeping 
operations in Kosovo apart from the regular defense budget. 
</P>
<P>
	The operation will be performed ``without harming military  
readiness,'' Clinton said in a letter to all House members. 
</P>
<P>
	The late afternoon letter on Thursday helped diffuse a tense  
battle in Congress over a GOP effort to bar funds for any 
operations in Yugoslavia -- even peacekeeping in the province of 
Kosovo -- after Sept. 30. 
</P>
<P>
	``Congress would be the laughingstock of the world,'' if such  
legislation passed one day after the dramatic Kosovo peace 
agreement, said Rep. Ike Skelton of Missouri, the senior Democrat 
on the House Armed Services Committee. 
</P>
<P>
	In the end, the House voted 270-155 to remove the cutoff  
provision from a $288.8 billion defense spending bill. Voting in 
favor of keeping the ban were 142 Republicans and 13 Democrats. 
</P>
<P>
	The overall bill was then approved 365-58.  
</P>
<P>
	It contains a 4.8 percent military pay raise and measures to  
tighten security at the nation's nuclear weapons labs. It now must 
be reconciled with a similar bill that earlier passed the Senate. 
</P>
<P>
	While both bills are alike, there are important differences.  
</P>
<P>
	The House bill, for instance, would order U.S. troops home from  
Haiti at the end of this year. It also would authorize the military 
to be used in the war against drugs in border areas. Neither 
provision is in the Senate measure. 
</P>
<P>
	Clinton's letter promised to seek congressional funds ``in a  
timely manner'' for U.S. participation in an international 
peacekeeping force expected to include 7,000 Americans. He signed 
the letter ``Bill.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Defense Secretary William Cohen said the peacekeeping operation  
was likely to cost U.S. taxpayers $1.5 billion to $2 billion a 
year. Independent estimates put the range at about twice that. An 
estimate by the Center for Strategic and Budgetary Assessment 
estimated the price tag at $2 billion to $3.5 billion a year. 
</P>
<P>
	Republican skeptics said they wanted Clinton to put in writing  
his verbal promise to congressional leaders not to further deplete 
an already thinly stretched military budget with the Kosovo peace 
operation. He did. 
</P>
<P>
	Republicans also wanted assurances that no U.S. funds would be  
used to rebuild Serbia as long as Slobodan Milosevic remained in 
power. 
</P>
<P>
	Clinton pledged in his Thursday night Oval Office address to the  
nation that Serbs should know the United States would not help them 
rebuild ``as long as your nation is ruled by an indicted war 
criminal.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Rep. Floyd Spence, R-S.C., chairman of the House Armed Services  
Committee, and an original supporter of the restrictions on Kosovo 
funds, said the Clinton letter had eased his concerns -- and enabled 
him to vote to do away with the restrictive provision. 
</P>
<P>
	The letter ``changed the landscape,'' said John Feehery, a  
spokesman for House Speaker Dennis Hastert. Hastert also voted 
against the fund cutoff. 
</P>
<P>
	But Democratic leaders suggested the Clinton letter only gave  
Republicans political cover, protecting them from what would have 
been a major embarrassment. They said it only put in writing what 
Clinton had been saying and was almost identical to one sent to 
Congress the day before by Budget Director Jacob Lew. 
</P>
<P>
	``Congress has been criticized for its erratic Kosovo policy.  
This is our chance to be consistent,'' House Minority Leader Dick 
Gephardt, D-Mo., said in a House speech. 
</P>
<P>
	``We've won the war. ... We now have an opportunity to win the  
peace,'' Gephardt said. 
</P>
<P>
	In late April, the House refused to endorse, on a 213-213 tie  
vote, the NATO airstrikes then under way. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
