<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Bancorp Boots Telemarketers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MINNEAPOLIS (AP) -- U.S. Bancorp broke off its relationships with  
about 15 telemarketing firms, one day after the state filed a 
lawsuit alleging one of those deals broke the law. 
</P>
<P>
	Thursday's decision ends the bank's arrangements with marketers  
that sell nonfinancial services and appeared to be an attempt to 
quickly head off any customer revolt. 
</P>
<P>
	In a suit filed Wednesday, Minnesota Attorney General Mike Hatch  
accused U.S. Bancorp, the largest bank based in Minnesota, of 
illegally selling customer data to a telemarketing firm and 
pocketing $4 million in commissions and fees. 
</P>
<P>
	The bank denied it misused customer information and said the  
bank will vigorously defend itself against Hatch's allegations. 
</P>
<P>
	In full-page ads in today's Star Tribune and Saint Paul Pioneer  
Press, U.S. Bancorp Chief Executive John Grundhofer moved to 
counter the bad publicity with an open letter to the customers and 
communities the bank serves. 
</P>
<P>
	``There is nothing we value more than the trust you put in us.  
When that trust is called into question it's something we take very 
seriously,'' the letter said. 
</P>
<P>
	``As a result we're ending our participation in this and all  
similar types of marketing programs for nonfinancial products. By 
doing this, we retain our focus on providing banking, investment 
and insurance solutions,'' it said. 
</P>
<P>
	Bank spokesman Don Waage said executives decided that it was too  
confusing for customers to have the bank affiliated with sales of 
nonfinancial products. 
</P>
<P>
	Hatch accused the bank of fraud and false advertising and said  
it violated the federal Fair Credit Reporting Act because it shared 
bank information and data from credit bureaus with a third party 
while promising customers in writing that their account information 
would be kept confidential. 
</P>
<P>
	Federal law doesn't prohibit a bank from selling data, but  
prohibits the sharing of information obtained from a third party, 
such as credit bureaus. 


  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
