<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 10 p.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Russian Troops Go Into Kosovo  
</P>
<P>
	PRISTINA, Yugoslavia (AP) -- A convoy of Russian soldiers rolled  
into the Kosovo capital of Pristina early Saturday to the crackle 
of gunfire, honking horns and cheering Serb crowds, the force 
apparently defying what NATO said was an understanding that Russia 
not enter the province alone. Shortly after their entry -- just 
hours before NATO was to send its own peacekeepers into Kosovo -- 
Russian Foreign Minister Igor Ivanov said the troops had arrived 
``unfortunately.'' On CNN, Ivanov said: ``They have been ordered to 
leave Kosovo immediately and to await further orders.'' The Russian 
news agency ITAR-Tass said the decision for Russian troops to 
advance had been made by the Defense Ministry and the Yugoslav 
military. 

</P>
<P>
	U.S. Surprised by Russian Move  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The United States was surprised by the  
movement of Russian troops into the Kosovo capital of Pristina just 
hours after getting assurances that NATO peacekeeping forces would 
arrive first. ``As (Russian) Foreign Minister (Igor) Ivanov has 
said, it was an unfortunate mistake and the Russian troops will be 
withdrawn immediately,'' White House spokesman Joe Lockhart said. 
``We're pleased that they've agreed to rectify the situation. The 
constructive talks toward determining the Russian's role in the 
peacekeeping forces continue with (U.S. Deputy Secretary of State) 
Strobe Talbott in Moscow.'' 

</P>
<P>
	Albright Vistis Refugee Camp  
</P>
<P>
	SKOPJE, Macedonia (AP) -- Secretary of State Madeleine Albright  
assured ethnic Albanian refugees that NATO peacekeepers would help 
them return home ``to live a decent, normal life.'' To cheers, 
Albright declared Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic and the 
Serbs have given up control of Kosovo. ``All the world knows about 
your suffering,'' she assured them. As Albright toured the 
Stenkovic camp, NATO troops made preparations to move into Kosovo 
to protect the returning ethnic Albanians. The deployments could 
begin Saturday. 

</P>
<P>
	Bush Launches Presidential Bid  
</P>
<P>
	CHICAGO (AP) -- Texas Gov. George W. Bush today launched his  
campaign for the Republican presidential nomination with two 
Midwest fund-raisers. ``See you in Iowa,'' he said after a private 
$1,000-a-plate luncheon at a Chicago hotel. Tomorrow, Bush visits 
Iowa, site of the nation's first caucuses. On Monday, he goes to 
New Hampshire, site of the first primary. 

</P>
<P>
	Senators Disclose Their Assets  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- According to financial disclosure forms  
released today, many senators and their spouses are worth millions, 
a select few many times that. Among the richest in 1998 were John 
D. Rockefeller IV, D-W.Va.; Herb Kohl, D-Wis.; Edward M. Kennedy, 
D-Mass.; Frank Lautenberg, D-N.J., and freshman Peter Fitzgerald, 
R-Ill. The rank-and-file salary is $136,700, with floor leaders 
earning $151,800. 

</P>
<P>
	Online Auctioneer eBay Fixes Site  
</P>
<P>
	SAN JOSE, Calif. (AP) -- The online auction house eBay fixed its  
site tonight after a computer crash forced it to suspend bidding, 
frustrating millions of customers of one of the hottest Internet 
businesses. The halt came after eBay tried to launch a revamped 
version of its Web site. Its computer server went down last night 
and was up again tonight. The shutdown disrupted bidding on 
millions of items. 

</P>
<P>
	FBI Probes Computer E-Mail Bug  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- The FBI today tried to track the author of a  
file-destroying computer virus that has hit some of the nation's 
biggest corporations and infected tens of thousands of machines. 
Software companies posted new virus-killing programs on their Web 
sites to attack the Worm.Explore.Zip virus, which is disguising 
itself as a friendly piece of e-mail. It hit systems at companies 
such as Compaq Computer and Motorola and other major companies, 
including AT&AMP;T, Boeing and General Electric. 

</P>
<P>
	Dow Ends Down 130.76  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Stocks fell sharply today after a tame inflation  
report failed to temper worry that the Federal Reserve will hike 
interest rates. The Dow industrials ended down 130.76 at 10,490.51. 
On the NYSE, losers led gainers 1,712-1,304. The Nasdaq fell 36.74 
points to 2,447.88. 

</P>
<P>
	Actor DeForest Kelley Dies at 79  
</P>
<P>
	LOS ANGELES (AP) -- Actor DeForest Kelley, who played crusty Dr.  
Leonard ``Bones'' McCoy on ``Star Trek,'' died today. He was 79. 
Kelley died after an extended illness, said the Motion Picture and 
Television Country Home and Hospital. ``He represented humanity and 
it fitted him well,'' said Leonard Nimoy, who played Mr. Spock on 
the science fiction series. ``He was a decent, loving, caring 
partner and will be deeply missed.'' 

</P>
<P>
	Orioles Beat Braves  
</P>
<P>
	ATLANTA (AP) -- With disgruntled Albert Belle on the bench for  
the first time since 1996, Sidney Ponson pitched a five-hitter and 
the Baltimore Orioles knocked out Atlanta's Greg Maddux with a 
five-run sixth inning, beating the Braves 6-2 tonight. Belle's 
longest active major-league streak of consecutive games ended at 
392. 

</P>
<P>
	AP NewsBrief by HOWARD SINER  

  	   	
