<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Wholesale Inflation Eases in May </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Inflation at the wholesale level slowed  
significantly in May as gasoline prices retreated after a record 
price jump, the government said today. 
</P>
<P>
	The Producer Price Index, which measures inflation pressures  
before they reach the consumer, rose just 0.2 percent last month, 
down sharply from the 0.5 percent advance in April. 
</P>
<P>
	The moderation reflected a big drop in energy prices. Gasoline  
prices at the wholesale level, which had risen by a record 29.1 
percent in April, retreated somewhat in May, declining 2.7 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	Big increases in both wholesale and consumer prices last month  
set off inflation jitters in financial markets. 
</P>
<P>
	After consumer prices jumped 0.9 percent in April, a nine-year  
high, the Federal Reserve let it be known that it was now leaning 
toward raising interest rates to keep inflation from getting out of 
control. 
</P>
<P>
	Many analysts believe that the moderation shown today in  
wholesale prices will also be reflected when the government reports 
next Wednesday on consumer prices. But analysts cautioned if 
consumer prices don't ease, the Fed is almost certain to start 
raising interest rates at their next meeting on June 29-30. 
</P>
<P>
	In a separate report, the Commerce Department said today that  
retail sales jumped by a strong 1 percent in May as Americans got 
ready for summer with purchases of everything from shorts to patio 
furniture. 
</P>
<P>
	So far this year, inflation at the wholesale level is rising at  
an annual rate of 2 pervent after having been flat in 1998. The 
acceleration in price pressures this year reflects a rebound in 
energy. American motorists got a big price break last year as the 
Asian currency crisis created a glut of crude oil on world markets, 
driving down prices. 
</P>
<P>
	For May, the 2.7 percent drop in gasoline prices, the biggest  
decline since last December, offset increases in home heating oil 
and natural gas, leaving overall energy costs unchanged for the 
month following a 5.1 percent surge in April. 
</P>
<P>
	Motorists are already starting to see the price declines at the  
wholesale level at the pump. Surveys show that gasoline pump 
prices, after having risen for more than two months, have started 
to edge down slightly. 
</P>
<P>
	Food prices last month rose 0.5 percent after a big 0.9 percent  
drop in April. The May increase included a big jump in pork prices. 
Fruit prices were also up sharply, with big gains for grapefruit, 
lemons and pears. 
</P>
<P>
	However, vegetable prices fell last month as the price of  
cauliflower, squash and lettuce all posted big declines. 
</P>
<P>
	Excluding the volatile food and energy sectors, prices at the  
wholesale level rose a tiny 0.1 percent, matching the small 
increase in April. So far this year, the so-called core rate of 
inflation at the wholesale level has been flat, an even better 
performance than a 1.9 percent rate of increase in the first five 
months of 1998. 
</P>
<P>
	For May, auto prices posted a 0.7 percent jump, the biggest gain  
since last September. Women's and men's clothing prices also rose 
in May. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
