<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-11 01:10:13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Medical Devices Getting Y2K Checks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Food and Drug Administration is preparing  
a list of medical device makers with products that could have Y2K 
problems. 
</P>
<P>
	The FDA also may issue public warnings or suggest voluntary  
recalls if the agency finds medical devices that could malfunction 
on Jan. 1, 2000, the Health and Human Services deputy secretary, 
Kevin Thurm, said. 
</P>
<P>
	In extreme cases, he said, dangerous devices will be seized.  
</P>
<P>
	Thurm spoke Thursday at a hearing of the Senate's special panel  
on the year 2000 computer problem. The Senate, meantime, tried to 
finish work on a bill, eagerly sought by business and high-tech 
groups, that would limit the ability to sue over Y2K-related 
breakdowns. 
</P>
<P>
	The legislation would give companies a 90-day period to fix  
computer problems before lawsuits can be filed, encourage 
mediation, make it harder to file class action lawsuits and cap 
punitive damages that small businesses must pay. 
</P>
<P>
	The Clinton administration supports the idea of stopping  
frivolous lawsuits but has threatened a veto, saying the bill would 
hurt consumers and small businesses with legitimate legal claims. 
</P>
<P>
	The FDA action on medical devices came amid concerns that the  
health industry may be one of the most vulnerable to problems from 
computers that read only the last two digits in dates and mistake 
2000 for 1900. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
