<CATEGORY> entertainment </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Ricky Martin Rocks Rockefeller Center </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- About 3,000 people jammed the blocks around  
NBC's ``Today'' studio Friday to catch a live outdoor performance 
by Ricky Martin, the Puerto Rican singing sensation. 
</P>
<P>
	``It was so good. Now I can brag to all my friends,'' said a  
delighted 12-year-old Jennifer Rasmussen of Toms River, N.J., who 
woke up at 4 a.m. and played hooky from school to see Martin. 
</P>
<P>
	As the throng squealed and threw streamers and confetti, Martin  
performed his signature hit, ``Livin' la Vida Loca'' -- which means 
living the crazy life -- and two other songs on an outdoor stage in 
Rockefeller Center. 
</P>
<P>
	``He's just so hot,'' said Rocia Rivera, a 26-year-old tourist  
from Puerto Rico. 
</P>
<P>
	A few dozen fans camped out Thursday night to get a good spot.  
</P>
<P>
	``He's really cute, and I heard that he's sweet,'' said Christy  
Monior, 17, who came with three friends. ``It's a bonding 
experience.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Suzanne Martinez, 49, and her daughter, Alysa Monachelli, 29,  
have followed Martin around the country since he was 12 and singing 
with the '80s pop group Menudo. Ms. Monachelli's 4-year-old 
daughter, Ashtyn, knows every word to ``La Vida Loca.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``She's been dancing to his music since she was 1,'' Ms.  
Monachelli said. 
</P>
<P>
	Martin, 27, is enjoying success with his first English-language  
CD, titled simply ``Ricky Martin.'' It had the best-ever album 
debut by a Hispanic artist on the mainstream Billboard charts. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
