<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Delta Bars Delivery of Boeing 777s </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ATLANTA (AP) -- Delta Air Lines has grounded its lofty plans for  
the new Boeing 777 planes because of an ongoing pay dispute with 
pilots. 
</P>
<P>
	The carrier announced Friday that it has halted future  
deliveries of the wide-body jets designed for long hauls and may 
sell or lease the two planes it began flying May 1. The airline 
said it can't include the planes in its upcoming winter schedule 
because of disagreement with pilots, who are seeking up to $319 an 
hour to fly the 777. 
</P>
<P>
	``I regret the action Delta has had to take regarding the 777  
program. The 777 was an integral part of our fleet plan and would 
have contributed substantially to achieving our goals,'' said Leo 
Mullin, Delta's chief executive officer. 
</P>
<P>
	A spokeswoman for the Air Line Pilots Association said the  
pilots are being used as ``a convenient scapegoat.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``Since B-777 negotiations began in February, management has  
shown little interest in or commitment to reaching an agreement 
with the pilots,'' said Karen McGuffey, a spokeswoman for Delta 
pilots. 
</P>
<P>
	She said the company has barely moved from its opening offer  
``and has spent the majority of the negotiating period issuing 
ultimatums about the B-777 fleet.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The union has suggested that Delta's position may be related to  
a softening of the trans-Atlantic market on which many of the 
planes would have been used. 
</P>
<P>
	A total 11 orders have now been halted, Delta said, adding that  
it won't be able to schedule 777 flights after Nov. 1 because of 
union rules that allow the pilots to refuse to fly a new plane 
after six months without an agreement. 
</P>
<P>
	Delta said its winter flight schedule must be ready by about  
Aug. 1. 
</P>
<P>
	``We still hope to reach an agreement with our pilots, but we  
cannot risk a disruption to our customers and we have to be 
economically feasible,'' Delta spokeswoman Kay Horner said. 
</P>
<P>
	Delta said it has offered pilots ``an industry-leading  
package,'' including up to $239 an hour for captains. 
</P>
<P>
	The two sides plan to meet again next week, but there have been  
no new proposals in their last two sessions. ``The parties remain 
far apart,'' Delta said. 
</P>
<P>
	Delta has been using the Boeing 777-200 planes, which carry 277  
people, on London-Cincinnati service and Atlanta-Orlando flights. 
Those two planes could be sold or leased if no pilots' agreement is 
reached, Ms. Horner said. 
</P>
<P>
	To replace the four 777 orders that were canceled earlier, Delta  
has ordered four Boeing 767-300ER aircraft. The smaller plane seats 
197 passengers. 

  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
