<HEADLINE> Big Movers in the Stock Market  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Stocks that are moving substantially or trading  
heavily today on the New York Stock Exchange and Nasdaq Stock 
Market. 

</P>
<P>
                               *NYSE    	
</P>
<P>
	VF Corp., down 3 3/16 at 43  
</P>
<P>
	The Greensboro, N.C.-based apparel company expects  
second-quarter earnings to be 10 percent lower than a year ago. VF 
said results will include a charge of $10 million to $15 million 
for the costs of closing its Jantzen sportswear business. Excluding 
this charge, VF said the earnings will be flat with year-ago 
figures. 

</P>
<P>
	MGM Grand, up 3 3/4 at 46 7/8  
</P>
<P>
	The Las Vegas hotel and casino company said it will offer $50 a  
share to buy back up to 6 million shares or about 10 percent of its 
outstanding stock. 

</P>
<P>
	American Home Products, up 1 1/8 at 54 3/16  
</P>
<P>
	CompUSA, up 3/4 at 8 1/2  
</P>
<P>
	Both companies are cited as possible takeover targets in  
Business Week's ``Inside Wall Street'' column in the June 21 issue. 

</P>
<P>
	Federal Signal, up 3 3/4 at 21  
</P>
<P>
	The Oak Brooke, Ill.-based company expects second-quarter  
earnings to fall below Wall Street analysts' estimates. 

</P>
<P>
                              *NASDAQ   	
</P>
<P>
	eBay, down 7 11/16 at 175  
</P>
<P>
	The San Jose, Calif.-based Internet auction house's Web site  
crash amid an outage in a computer. 

</P>
<P>
	SteriGenics, up 6 3/4 at 26 1/4  
</P>
<P>
	The Fremont, Calif.-based company, which provides irradiation  
and sterilization services, will be bought by Ion Beam Applications 
of Belgium for $214 million. 

</P>
<P>
	Harbinger, up 2 at 12 7/16  
</P>
<P>
	The Atlanta-based company said second-quarter earnings will meet  
or exceed analysts' expectations. The company also said it expects 
results for the third quarter to be slightly ahead of estimates. 

</P>
<P>
	Advantage Learning, down 5 7/16 at 18 1/16  
</P>
<P>
	The Wisconsin Rapids, Wis.-based company, which provides schools  
with computerized learning information systems, will buy 
Generation21 Learning Systems of Denver, which develops software 
for Web-based training. 

</P>
<P>
	Closure Medical, down 2 at 26 3/4  
</P>
<P>
	SG Cowen Securities downgraded its rating of the Raleigh,  
N.C.-based maker of medical adhesive products, and slashed the 
company's 1999 earnings-per-share outlook, citing sluggish sales 
for its Dermabond wound-closing medicine. 


  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
