<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Chain Must Tell About Expired Items </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	OAKLAND, Calif. (AP) -- Rite Aid Corp. must inform California  
customers they may have purchased expired products, including 
condoms and baby formula, a judge ruled. 
</P>
<P>
	Superior Court Judge Harry Needham issued a temporary  
restraining order Thursday after district attorneys from three 
counties and one city filed a consumer protection lawsuit earlier 
this week. 
</P>
<P>
	The prosecutors said they inspected Rite Aid stores across the  
state and found that expired condoms, pregnancy tests, infant 
formula and children's medication were being sold. 
</P>
<P>
	Rite Aid has said it would increase efforts to educate staff of  
proper inventory procedure. The Camp Hill, Pa.-based company said 
it would keep following its policy of taking products off the shelf 
60 days before their expiration dates. 
</P>
<P>
	``The action sought today was really unnecessary because Rite  
Aid has been taking actions to solve this problem,'' the company 
said in a statement. ``Furthermore, there is nothing in the 
district attorney's arguments that even allege public harm.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Prosecutors said they notified Rite Aid in February that expired  
items were being sold and received written assurance that the 
practice would stop. 
</P>
<P>
	Continued inspections at 50 of Rite Aid's 660 California stores  
revealed that outdated products were still being sold, said Merced 
District Attorney Gordon Spencer. 


  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
