<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Gay Nominee Battle Escalates </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The White House is appealing to Senate  
Majority Leader Trent Lott not to block other nominees in an 
escalating dispute over the ambassadorial appointment of an openly 
gay businessman. 
</P>
<P>
	But the Mississippi Republican wants a pledge from Clinton he  
won't circumvent the Senate by announcing controversial 
appointments during short congressional recesses in the future. 
</P>
<P>
	``It has to be stopped,'' said Lott spokesman John Czwartacki.  
</P>
<P>
	Lott remains upset about the president's tactics in naming James  
Hormel, a San Francisco philanthropist and heir to a meatpacking 
fortune, as ambassador to Luxembourg without waiting for Senate 
approval, Czwartacki said Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	Still, the spokesman said, ``we expect this to be resolved''  
before the dispute threatens key nominations, including Lawrence 
Summers as treasury secretary and Richard Holbrooke as ambassador 
to the United Nations. 
</P>
<P>
	The dispute erupted a week ago when Clinton, tired of waiting  
for the Senate to act on his 1997 nomination of Hormel, installed 
him directly -- invoking a provision in the Constitution permitting 
such appointments during congressional recesses. 
</P>
<P>
	With his ``recess appointment,'' Hormel can serve without Senate  
approval until the end of the next session of Congress -- the end of 
2000. 
</P>
<P>
	Lott denounced the practice, suggesting he was blindsided. And  
Sen. James Inhofe, R-Okla., announced he would seek to block every 
presidential civilian appointment to protest the move. 
</P>
<P>
	White House chief of staff James Podesta, in a letter to Lott,  
took ``significant issue'' with Inhofe's assertion that Clinton 
demonstrated ``contempt for Congress and the Constitution'' in 
circumventing the Senate confirmation process. 
</P>
<P>
	``The debate on Mr. Hormel is not about constitutional  
authority, it is about a very small number of senators who believe 
that sexual orientation can disqualify an exceptional nominee from 
confirmation,'' Podesta wrote. 
</P>
<P>
	``It is unfortunate that Sen. Inhofe now finds cause for  
objection to this process,'' Podesta added. He urged Lott to resist 
joining Inhofe's protest and ``make certain that all of the 
president's nominees receive fair consideration before the full 
Senate.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Lott has said he agrees with Inhofe's complaints, even though it  
was not his ``inclination'' to place a hold on all other 
nominations ``indefinitely.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Czwartacki said Lott has not changed his position but wants to  
work out a deal with the White House under which the president 
would promise to refrain from springing on the Senate further 
high-profile recess appointments. 
</P>
<P>
	``Sen. Lott does agree with Sen. Inhofe that this practice of  
naming controversial appointments during short recesses without 
much prior consultation is a practice that can't be sustained. It 
has to be stopped,'' Czwartacki said. 
</P>
<P>
	Inhofe said he was only following a precedent set by Sen. Robert  
C. Byrd, D-W.Va., in 1985, when Byrd as minority leader blocked 
President Reagan's appointments until Reagan agreed to refrain from 
further recess appointments. 
</P>
<P>
	Lott wants the same sort of pledge from Clinton, Czwartacki  
said. 
</P>
<P>
	But Podesta, in his letter, said, ``Any fair reading of the  
record of that period demonstrates clearly that Sen. Byrd and 
Senate Democrats simply sought to secure the very consultation and 
courtesies now provided by this administration to Senate 
Republicans.'' 
</P>
<P>
	White House officials said Lott did get advance word of Hormel's  
recess appointment. Republicans said the word came shortly before 
the appointment was announced on the final day of the week-long 
Memorial Day recess. 
</P>
<P>
	By custom, any senator can place a ``hold'' on any nomination.  
But this usually is done on individual nominees, not en masse, and 
the Senate majority leader does not have to honor a hold. 
</P>
<P>
	Meanwhile, Democrats said that if Inhofe makes good on his  
threat, and it is honored by Lott, they will stage their own 
protest. 
</P>
<P>
	``We would have to respond as well,'' perhaps by seeking to  
block committees from meeting and stalling Republican-sought 
legislation, said Senate Minority Leader Tom Daschle, D-S.D. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990611.0295 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-11 15:14:00 </DATE_TIME>
