<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> White House Defends Nominations </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- President Clinton meant no contempt for  
Congress in appointing a gay businessman to a diplomatic post 
without Senate consent, the president's chief of staff told Senate 
Majority Leader Trent Lott in an effort to head off retaliation. 
</P>
<P>
	John Podesta appealed to the Mississippi Republican not to block  
other White House nominations in the escalating dispute over the 
appointment of James Hormel as ambassador to Luxembourg. 
</P>
<P>
	Lott remains upset about the president's tactics, Lott's  
spokesman John Czwartacki said Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	Still, Czwartacki said, ``we expect this to be resolved'' before  
it threatens key nominations, including Lawrence Summers as 
treasury secretary and Richard Holbrooke as ambassador to the 
United Nations. 
</P>
<P>
	The dispute erupted a week ago during Congress' Memorial Day  
recess, when Clinton, tired of waiting for the Senate to act on his 
1997 nomination of Hormel, installed him directly. Clinton invoked 
a provision in the Constitution permitting such appointments during 
congressional recesses. 
</P>
<P>
	With his ``recess appointment,'' Hormel can serve without Senate  
approval until the end of the next session of Congress -- the end of 
2000. 
</P>
<P>
	Lott denounced the practice, suggesting he was blindsided. And  
Sen. James Inhofe, R-Okla., announced he would try to block every 
presidential civilian appointment to protest the move. 
</P>
<P>
	Podesta took ``significant issue'' with Inhofe's assertion that  
Clinton demonstrated ``contempt for Congress and the Constitution'' 
in circumventing the Senate confirmation process. 
</P>
<P>
	``The debate on Mr. Hormel is not about constitutional  
authority, it is about a very small number of senators who believe 
that sexual orientation can disqualify an exceptional nominee from 
confirmation,'' Podesta wrote in the Thursday letter. 
</P>
<P>
	``It is unfortunate that Senator Inhofe now finds cause for  
objection to this process,'' Podesta wrote. He urged Lott to resist 
joining Inhofe's protest and ``make certain that all of the 
president's nominees receive fair consideration before the full 
Senate.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Lott has said that he agrees with Inhofe's complaints, even  
though it was not his ``inclination'' to place a hold on all other 
nominations ``indefinitely.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Czwartacki said Lott has not changed his position but wants to  
work out a deal in which the president would promise to refrain 
from bypassing the Senate with high-profile recess appointments. 
</P>
<P>
	``Senator Lott does agree with Senator Inhofe that this practice  
of naming controversial appointments during short recesses without 
much prior consultation is a practice that can't be sustained. It 
has to be stopped,'' Czwartacki said. 
</P>
<P>
	Inhofe said he was only following a precedent set by Sen. Robert  
C. Byrd, D-W.Va., in 1985, when Byrd as minority leader blocked 
President Reagan's appointments until Reagan agreed to refrain from 
further recess appointments. 
</P>
<P>
	Lott wants the same sort of pledge from Clinton, Czwartacki  
said. 
</P>
<P>
	But Podesta, in his letter, said, ``Any fair reading of the  
record of that period demonstrates clearly that Sen. Byrd and 
Senate Democrats simply sought to secure the very consultation and 
courtesies now provided by this administration to Senate 
Republicans.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The White House says it did give Lott advance word of Hormel's  
upcoming recess appointment. Republicans argued the word came 
shortly before the appointment was announced on the final day of 
the week-long Memorial Day recess. 
</P>
<P>
	By custom, any senator can place a ``hold'' on any nomination.  
But usually they are done on individual nominees, and not en masse. 
And the majority leader does not have to honor them. 
</P>
<P>
	Meanwhile, Democrats have said that if Inhofe makes good on his  
threat, and it is honored by Lott, they will stage their own 
protest. 
</P>
<P>
	``We would have to respond as well,'' perhaps by seeking to  
block committees from meeting and stalling GOP-sought legislation, 
said Senate Minority Leader Tom Daschle, D-S.D. 
</P>
<P>
	Daschle said this would lead to ``a messy set of circumstances  
if things aren't resolved.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
