<HEADLINE> Costner Will Attend College Series </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	OMAHA, Neb. (AP) -- The Titans made the College World Series, and  
Kevin Costner will come. 
</P>
<P>
	Cal State-Fullerton sports information director Mel Franks said  
the actor was scheduled to fly into Omaha on Saturday for the 
Titans' game against Stanford. 
</P>
<P>
	Costner, a Cal State-Fullerton alum, attended the series in 1995  
when the Titans won the championship. He was expected to arrive 
Saturday by private jet. 
</P>
<P>
	Franks said the star of ``Bull Durham,'' ``Field of Dreams,''  
``Dances With Wolves'' and ``Waterworld'' was hoping for just one 
thing in Omaha -- a game of catch. 
</P>
<P>
	``He wants to be in the dugout but the NCAA said no,'' Franks  
said. ``He's bringing his glove.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Costner's agent, Steven Rivers, confirmed late Friday that  
Costner would attend. Franks said Costner hoped to participate in 
infield or batting practice before Saturday's game between the 
Titans and Stanford. 
</P>
<P>
	``If they'd let him, he'd ride on the bus with them and take  
(batting practice) and everything,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	 *HIGHLIGHT REEL:* Call it the consequences of making the play.  
</P>
<P>
	Jason Van Arkel, 23, suffered a bruised knee when he fell  
backward over the left field wall while trying to keep a beach ball 
from floating onto the field at Rosenblatt Stadium. 
</P>
<P>
	``He's a hero,'' said Steve Lefeber, 42, of Omaha, another fan  
in the left field bleachers. 
</P>
<P>
	Van Arkel was helped off the field by grounds crew members but  
returned a short time later to cheers and a brief ovation. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't know how I'm a hero,'' he said sheepishly. ``I just  
fell over the wall. 
</P>
<P>
	``I started to fall headfirst, and I just grabbed the wall and  
landed on my knee,'' said Van Arkel, an overnight news producer for 
an Omaha radio station. 
</P>
<P>
	Van Arkel said he has been coming to the College World Series  
for years, but never with such an eventful day. 
</P>
<P>
	``I was afraid they'd kick me out,'' he said. ``But they let me  
back in.'' 
</P>
<P>
	One bystander called the episode ``the most exciting part'' of  
the nearly four-hour game. 
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	 *BIG RED MACHINE:* There's only one thing that could push aside  
coverage of the College World Series in Omaha: Nebraska Cornhuskers 
football. 
</P>
<P>
	In Friday's sports section of the Omaha World-Herald, the  
College World Series and Stanley Cup finals competed with news 
about the recovery of injured Nebraska quarterback Bobby Newcombe. 
</P>
<P>
	Newcombe missed most of last season with a torn knee ligament  
and had surgery in December. He rejoined his teammates this week 
during informal offseason workouts and continues to do 
rehabilitation work. 
</P>
<P>
	Newcombe wore no pads and didn't even participate in every  
exercise. But it was a start -- and it was section-front news in 
football-crazed Nebraska. 
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	 *PLAYING TAG:* Oklahoma State had a painful first day -- in more  
ways than one. 
</P>
<P>
	Josh Holliday was hit twice by pitches in the Cowboys' 11-2 loss  
to Alabama. That tied a College World Series record and made 
Holliday the 18th player in CWS history to be hit twice in a game. 
</P>
<P>
	Pinch-hitter Chris Becerra also was hit by a pitch, bringing  
Oklahoma State's season total to 96. The previous school record was 
84 in 1995. 
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	 *EVERYTHING'S POLITICAL:* Rep. Lee Terry, R-Neb., used the start  
of the College World Series to increase his political profile, 
holding a fund-raiser at the adjacent Henry Doorly Zoo. 
</P>
<P>
	The event was expected to raise about $100,000 for the National  
Republican Congressional Committee, committee spokeswoman Jill 
Schroeder said. 
</P>
<P>
	Seven Republican congressmen were scheduled to attend a  
reception and Friday's games, including Rep. John Thune of South 
Dakota, Nebraska Reps. Doug Bereuter and Bill Barrett and Rep. 
Frank Lucas of Oklahoma -- whose Oklahoma State Cowboys played 
Alabama in the series opener. 
</P>
<P>
	Schroeder said it is not uncommon for politicians to  
``piggyback'' such fund-raising events onto a sports event like the 
College World Series or the Super Bowl. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's fun,'' she said. ``And it's not the same old rubber  
chicken dinner.'' 
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	 *ROLL TIDE:* Alabama shortstop Andy Phillips extended his  
hitting streak to 34 games Friday, breaking a tie with Louisiana 
State's Todd Walker for the Southeastern Conference record. 
</P>
<P>
	Phillips singled to left in the third inning against Oklahoma  
State. He then stole second base, but was stranded there. 
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	 *STAMP OF APPROVAL:* The U.S. Postal Service has added its 33  
cents to the College World Series. 
</P>
<P>
	The post office opened a temporary branch just outside  
Rosenblatt Stadium that will be open during the series. 
</P>
<P>
	The post office is across the street from the community of  
recreational vehicles known as ``Dingerville.'' The Postal Service 
said customers could buy special pictorial stamps, envelopes, 
regular stamps and other items. 
  	   	
</P>
