<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 6 p.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	 *Pentagon: No Rush on Peacekeepers    	
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- NATO said today a ``substantial'' peacekeeping  
force would be in place in Kosovo by tomorrow afternoon, but 
officials in Europe and at the Pentagon were vague on the details. 
There should be no rush to put troops in danger, the Pentagon said. 
American, British and other troops assigned to secure the province 
as Serb troops depart milled around the Kosovo border, ready to 
move when they get the word. An elite unit of British paratroopers 
and Gurkha riflemen was to go first. 

</P>
<P>
	Clinton Warns of Kosovo Dangers  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- President Clinton said today Americans must be  
prepared for possible casualties as the difficult work of 
peacekeeping begins in Kosovo. At Whiteman Air Force Base in 
Missouri, Clinton thanked B-2 pilots who flew 30-hour roundtrips to 
the Balkans. ``Thanks to you, the century is ending not with 
helpless indignation over such unspeakable cruelty, but with its 
opposite -- a ringing affirmation by free people of human dignity,'' 
Clinton said. 

</P>
<P>
	Bush Launches Presidential Bid  
</P>
<P>
	CHICAGO (AP) -- Texas Gov. George W. Bush today launched his  
campaign for the Republican presidential nomination with two 
Midwest fund-raisers. ``See you in Iowa,'' he said after a private 
$1,000-a-plate luncheon at a Chicago hotel. Tomorrow, Bush visits 
Iowa, site of the nation's first caucuses. On Monday, he goes to 
New Hampshire, site of the first primary. 

</P>
<P>
	Senators Disclose Their Assets  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- According to financial disclosure forms  
released today, many senators and their spouses are worth millions, 
a select few many times that. Among the richest in 1998 were John 
D. Rockefeller IV, D-W.Va.; Herb Kohl, D-Wis.; Edward M. Kennedy, 
D-Mass.; Frank Lautenberg, D-N.J., and freshman Peter Fitzgerald, 
R-Ill. The rank-and-file salary is $136,700, with floor leaders 
earning $151,800. 

</P>
<P>
	Wholesale Inflation Eases  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Inflation at the wholesale level tapered off  
in May after rising sharply the month before. The Producer Price 
Index, which measures inflation pressures before they reach the 
consumer, rose just 0.2 percent last month. A separate report by 
the Commerce Department said retail sales rose by a hefty 1 percent 
last month, led by a sharp 2.5 percent increase in auto purchases. 

</P>
<P>
	Vatican, Lutherans End Dispute  
</P>
<P>
	GENEVA (AP) -- The Roman Catholic and Lutheran churches have  
ended a nearly 5-century-old dispute over how people achieve 
salvation, officials announced today. The accord represents ``a 
decisive step forward in the process of reconciliation,'' said Rev. 
Ismael Noko, general secretary of the Lutheran World Federation. 
The two sides crafted a compromise on ``justification,'' or how 
humankind achieves salvation. For the Lutherans, salvation depends 
on the grace of God, while Catholics maintain that good works are 
also involved. The declaration states that divine forgiveness comes 
``solely by God's grace'' and that good works flow from that. 

</P>
<P>
	Hackers Attack Senate Web Site  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Computer hackers attacked the U.S. Senate's  
main Web site today, the second such assault on the high-profile 
Internet page in just over two weeks. The hackers defaced the Web 
page, www.senate.gov, but left its overall look similar to how it 
normally appears. The FBI already was investigating a May 27 attack 
on the Web site. 

</P>
<P>
	Computer Crash Halts eBay  
</P>
<P>
	SAN JOSE, Calif. (AP) -- A computer crash forced the online  
auction house eBay to suspend all bidding, frustrating millions of 
customers of one of the hottest businesses on both the Internet and 
Wall Street. The halt came after eBay tried to launch a revamped 
version of its Web site. The computer server went down last night, 
and eBay was still trying to reconstruct the data to get it running 
again this afternoon. 

</P>
<P>
	Dow Ends Down 130.76  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Stocks fell sharply today after a tame inflation  
report failed to temper worry that the Federal Reserve will hike 
interest rates. The Dow industrials ended down 130.76 at 10,490.51. 
On the NYSE, losers led gainers 1,712-1,304. The Nasdaq fell 37.06 
points to 2,447.56. 

</P>
<P>
	Jury: SI Must Pay Boxer $10.7 Mil.  
</P>
<P>
	NASHVILLE, Tenn. (AP) -- Time Inc. must pay ex-heavyweight boxer  
Randall ``Tex'' Cobb $10.7 million for a 1993 Sports Illustrated 
article saying he fixed a fight and shared cocaine with the loser, 
a federal jury decided. Jurors awarded Cobb $2.2 million in 
punitive damages today to go with $8.5 million that they awarded 
Wednesday in compensatory damages. 

</P>
<P>
	AP NewsBrief by HOWARD SINER  
  	   	
</P>
