<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Wholesale Inflation Eases in May </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Inflation at the wholesale level tapered off  
in May after rising sharply the month before. Still-confident 
Americans, meanwhile, kept buying everything from clothes to cars. 
</P>
<P>
	The Producer Price Index, which measures inflation pressures  
before they reach the consumer, rose just 0.2 percent last month, 
reflecting a drop in gasoline prices, which posted a record 
increase the month before, the Labor Department said Friday. 
Wholesale prices in April had gone up 0.5 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	A separate report by the Commerce Department said retail sales  
rose by a hefty 1 percent last month, led by a sharp 2.5 percent 
increase in auto purchases. Retail sales have climbed or held 
steady for 10 months running and were 7.8 percent higher than May 
of last year. 
</P>
<P>
	``The American consumer appears to have an insatiable appetite,'  
said Oscar Gonzalez, an economist with John Hancock. 
</P>
<P>
	The tame wholesale inflation, while good news, didn't offset  
economists' belief that the Fed may be concerned that strong retail 
sales figure is a sign that the nation's economy, powered by 
consumer spending, is growing too quickly and could touch off 
inflation. 
</P>
<P>
	Many economists said they were looking for the Fed to start  
raising interest rates at its next meeting, June 29-30. 
</P>
<P>
	``There's lots of momentum in retail sales,'' said economist Tim  
O'Neill with Harris Bank and the Bank of Montreal. ``If you are 
worried about the inflation speedometer, then you'll need to slow 
down consumer gas, which fuels the economic engine, and that would 
happen by the Fed raising interest rates.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Cynthia Latta, an economist with DRI/McGraw Hill, said other  
factors the Fed may use to justify a rate increase were reports 
this week that struggling overseas economies, including Japan's, 
may be gaining strength, which could push up global price 
pressures. 
</P>
<P>
	``The Fed is concerned, I think, that the U.S. economy is so  
strong and that with other economies perhaps starting to turn the 
corner and recover, there will be an increase in global demand,'' 
Latta said. 
</P>
<P>
	The moderation in wholesale prices in May reflected a big drop  
in energy prices. Gasoline prices at the wholesale level, which had 
risen by a record 29.1 percent in April, dropped 2.7 percent last 
month. 
</P>
<P>
	That moderation is expected to show up in retail prices. Many  
analysts are forecasting an increase of around 0.2 percent in the 
May Consumer Price Index, which will be released next Wednesday, 
down from a nine-year high of 0.7 percent in April. 
</P>
<P>
	After the CPI increase was reported last month, the Fed  
announced that it was leaning toward raising interest rates to keep 
inflation from getting out of control. 
</P>
<P>
	Financial markets remained on alert for a Fed rate increase. The  
Dow Jones industrial average closed at 10,490.51, down 130.76 
points, and the yield on Treasury's benchmark 30-year bond remained 
above the 6 percent level, a threshhold indicating nervousness 
about the central bank's intentions. 
</P>
<P>
	For May, the 2.7 percent drop in gasoline prices, the biggest  
decline since last December, offset increases in home heating oil 
and natural gas, leaving overall energy costs unchanged for the 
month following a 5.1 percent surge in April. 
</P>
<P>
	Motorists are already starting to see the price declines at the  
wholesale level at the pump. Surveys show that gasoline pump 
prices, after having risen for more than two months, have started 
to edge down slightly. 
</P>
<P>
	Food prices last month rose 0.5 percent after a big 0.9 percent  
drop in April. The May increase included a big jump in pork prices. 
Fruit prices were also up sharply, with big gains for grapefruit, 
lemons and pears. 
</P>
<P>
	However, vegetable prices fell last month as the price of  
cauliflower, squash and lettuce all posted big declines. 
</P>
<P>
	Excluding the volatile food and energy sectors, prices at the  
wholesale level rose a tiny 0.1 percent, matching the small 
increase in April. So far this year, the so-called core rate of 
inflation at the wholesale level has been flat, an even better 
performance than a 1.9 percent rate of increase in the first five 
months of 1998. 

  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
