<HEADLINE> NBC, AT&AMP;T To Bring HDTV to Cable </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- AT&AMP;T will soon be providing NBC programs in  
high-definition television through its cable TV lines. 
</P>
<P>
	An eight-year deal announced Thursday between AT&AMP;T Broadband &AMP;  
Internet Services and NBC is one of the first HDTV partnerships 
between a cable company and a broadcaster. 
</P>
<P>
	The agreement also commits AT&AMP;T Broadband &AMP; Internet to carrying  
NBC's cable services MSNBC and CNBC, and the network's Olympics 
programming, according to a statement released by the companies. 
</P>
<P>
	Cable operators previously had said they did not have enough  
capacity to carry HDTV programming because it eats up too much 
space on cable TV systems. 
</P>
<P>
	``This new agreement, which will bring great value and benefit  
to our customers well into the next decade, demonstrates that the 
cable industry and broadcasters can amicably reach agreement on 
important matters,'' Leo J. Hindrey Jr., president and CEO of AT&AMP;T 
Broadband and Internet, said in a statement. 
</P>
<P>
	The two companies said they will not only work to provide  
digital programming for new high-definition television sets, but 
also for traditional TVs through set-top boxes that will be 
compatible with high-definition signals. 
</P>
<P>
	Federal regulators now require stations in the 10 largest U.S.  
cities to send digital signals. This fall, another 20 cities will 
face that requirement. 
</P>
<P>
	The few television shows that are currently shot in digital  
format, including ``The Tonight Show With Jay Leno,'' are still 
converted to analog for most viewers. 
</P>
<P>
	AT&AMP;T Broadband &AMP; Internet, formerly known as Tele-Communications  
Inc. prior to a merger with New York-based AT&AMP;T, has more than 10 
million customers nationwide. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
