<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Suspected Nazi Leaves U.S. </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- A retiree identified by the United States as a  
Nazi guard at slave labor camps in Poland has left the country and 
renounced his U.S. citizenship, authorities say. 
</P>
<P>
	Dmytro Sawchuk, 74, had been charged in U.S. District Court in  
New York City with failing to tell U.S. officials of his alleged 
Nazi past when he applied for a visa to enter the country in 1951. 
</P>
<P>
	The civil complaint sought to revoke his citizenship.  
</P>
<P>
	U.S. Attorney Mary Jo White said the case became moot when, on  
March 23, Sawchuk renounced his citizenship and surrendered his 
U.S. passport at the U.S. consulate in Frankfurt, Germany. 
</P>
<P>
	Sawchuk allegedly guarded Nazi slave-labor camps from 1943 to  
1945 and participated in the liquidation of a Jewish ghetto in 
Nazi-occupied Poland. He told authorities he spent the war years as 
a farm worker in his native Poland, and also worked at a German 
sawmill. 
</P>
<P>
	Sawchuk, a retired tailor, had lived with his wife and two sons  
in Glen Spey, a small Catskills town about 65 miles northwest of 
New York. A telephone call to Sawchuk's lawyer for comment was not 
returned Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	The U.S. government has placed Sawchuk's name on its ``watch  
list,'' which bars him from returning to the United States, 
prosecutors said. 
</P>
<P>
	Eli Rosenbaum, director of the Office of Special Investigations  
in the Justice Department's Criminal Division, said the action 
against Sawchuk was ``one more step in the government's ongoing 
efforts to identify and take legal action against former 
participants in Nazi persecution residing in this country.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990611.0312 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-11 14:10:18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> AP Names Omaha News Editor </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	OMAHA, Neb. (AP) -- Barry J. Bedlan, a newsman in the Omaha  
bureau of The Associated Press, has been promoted to news editor 
for Nebraska. 
</P>
<P>
	The appointment was announced Friday by Chief of Bureau Paul  
Simon. 
</P>
<P>
	Bedlan, 27, joined the AP in Omaha in 1995. He previously worked  
for the Star-Herald in Scottsbluff, Neb. 
</P>
<P>
	Bedlan, a graduate of Creighton University, succeeds Maryann  
Mrowca, who has been named assistant chief of bureau in Atlanta. 
  	   	
</P>
